@NODE "Mail.4" "WritePixelArray8()"
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 10:22:49 +0000
From: James Marshall <homegrown@eclipse.co.uk>
Subject: WritePixelArray8()

Hi everyone (especially Paul),
  well, efforts to convert my game to graphics card compatibility
despite not owning a graphics card are continuing. Here's my latest
question:
As Paul Burkey suggested, I converted my shape objects to chunky format
and now have them stored in FAST RAM in my game. I copy these to a
special chunky screen buffer to create the display, then use
WritePixelArray8() to render this to my OS window. But with my 030 50Mhz
system, without a graphics card, this is too slow (you can actually see
the pixels being written, going down the screen, as opposed to, say,
BitmapToWindow, where you can't really see the process, apart from some
flickering). So, would this effect dissappear if I was actually using a
graphics card? Is there a minimum processor speed I would need to
achieve reasonable results? I'm not using double buffering, at the
moment, but I think even if I were, my game would still be too slow the
way things are now. Thanks in advance for any help,
    James

--
Homegrown Software - Independent Amiga Games Developers
Web - http://www.eclipse.co.uk/homegrown
email - homegrown@eclipse.co.uk




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.5" "Re: WritePixelArray8()"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 17:13:51 +0100
Subject: Re: WritePixelArray8()

Hi James,

> and now have them stored in FAST RAM in my game. I copy these to a
> special chunky screen buffer to create the display, then use
> WritePixelArray8() to render this to my OS window. But with my 030 50Mhz
> system, without a graphics card, this is too slow (you can actually see
> the pixels being written, going down the screen, as opposed to, say,
> BitmapToWindow, where you can't really see the process, apart from some
> flickering). So, would this effect dissappear if I was actually using a
> graphics card? Is there a minimum processor speed I would need to
> achieve reasonable results?

WritePixelArray8 on a GFX card would copy the data very quickly
compared to WPA8 on an AGA setup. AGA needs c2p and the WPA8 c2p
is supposed to be prety slow.

You could try util/boot/NewWPA8.lha on aminet to patch AmigaOS to
use one of the cool new c2p routines which should make it run
faster on AGA but it's still going to be a lot slower than it
would on a GFX card. Most CGFX systems have a fast Zorro3 bus
which is much faster than AGA and theres no c2p involved.  

> I'm not using double buffering, at the
> moment, but I think even if I were, my game would still be too slow the
> way things are now.

You can almost forget double buffer on a gfx card. When you dump
your WritePixelArray8 data to th gfx card it'll be copied so
fast and so clean (no planar flicker) that double buffering is
no longer needed for visual purposes. Using double/tripple buffers
for speed is another issue. 

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk




