@NODE "Mail.11" "Re: WritePixelArray8"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Wed, 04 Mar 1998 20:43:17 +0100
Subject: Re: WritePixelArray8

Hi James,

>   can someone tell me the parameters for WritePixelArray8()? The Blitz
> on-line help tells me the parameter names, but I don`t know exactly what
> they mean. In particular there are two parameters called rp and temprp,
> not sure what these should be.

If you need detailed info then you're better off "aquiring" the
AmigaOS Autodocs. They are very important if you want to use
the graphics.library and other OS libraries. I remember a site
mentioned on the blitz-list that had them freely available although
it's not totaly legal (not at all). The file you need for this
function is the graphics.library doc which I have sitting on
my HD. hint. hint. 

Anyway, a quick help on this function:-

The rp which is used for almost every graphics.library function
is RastPort. So for rp you will use RastPort(window#) which is
the window you are rendering to.

temprp is somthing I never use. I always set it to 0. If you want
the explanation then this is what the autodoc says:

temporary rastport (copy of rp with Layer set == NULL,
temporary memory allocated for
temprp->BitMap with Rows set == 1,
temprp->BytesPerRow == (((width+15)>>4)<<1),
and temporary memory allocated for
temprp->BitMap->Planes[])
 
> Also startx, starty, stopx and stopy...
> do these refer to the area on the screen that the pixels should be
> written to (startx, starty= top left, stopx, stopy=bottom right)?


Yes, it's basicly the area where the pixels will go. It's also
the only way the function will know how many pixels to write.

>   On a related note, does anyone have update CPUBlit code for blitting a
> shape (in planar form) to a chunky section of mem (ready for
> WritePixelArray8).

When you mention CPUBlit then I imagine you want to do this
in realtime. If that is the case then you're better off using
something like WBlit or WindowToBitmap. If you want to convert
planar shapes to chunky shapes then you only have to use
a combination of ShapesBitmap and Point to read the pixels
into an array (or reserved memory).

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

