@NODE "Mail.64" "Re: Sys load"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 15 Mar 1998 19:17:43 -0600
Subject: Re: Sys load

Hi Dave,

On 15-Mar-98, Dave wrote:
>Hi

>  If I was writing a fast OS game , is it possible to find out
>  how much is already running on the system and if there is too
>  much for the game to run at full speed, tell the user?

You could make up some sort of a test loop that would run for a second or two,
and use the timer commands to see how many ticks it takes to complete.  Then
compare this to the amount it takes to run your game at full speed, and let
the user know if there is a problem.

For example, let's say that this test loop must execute in less than 80 ticks
to run at full speed.  (You will need to determine this time by your own
experiments - just keep adding tasks to your system until you can get the game
to slow down)  So, you run the test and find it completes in 70 ticks - the
game should run fine.  You might want to warn them that it is close to the
limit, and starting other tasks could affect it.  If the test shows 40 ticks,
you have plenty of time, no need to worry.  If it is over 80, the game will be
slowed.

-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
