@NODE "Mail.72" "Re: Sorting files"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Sun, 15 Mar 1998 21:55:59 +0100
Subject: Re: Sorting files


 Hiya,

I have included a rip from the ElmoreSysLib doc'sm which  shows you
how to do this in an easy way. You  need  to have the  ElmoreSysLib
installed on your system, for it to work. Some people has  had some
problem with these commands, but it works fine on my system, infact
I used it today to get the file names in a drawer. I'm  sure you'll
figure out how to sort the  dir's and  file's  usung  the  EntryDIR
command, it's not hard at all.

 ByE!

*********************
* DIRECTORY EXAMPLE *
*********************

This example will list the entries in RAM: in a format very similar
to the AmigaDOS "LIST" command.  Note  that you  need to "ChDir" to
a directory in order to read it from the first entry again.


ChDir "RAM:"

While MoreEntries
  Print LSet$(EntryName$,30)
  If EntryDIR then Print "Dir   " Else Print LSet$(Str$(EntrySize),6)
  Print EntryBits$," ",Date$(EntryDate)," "
  Print EntryHour,":",Right$("0"+Str$(EntryMins),2),":"
  NPrint Right$("0"+Str$(EntrySecs),2)
Wend

MouseWait
End






@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.73" "Re: Sorting files"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 19:48:48 -0600
Subject: Re: Sorting files

Hi,

On 16-Mar-98, Oliver Marks wrote:
>Hi,

>I have now got my program loading in files in a directory the problem
>i am having now is storing them in an array i was wondering if it is
>possible to change the size of an array or get rid of it because i
>want to store the filenames in an array the only problem is if there
>is to many files to store in the array. 
>Does creating an array take up memory because if you had to create a
>large array surly it would take up a large amount of memory or does
>the memory not get used until something is stored in the array..

I believe that a string array really contains only pointers to each string.
The strings themselves would use no memory unless there was something stored
in them.  So if you clear out your array when you are done with it, it will
not use much memory.

Once an array is Dim'd, you can't change the size.


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



