@NODE "Mail.79" "Re: Some questions.."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 05 Mar 1998 14:58:51 -0600
Subject: Re: Some questions..

Hi,

On 05-Mar-98, Tommi Nieminen wrote:


>>> 2.How can i select the font that is used in GT text etc. gadgets?
>>
>>Use the LoadFont command at the top of your program. Syntax is:
>>
>>   LoadFont fontnumber,fontname,ysize[,style]
>>
>>ie.
>>   LoadFont 0,"personal.font",8
>>
>>
>I do use the loadfont command as you say but still the font used in the 
>buttons is the system font, i.e XEN/11 .
>So where could the problem be?

You must load the font BEFORE you make your GT gadget list(s).  The
GTgadgetlist will always use the last font that was loaded before you make it.
 If you have more than one font loaded, put:

Use Intuifont 0 (or whichever one you want on the gadgets)

just before making the GTlist.

Once the GTlist is made, the gadget font is locked in and it doesn't matter
what fonts you load later. 

                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.80" "Re: Some questions.."
          Fri, 6 Mar 1998 17:27:16 +0000
          6 Mar 98 17:26:50 +0000
From: "S.J.CROY" <ap6013@qmw.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 6 Mar 1998 17:26:23 +0000
Subject: Re: Some questions..

Tommi Nieminen wrote:

> Hi!
Hello

>  3.And also i wrote couple weeks ago about creating a rotating starfield 
> effect to my game, has anybody anything that i could use as i couldnt 
> get anything working.

Sorry if Im not much help with the other questions but this might get 
you started with the starfield.

Try to imagine a circle, but only one pixel can be displayed.  From 
the centre, a right angled triangle can be drawn.   In a right angled 
triangle x is cos(angle) and y is sin(angle).  By multiplying these 
by a constant you can get a different size of a circle

Here`s a short proggy:  (use joystick 1 to rotate it)

Dim s(360),c(360)

For loop=0 to 360: 
s(loop)=sin(loop*pi/180):c(loop)=cos(loop*pi/180):next
<= This converts radians into degrees, which are easier to work with

CentreX=160:CenterY=128
Size=100
angle=0

repeat
vwait
Plot CentreX+Size*c(angle),CentreY+Size*s(angle),1

angle=qwrap(angle+joyx(1),0,360)

until joyb(0)

end

Ok, this justs plots one pixel but if you set up a loop of some sort, 
change the variable Size, you can have rotating stars at different 
positions.

Sorry if this is just complete nonsense to you, but email us directly 
and I will send you a working example.

Regards
Steven 


