>-Is harddisk installable
>-Shows the graphic, sound, multitasking and other capabilities
>-Show how the standard workbench works
>-Shows some game screenshots
>-Shows video capabilities
>-Has all texts in seperate files so local distributors/dealers can translate
>it
>-Is freely downloadable from Aminet or the Amiga website

>Of course, it could also say "This is what you can do with Blitz!" or
>something alike.

>It would be a great development push for Blitz if the users of the Blitz
>list could offer it as gift to Amiga International, I think. And of course
>it would be a great gift to the Amiga itself...

>Don't let me be misunderstood, of course we are also looking for a cheap
>demo to run in our store, I will be the last one to deny that. But we also
>love the Amiga and want it to be promoted in as many ways as possible. And a
>"shop-demo" is something that is needed very much...

>What do you think?

>Best regards,
>Ron.

Yes, I think this is a worthwhile project!

I would be glad to act as the "Co-ordinator" for this project.
I already have code that could do this:

* Open an "invisible" workbench window, and fade in a message here
(this could be the "powered by Amiga" logo, perhaps with a message
such as "Have it YOUR way", or something similar)
* Load a picture to an un unseen custom screen
* Pop this to the front of the display
* After some seconds, put a window on this to show some information
* Fade this out back to the workbench
* repeat this for any number of pictures.
* also play a selection of mods with this - each picture could even have it's
own mod.

Of course, this is nothing more than a slide show really, but it would give
you something almost immediately to start with, and these pictures could show
what I consider the best part of the Amiga concept - it's complete user
configurability.
These pics would be screenshots of people's workbenches, grabs of game
screens, and apps, and would really catch the viewer's eye.  Every Windows
computer I have ever seen has EXACTLY THE SAME desktop, but I've never seen
two workbenches that looked the same. Some are stunning, some very
business-like, some comical, some plain - each exactly suited to it's own
user.

The windows would say "256 colour workbench" "Curt Esser", etc., or "My
wonderful Game", "By someone", "Available from...", etc.

Also we could include one "picture" with information on all who contributed to
the demo and what they did.  Maybe using the Blitz logo as a background.

The other parts could be done as "Modules" by other interested coders, and
could be added to the program as they are completed.

And of course, all text would be loaded from separate text files, to provide
for easy translation.

The whole thing would instantly exit at the touch of a mousebutton
(if desired) so the salesperson could show the computer to interested parties.

What do you guys think about this?



-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.89" "Re: Sell the Amiga"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 21 Mar 1998 09:37:55 -0600
Subject: Re: Sell the Amiga

Hi again,

On 21-Mar-98, Dave wrote:

>  Great idea if like that guy said there are no others available.
>  I think it could be made more than a slide show though , I think it
>  would be good to have the actual game running in a predefined way so
>  the person watching could see what the action was really like.
>  for eg. you could have an action sequence of a fight from a beat-em-up
>  very short but fast and effective.
>  I think the slide show would good as well because there are a lot of 
>  great gfx picture that have been created on the amiga.
>  
>  I know two guys from Vortex who make really amazing Mods.

Yes, maybe I didn't explain too well.  I didn't mean that it would be simply a
slide-show.  Only that this is the part that I am able to contribute.

And also in addition to the slide show, it would act as the master control for
the rest of the modules.

So it would work like this:

The main program runs through a list of "things to do"

Maybe it shows 3 or 4 pictures of the slide show, now it comes to your game
demo.
Here, instead of showing another picture, it now runs the code you have
supplied to do the demo of the game.  Maybe this is an animation, or a bit of
the actual game set to run itself, or whatever.

Each person would supply their own code, pics, anims, or whatever as a self
contained mini-program module, coded in whatever way they wish.

I would supply the master control program, set up to operate on the slide-show
principle.

This is what I meant by the "Modules"

This way, everyone could contribute whatever they like, whether it is nothing
more than a WB screenshot, or a complete game demo as you have described, or
anything else...

The only restriction would be that the whole module would have to exit
immediately if the mouse button was clicked (or whatever signal we decide on),
and place a message to signal the master program that it is time to quit. 
(This could be a small file sent to the ram disk)
 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
