@NODE "Mail.105" "Score Display"
From: Jake Frederick <gonzo@acadia.net>
Date: Sun, 29 Jan 1978 04:28:45 +0500
Subject: Score Display

How can I implement a separate bitmap that uses 20 lines at the top of the
screen into the following code? What I want is a a score display above the
playfield. Is there a better way of doing it, instead of opening a whole new
bitmap? I am using a 640x200 screen that scrolls over a 1280x200 bitmap. The
code included is just the parts that handle the bitmap. There may be some
unrelated statments, I just wanted to give as much background as I could
without including the whole program. Any help would be greatly appreciated.

   BitMap 0,1280,180,8
   LoadbitMap 0,"pic",0
   CopyBitMap 0,1
   InitCopList 0,64,180,$13918,8,256,0
   Buffer 0,55000
   Buffer 0,55000

   BLITZ

   CreateDisplay 0
   DisplayPalette 0,0
   VWait
   DisplayBitMap 0,akbit,x,y
   akbit=1-akbit
   Use BitMap akbit
   Unbuffer akbit
-- 
                                -iF-
-tHE dOORS oF pERCEPTION wERE cLEANSED eVERYTHING wOULD aPPEAR aS iT iS-
                             -iNFINITE-



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.106" "Re: Score Display"
	(envelope-from tucks@pavilion.co.uk)
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 20:58:19 +0000
From: Liz Tucker <tucks@pavilion.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Score Display

Jake Frederick wrote:
> 
> How can I implement a separate bitmap that uses 20 lines at the top of the
> screen into the following code? What I want is a a score display above the
> playfield. Is there a better way of doing it, instead of opening a whole new
> bitmap? I am using a 640x200 screen that scrolls over a 1280x200 bitmap. The
> code included is just the parts that handle the bitmap. There may be some
> unrelated statments, I just wanted to give as much background as I could
> without including the whole program. Any help would be greatly appreciated.

The easiest way would be to create a separate copperlist for the top 20 lines
of the display and place the score display on there. Then it won`t be corrupted
by your scrolling bitmap as it moves around because it is displayed in a 
separate copperlist.

See you,

Liz.   

