@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.111" "Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?"
Subject: Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 16:46:57 +0000 (GMT)
From: "Adam Lounds" <adaml@tcp.net.uk>

> 
> On 18 Mar 98 at 14:56, Paul Burkey spewed forth:
> 
> > An interesting idea would be to copy C as much as possible
> > while keeping things in a comfortable Blitz-like environment.
> > The ability to import Blitz code or Export C code would
> > be interesting with steps to keep compatability between
> > the two languages whenever possible. Another 'C' variant is
> > not interesting and a Blitz 'rip off' is pointless. Something
> > inbetween is necessary.
> 
>  I think that blitz needs to be a bit more structured as far as 
> variables go: liek C, having to declare variables at the start of 
> functions etc, before they are used. This would make the language 
> easier to understand, and the compiler would maybe be a bit easier to 
> produce, if all declarations are grouped together.

But the beauty of blitz is its accessibility to newbies.

If you go and tell them they have to define all their variables
at the start, it'll put them off. I for one make up new vars as and 
when they are needed - obviously I define them all at the top
later, but for the nuts and bolts coding, it's much easier
to have the flexibility available.

Think of perl - what's the point in defining everything first, as long
as it's easy to understand?

-- 
