@NODE "Mail.115" "Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?"
From: James L Boyd <jamesboyd@velvety.demon.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 23:59:39 +0000
Subject: Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?

On 18-Mar-98, Steve Matty 01705 260639 churned out *this* drivel:

> The Ultimate Blitz CD which is now in the shops had 0
> involvement with Acid Software - they were paid a royalty
> for each copy sold. NOTE: The *entire* Blitz Support Suite
> was put on this CD, WITHOUT our knowledge or consent.
> We have received 0, zilch, nothing, from the 500 or so
> sales of this CD (and hence, the 500 lost sales of BSS).

Wow,and we all thought piracy was down to a few lousy "hackers".
Things are bad if a major (in Amiga terms ;) company is ripping
off other people's stuff to sell.

> time I used to have (when I was at uni..). I still
> want to work on a future Blitz-alike language.

This is what interested me about this mail - "blitz-alike"...
I think that's what needs to be done,considering the reluctance
Guildhall have (and their apparently "little-bit-underhand" workings),
and the supposed mess of the blitz source.

There are plenty of people on this list with the ability to help
develop a new Blitz style language,as far as I can tell (OK,I'm not
one of them ;)

> Q. What about BlitzPPC
> A. We definately want to a Blitz-alike language
> which produces PPC code. It will still use
> a library system similar (but without the inherent
> drawbacks) to the current Blitz. Libraries

There's that blitz-alike stuff again - I like it!

I think giving Blitz PPC abilities would make it even more of
a botch-job than it already is...a new start could have this and
RTG,RTA etc all planned at the very start.And with those who are
"in the know" as far as future Amiga developments go helping out,
it could be pretty future-proof.

> will consist of function and data sections so
> that only code called by your program is
> included in the executable.

Yaaayy!

> Other
> details have to be decided - this is where
> your input comes in.

I think it's very important that the new language (?) is pretty
easy for beginners,and for those of us who know nothing (or very little)
about C,E,and all those kind of things.Just code in C if you want that
kind of stuff :)

There's nothing wrong in making a language easy to use!

But I think it's important to start again,instead of patching the
current Blitz all over the place - it'll fall apart eventually!

Remember,Blitz /was/ written when OS-friendliness,decent specs,RTG,etc
weren't considered quite so important.Oh,and like somebody said,even if
it is a variation on BASIC,don't call it BASIC!

> I hope this answers the most important
> questions. I'd like to open up the
> whole development of a future Blitz-alike
> to you people - a concerted, co-operative
> effort could reap huge rewards.

I think this is the best idea so far.Abandon the idea of
furthering the actual Blitz "product",and create a new one
from scratch :)

Definitely the way to go.

Still do all this committee stuff,and web-site,it would all
be a useful part of it...

See ya,
-- 
James L Boyd

jamesboyd@velvety.demon.co.uk




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.116" "Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
    Blitz-list <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 14:56:18 +0100
Subject: Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?

Hi Steve,

I mailed this to the blitz-list as well as to you Steve just in case
you're unsubscribed from the list. Recieving two copies of the same
message pisses me off so I apologise for it :) Just let us know
you're actually subscribed.

> The Ultimate Blitz CD which is now in the shops had 0
> involvement with Acid Software - they were paid a royalty
> for each copy sold. NOTE: The *entire* Blitz Support Suite
> was put on this CD, WITHOUT our knowledge or consent.

I hope there are some routes to follow that will allow you to
chase up your hard erned royalties you so rightly deserve!!
Who compiled the CD? Did Guildhall know about the inclusion
of BSS or was it the handy work of the CD publishers?

> Q. How will RWE get ownership?
> A. Not sure. Guildhall seemed unwilling to sell the
> rights to Blitz Basic (which they bought from Acid)
> to us. Any version of 'Blitz' will be completely
> unofficial, and therefore is unlikely to be called
> Blitz (or published via Guildhall, for reasons above)

I'm not optimistic about any kind of official 'take over' of
Blitz. We all agree that Blitz is a unique and wonderfull
language so giving up the rights or handing over some of the
development would cause problems if ever there was a time
that the Amiga grew into a large commercial platform again
or a PC/Mac version became necessary.

> I am still keen, but don't have anywhere NEAR the amount of
> spare time I used to have (when I was at uni..). I still
> want to work on a future Blitz-alike language.

Ahaa. This sounds very interesting. I know someone has already
mentioned that it could be an idea to create PPCBlitz from
scratch and I thought it was  viable iea at the time no matter
how ambitious it sounds. Talking about the members of this
list... do we have enough knowlege to enable us to create
this new language? I certainly have many ideas about this type
of project. Without going into a long list of 'fantasy league'
ideas I think a Blitz type language with a huge amount of
discussion and planning could be an educational experience
in itself. I would even consider setting up a mailing-list
especially for the discussion of this project. I'm certainly not
suggesting we all dump Blitz and make our own language but the
discussion should be aimed towards taking the Blitz language
further even if it must be via the most ambitious avenues.

> A. We definately want to a Blitz-alike language
> which produces PPC code. It will still use
> a library system similar (but without the inherent
> drawbacks) to the current Blitz. Libraries
> will consist of function and data sections so
> that only code called by your program is
> included in the executable.

I always feel that a naive approach to complicated issues can
often bring new angles and solutions to problems. That is
why I think a gathering up of mixed views and ideas from people
with mixed experiences would create a good environment for the
planning of a new/improoved language.

Time for a few open questions/ideas...

Talking seriously and forgetting about the planning stages
for the moment, How long would it take to create a simple
compiler that could handle the basics like variables and
some basic input/output via AmigaOS.

An important approach to this projct would be to keep the
possibility of multiplatform, multi cpu and a retargetable
approach from the very start.

An interesting idea would be to copy C as much as possible
while keeping things in a comfortable Blitz-like environment.
The ability to import Blitz code or Export C code would
be interesting with steps to keep compatability between
the two languages whenever possible. Another 'C' variant is
not interesting and a Blitz 'rip off' is pointless. Something
inbetween is necessary.

Having said all this, I still think the further development
of Blitz itself is just as good an option an probably the
most viable if that is ever an option.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

