@NODE "Mail.118" "RWE and Blitz - do we own it?"
Disclose-Recipients: prohibited
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 10:38:18 +0000 (GMT)
From: Steve Matty 01705 260639 <steven.matty@gecm.com>
Subject: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?
Autoforwarded: false
Importance: low
Sensitivity: Personal
Ua-Content-Id: 11C392E61100
X400-Mts-Identifier: [;4618381118031998/A05263/WVTEAM]
Hop-Count: 2

Hi,

This is a message detailing our relationship with Acid, Guildhall
and Blitz Basic. I think I'll do it in a Q & A style....


Q. Where are Acid Software?
A. Simon Armstrong has long since left the Amiga market. The
last I heard he was doing some work for Codemasters. The
label 'Acid Software' is now owned by Guildhall Leisure.
The Ultimate Blitz CD which is now in the shops had 0
involvement with Acid Software - they were paid a royalty
for each copy sold. NOTE: The *entire* Blitz Support Suite
was put on this CD, WITHOUT our knowledge or consent.
We have received 0, zilch, nothing, from the 500 or so
sales of this CD (and hence, the 500 lost sales of BSS).
For sales of BSS (legitimate) we received 6 ukpounds
per copy. For this Ultimate Blitz CD which has lost
us 500 sales, we were offered nowhere NEAR
that much (clue <1 ukpound) so we have some
things to 'sort out' with Guildhall.

Q. Do you own the rights to Blitz Basic?
A. No. We have no ownership of the current (or future)
version of Blitz Basic. Acid gave us the source code
with a view to us enhancing it (as we did with SuperTED)
and working with them on a Blitz 3. This plan died
a long time ago.

Q. How will RWE get ownership?
A. Not sure. Guildhall seemed unwilling to sell the
rights to Blitz Basic (which they bought from Acid)
to us. Any version of 'Blitz' will be completely
unofficial, and therefore is unlikely to be called
Blitz (or published via Guildhall, for reasons above)

Q. Who at RWE is working on Blitz?
A. About 1 and a half :-) There are 3 programmers
at RWE. Myself, SteveMc and Nigel. Nigel is
now working on PC products. SteveMc has lost
interest in computers in general (something
to do with women..). I am still keen, but don't
have anywhere NEAR the amount of spare
time I used to have (when I was at uni..). I still
want to work on a future Blitz-alike language.

Q. What happened to Blitz2.6
A. We almost finished it - the debugger needed
a fair bit of work on it to have all the features
we wanted. SuperTED has some bugs, the
compiler worked from CLI. All in all, I guess
there would be another 2 months work in it.
Because we have no ownership rights,
we cannot distribute our source to
SuperTED or Blitz - which makes opening
up development with other programmers
a bit tricky.

Q. What about BlitzPPC
A. We definately want to a Blitz-alike language
which produces PPC code. It will still use
a library system similar (but without the inherent
drawbacks) to the current Blitz. Libraries
will consist of function and data sections so
that only code called by your program is
included in the executable. Other
details have to be decided - this is where
your input comes in.

I hope this answers the most important
questions. I'd like to open up the
whole development of a future Blitz-alike
to you people - a concerted, co-operative
effort could reap huge rewards.

Any questions, please don't hesitate
to email me. [I'll do my best to
reply quickly... :-)  ]

Steve.



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.119" "Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?"
From: Steven Wojciechowski <stevie-woj@boy-woj.demon.co.uk>
Date: 19 Mar 98 01:59:54 +0000
Subject: Re: RWE and Blitz - do we own it?

Previously in Life Paul Burkey(burkey@bigfoot.com) had this to say:
> I'm not optimistic about any kind of official 'take over' of
> Blitz. We all agree that Blitz is a unique and wonderfull
> language so giving up the rights or handing over some of the
> development would cause problems if ever there was a time
> that the Amiga grew into a large commercial platform again
> or a PC/Mac version became necessary.
> 
If RWE really want to take over the rights to Blitz then now is the
time to do it.  The amiga market is small so the rights shouldn't be
worth too much, if it's left till later when the Amiga get big again
or a PC/Mac version is needed then the rights will be worth alot more.


> > A. We definately want to a Blitz-alike language
> > which produces PPC code. It will still use
> > a library system similar (but without the inherent
> > drawbacks) to the current Blitz. Libraries
> > will consist of function and data sections so
> > that only code called by your program is
> > included in the executable.
> 
Good to hear :)


> An important approach to this projct would be to keep the
> possibility of multiplatform, multi cpu and a retargetable
> approach from the very start.
> 
Portability should be high priority.  Would the language need to take
account of multi cpus?  Wouldn't the OS handle CPU allocation for each
task?


> An interesting idea would be to copy C as much as possible
> while keeping things in a comfortable Blitz-like environment.
> The ability to import Blitz code or Export C code would
> be interesting with steps to keep compatability between
> the two languages whenever possible. Another 'C' variant is
> not interesting and a Blitz 'rip off' is pointless. Something
> inbetween is necessary.
> 
A developement suite type thing would be useful, much like M$ Visual
range.  Integrated GUI builder, etc would be incredably useful.

How about creating a language which uses the structures of C but just
represents them differently.  Infact, just a rework of C this would
make importing and exporting of C easy.  Maybe even have 2 modes, a C
mode and the Blitz-like mode.  In the Blitz-like mode things like
opening libraries would be handled by the compiler but in C you would
have to do it yourself.  Obviously this could be looked on as a C
variant but I think just reworking the presentation of C would be a
fairly effective method.  Thoughts?


> Having said all this, I still think the further development
> of Blitz itself is just as good an option an probably the
> most viable if that is ever an option.
> 
Guess we shouldn't forget that :)
--
Stevie W. 
http://www.boy-woj.demon.co.uk/
stevie-woj@boy-woj.demon.co.uk


