@NODE "Mail.145" "Re[6]: Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 1998 03:34:44 +0000
Subject: Re[6]: Next Generation of Blitz

Hi,

> > It would be (relatively) straightforward to create an ARexx script which
> > checks which word the cursor is on and sends that off to the online help
> > search program.

>   There is one point yet which we need to address.  Many buyers of
> Phoenix won't have one of these fancy editors nor know how to configure
> one to do all this cool stuff.  Many will be the user who hasn't found
> their way around who would REALLY be pissed if the Pheonix package
> didn't work as is when they got it but rather required them to purchase
> another expensive program which they didn't know where to get or how
> to use.

If Phoenix is going to be relased with an Editor as good as any
modern editor then it'll need to be developed. I'd say at least
2 people working full time for at least a year to come up with
such a beast. Now this is going to add a huge amount to the cost
of the development of the total package. I'm not talking about
financial costs because we're really talking about personal
effort and personal time. Once we get to the point where people
have put a year of hard work into a project we start to get
into the risky commercial side of things. I doubt we would ever
see any kind of commercial reward to justify such investment in
people for this kind of project. Using the power of 3rd party tools
like Text Editors will lessen the amount of developer time and
lower the costs.

Having said all this I do feel that an editor of the quality of
SuperTed with many additional features would be perfect. I don't
want to put SuperTed down... I'm very happy with it, but it could
do with some extra features and we all agree on that. I'm sure
it would be possible to get away with a modified SuperTed for the
official editor of Phoenix.

I'm just saying it'll never be as good as alternative editors.

> How about this for an idea:  We decide on a couple of good, modern
> editors. Next we see if we can arrange a deal with one of the
> manufacturers for a liscensed version at a good cost which we would
> include in the package WITH all of the necessary scripts, etc for
> making it work with Phoenix.  That way new users would have a complete,
> ready-to-use package with all the trimmings and all our editor team
> would have to do is plan the features to add and make the scripts.
> How does that sound?

This is what StormC++ did. StormC++ came with a registered version
of GoldEd from whatI can remember.

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

"disabled people are just too lazy to get out of their wheelchairs."
-- Brass Eye




@ENDNODE
