    Hi Blitzers,

[Paul was saying that...]
 =

>> The NLen command has been optimized -> About the same speed that the
>> original command and smaller.
> =

> Yes, this is much better. It's now only 5% slower than the original.
> I guess th real optimizing should be done when the commands are
> fully done.

    Good... Agree, Optimizing after the commands works... =

 =

>> ;-). Hope the number of function supported will be growing... If anyon=
e
>> want to join this (crazy) project...
> =

> If I had the time and the Asm skills I'd certainly like to help. Maybe
> I can help with the optimizing and bugtesting stages.

    Ok, No problem. You're welcome. Just say me which library you want to=

support first...
 =

> It would be a good idea to create a benchmark program that tests
> all of the new functions. That ay we can all give you some good
> speed tests as well as the possibility of incompatabilities. The
> benchmark program should be distributed in source code form to
> allow users to test out the before ans after speeds and exe sizes.

    I've it. It's timer based benchmarks and seems to be very accurate.

    Now, the news : I've added revised my point of view : Like I've not
enought library to do all the commands I want, I've put the command in th=
e
same library. So, there is one .obj for NewScreen commands and one other =
for
NewWindow commands. The result is impressive too. The Window.obj has thes=
e
commands and take only 390b when compiled :

    * NWindow(Tags)  ; Standart window
    * NWindowHeight =

    * NWindowWidth
    * NWBox
    * NWPlot         ; This one is 20% faster than the old function !
    * NWColour       =

    * NCloseWindow  =


    I think this would be easy to convert all the window related blitz2
commands into new format. Wait and see... For now, I create a 800b proggy=

which find the WBScreen, open a window, draw a plot and a box, wait a
mouseclick, return windowheight/width and quit. Try to do it in standart
blitz2 format and you will see a massive 13kb proggy ;-)

    Bye,

        Fred

PS: You must Remove all your old NWin*.obj and NScr*.obj file.
