Date: Wed, 01 Apr 1998 19:39:05 -0600
Subject: Re[5]: WritePixelArray8 (example)

Hi again
On 01-Apr-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
>Hi Curt,

>> > Just think of RastPort() as a way of telling OS functions which window
>> > you're talking about.

>> This I understand (I think, see the code below)

>The problem is, you're not doing this in the code below.

>> Window 1,winx,winy,winwid,winhi,$800,"",1,0        ;temporary rastport???

>Forget about temp rastports. Just use 0 until you find out what the
>temprp is for.

>> Window 0,winx,winy,winwid,winhi,$800|$1000,"",1,0  ;viewing window
>> rp.l=   Addr Window(0)                             ;rastport pointer

>This is wrong! You don't ant h address, you want the RastPort:-

>rp.l=RastPort(0)

OK, I understand (finally!)

>> chunk.l=Addr Chunky(2)         ;this is wrong, I know - but what for this??
>> count.l=WritePixelArray8_ (rp,0,0,winwid,winhi,chunk,tmprp)

>okay, heres a bit more info. You're don't tell WritePixelArray the
>size of the window. You give it the size of your chunky buffer. If
>your buffer is winwid,winhit then your WPA8_ will be:

>0,0,winwid-1,winhit-1

>The size of the window doesn't matter at all.

>So the following line would work:

>WritePixelArray8_ RastPort(0),0,0,winwid-1,winhit-1,chunk,0

>You don't have to use the return value: 'count='


>I've attached the most simple example of WritePixelArray8 you
>could ever imagine :) I can't say for sure that it works on AGA
>systems but it's a good easy example anyway.

Thanks for all the help on this.  Unfortunately, the real problem turns out to
be that the WPA8_ command appears NOT to be able to work on an AGA system.

I tried your example, and it does the same thing as my code - opens an empty
window, then the program hangs...

Looks like the only option is to convert the chunky back to a normal bitmap,
then use BitMapToWindow when I want to display it.

Still, doing my manipulations to the fast ram chunky are faster than doing
them with normal bitmap commands.  And I think this would allow the program to
be compatable with GFX cards too - I could do the conversion to a bitmap on
AGA systems, and use WPA8_ for GFX cards.

Thanks Paul and everybody else for the help and ideas on this.

-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
