@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.170" "Re[4]: Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Mon, 30 Mar 1998 20:51:17 +0000
Subject: Re[4]: Next Generation of Blitz

Hi Donovan,

>   Your points are all good and valid as far as simply editing code goes.
> But when I said extra, helpful features I meant help specific to the
> language itself and tokenization aimed specifically at aiding programing
> in that particular language.  The helps and tokenization in the fine
> editors you mentioned are all aimed at text editing in general and would
> offer no help with commands or procedures specific to Blitz/Pheonix.

Tokenizing Blitz code is no problem to GoldEd. You just have to
create a Blitz/Phoenix module and it'll then tokenize the source
in far more detail than Ted ever did.

>   Maybe what I am envisioning is to complex, I don't know.  It just seems
> like having a lot of specific on-line help would help the creative juices
> flow better and faster.  I personally hate to have to go searching,
> searching for some syntax, command or method that I forgot when I'm
> trying to juggle complex ideas and fresh inspirations in my head.

Adding Blitz based on-line help to a modern editor is also no
problem. If a blitz cli based compiler was released this week
you'd have online help and tokenizing within a few days.

> I hope I am not making myself obnoxious here as I realise there are
> definately several different preferances extant on this subject.

I must admit to not being totaly at home with GoldEd but I'm quite
looking forward to editing it to suit my needs when I'm writing my
next project. Most features of SuperTed could be 'ported' over to
GoldEd via macros/menus/shortcuts which would leave us almost in
the same possition we are now. By that time anyone with 'different
preferences' will see that it's not a huge difference and the
added bonus features will come in time.

Before I started coding in Blitz a couple of years ago I was
used to using AmosPro. Trying to get used to Ted was shear hell.
I could say the same thing about AMOSPro when I was used to
using the original Amos. After a couple of weeks you soon start
to feel at home.

I'd never recomend moving to the kind of GCC/SASC world of
makefiles, dos scripts and Intergrated Environments held together
by sticky tape and glue. I'm keen to see things put together in
such a way as to look professional, Smooth and Simple. I know
that a fresh compiler and a lot of planning could achieve this
with or without an intergrated editor.

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

...and always remember the last words of
my grandfather, who said "A truck!""
-- Emo Phillips




