@NODE "Mail.175" "Re: Re[4]: BlitzPPC?"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 17:45:54 +1200
Subject: Re: Re[4]: BlitzPPC?

On 14-Mar-98, Donovan Reeve wrote:
 
>  So why is RISC the way to go now? Simply because it
>has been developed more and taken to higher speeds.
>  If the same energy, time and research had been
>expended on CISC chips they would at this time be
>superior to RISC chips.  

  A point people have put foward for RISC, is in assembler, you can
customise your code more, you can taylor your routines to make them more
efficient, whereas on a CISC chip those routines might be set in the
chip itself and may not be as efficient for your use of them.
  Wether it would make any difference to compiled code, I don't know.

   I don't know how many registers Pentiums have now, but chips like the
486 always had a lot less registers than a more RISC-like 68k chip- the
extra registers can make your code much more efficient (especially in
assem). 
 
-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
       



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.176" "Re: Re[4]: BlitzPPC?"
	Mon, 16 Mar 1998 18:27:23 +0100 (MET)
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 18:27:23 +0100 (MET)
From: Claus Herrmann <cyclone@rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>
Subject: Re: Re[4]: BlitzPPC?

On Mon, 16 Mar 1998, Anton Reinauer wrote:

> On 14-Mar-98, Donovan Reeve wrote:
>  
> >  So why is RISC the way to go now? Simply because it
> >has been developed more and taken to higher speeds.
> >  If the same energy, time and research had been
> >expended on CISC chips they would at this time be
> >superior to RISC chips.  
> 
>   A point people have put foward for RISC, is in assembler, you can
> customise your code more, you can taylor your routines to make them more
> efficient, whereas on a CISC chip those routines might be set in the
> chip itself and may not be as efficient for your use of them.
>   Wether it would make any difference to compiled code, I don't know.
> 
you have to ook at the code you produce.. in my studies of 
computerscience my professor told me that 80% of all soft6ware just uses 
20% of a cisc commands and thats why they build a RISC (reduced 
instruction.) chip. if software (the 20%) uses other commands they could 
be easyly reproduced with other risc commands.
with this genuine idea, chip designers could make RISC chips smaller and 
thus more speedier than cisc cpu (as you see look at a 300Mhz Pentium 2 
and a 750Mhz 604e (on www.mot.com) from motorola).
some of you own now a ppc card from phase5.. they should look at the 
enourmous size of their companion CPU (the CISC 68k cpu) to the thumbnail 
big 604e with 150,180,200 Mhz.
And if somebody says, that cisc are better, then i have a question for 
him, why does the pentium chip also have 3 risc cpus inside his ceramic 
design ?? 1 risc for converting cisc to risc and two for doing the job ??


>    I don't know how many registers Pentiums have now, but chips like the
> 486 always had a lot less registers than a more RISC-like 68k chip- the
> extra registers can make your code much more efficient (especially in
> assem). 
>  

tsts.. 68K are CISC chips with 8 registers for Data and 8 registers for 
adresses.
the PPC 604e is a risc chip with 32GPR (general purpose registers, you 
can use them for adressing and for data!) and even 32 registers for fpu ! 
and all registers are 64 bit wide.. (68k registers are only 32bit)

cheerio 

> -- 
>         Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
>        
> 
> 


