@NODE "Mail.178" "Re: Re[4]: BlitzPPC?"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 09:29:32 +0500
Subject: Re: Re[4]: BlitzPPC?

On 16-Mar-98, Anton Reinauer flashed:
>On 14-Mar-98, Donovan Reeve wrote:
> 
>>  So why is RISC the way to go now? Simply because it
>>has been developed more and taken to higher speeds.
>>  If the same energy, time and research had been
>>expended on CISC chips they would at this time be
>>superior to RISC chips.  

>  A point people have put foward for RISC, is in assembler, you can
>customise your code more, you can taylor your routines to make them more
>efficient, whereas on a CISC chip those routines might be set in the
>chip itself and may not be as efficient for your use of them.
>  Wether it would make any difference to compiled code, I don't know.

  This does indeed have merit in some cases, but it has been my
experiance that the improved effeciancy is generally hard to accomplish
and usually doesn't make up for the need for extra clock cycles.

>   I don't know how many registers Pentiums have now, but chips like the
>486 always had a lot less registers than a more RISC-like 68k chip- the
>extra registers can make your code much more efficient (especially in
>assem).

 True

 My original points were simply intended to be that RISC processors
don't basically 'do more per clock cycle than CISC (the particular 
design of the individual chip model can effect this in many ways),
and that I do believe that RISC is the way to go now even though it
might not have been the best choice for developement orrigionally.

 The (assumed) point underlying all of this being that yes, it is
important for Blitz Basic to have PPC support added because for
whatever reasons PPC has become important to the Amiga at this point
in time.
  And, as has been indicated by several people erlier in this particular
thread,  it would be very nice if Blitz could be set up to allow for
support of other processors in the future as well.

  I appologize for wandering perhaps to far from the main subject.

          
         Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)

 




@ENDNODE
