>  I just checked on Alta-Vista - there's a Phoenix Software Corporation,=

>which could be a problem.
>  The problem with the name Phoenix, is it's such a widespread name,
>used by many businesses- you'd have to carefully check wether you could
>use it :-/


  In the U.S.A. at least, business names, titles, personal names, song
names, etc. are not copywritable.  I believe it is that way in
international copywrite law as well.  Product names and product line
trade names ARE copywritable however.

  In other words, nameing the company Pheonix would be no problem, but
naming the product Pheonix would present a problem if there exists a
product already with that name.

  There is still no problem really however.  All we have to do is make
sure there is no product with that EXACT name.  What everybody winds
up calling doesn't matter.  Many people call the I.B.M. clones P.C.s
even though the term was in existance long befor they came along.
  So all we have to do is name our product Pheonix Basic or Pheonix
Programing system or Pheonix AB or some such name and everybody can
call it Pheonix if they like.  It is really no problem as long as the
OFFICIAL name is different in some way to any existing product.


     Have a good one,

         Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com) for now (may change soon)




@ENDNODE
