@NODE "Mail.186" "Re[3]: Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Sun, 29 Mar 1998 13:59:30 +0100
Subject: Re[3]: Next Generation of Blitz


PB>Ted offers very little extras  compared  to  a  modern  text  editor.
PB>Something  like  GoldEd  offers Tokenizing, Procedure folding, Drag &
PB>Drop, QuickReference/Online-Help,  Indention  of  blocks,  Formatting
PB>functions,  AutoBackup,  Clipboard support, Parenthesis check (can be
PB>modified for If..EndIf Repeat..Until checking), AutoCase,  Wildcards,
PB>Insertion/remove  of  columns,  Proper  Undo & redo, Automatic phrase
PB>completion,  XPK  support,  Built-in  file   search,   Sequence/Macro
PB>recording,   Very   Configurable   GUI,  Amazingly(sp?)  Configurable
PB>Menus/Hotkeys/Macros etc..

Yes I agree that GoldED offers a very wide range of features,  and  that
it's  a  really  good editor. Infact I'm using GoldED to write this mail
now. If you start comparing GoldED and  SuperTED,  you'll  soon  realise
that  superTEd needs a face life. But we all know that it has a few bugs
to work out, and some missing features to be given. But I wont go on and
on and on about what we already know.

PB>What I'd like to see if a very open compiler system.  Maybe  a  small
PB>GUI  that  can sit on the screen of your favourite editor (SuperTed?)
PB>an this can be used for compiling and compiler options.  In  addition
PB>to this it could be controled from the editor with user defined menus
PB>options via a Rex port. So, I suggest that the new compiler is simply
PB>a  GUI/Commodity  that  can  be  controlled  from a modified SuperTED
PB>and/or any other Editor. I see no reason why SuperTED can't evolve to
PB>support  this  system but the 3rd part Editors will always offer more
PB>Editing features.

Have you guys every seen StormC++ ?? Now thats what I would like for the
Phoenix  system to be built up. It has a small controle panel, with nine
buttons, a small text feild and nothing  more.  These  buttons  are  the
basic  things  like  New,  Load,  Save,  Run, Compile etc. This is where
everything is controled from. StormC comes with a editor, which you  can
if  IF  you want to. It's nothing fancy at all, but it's really suiteble
for StormC, it has tokenizing (not in  blitz  style  though,  it  colors
commands  in  one  color,  parameters  in  one color, etc. Which is VERY
smart.) and such things. Now you can use this if you want  to,  but  you
dont  have  to.  You  can use GoldED (or any other editor), if you want,
since you can CLI compile from StormC, so you just config your editor to
send the right parameters to the compiler, and it compiles it.

It also has a Linker window, which you can bring up at anytime. It shows
which  libraries  anf  files  you  have incuded to your program. It also
shows you what the name of the executable file is, etc. This is  a  very
good thing, and I think Phoenix should have something simular.

Another thing that StormC offers is Projects. Lets say your working on a
program,  and  you  have  written 2 files, that you include in your main
program (yes, this is also possible in blitz). Now lets say you have  to
change  the  contents of the include files as you program the main file,
then you would open all three files in  diffrent  editor  windows  (also
possible in blitz). Ok, now here comes the part that SuperTED misses out
on. Now you decide to save your program, and  go  and  have  dinner.  In
SuperTED  you  would  save the three files, and quit. But in StormC, you
would see to it, that you have saves the three  files,  and  saved  your
Project.  Now  the  next  time you get back to your program to code, you
would have to open all three files in SuperTED as seperat files, but  in
StormC you would only have to open the Project, and it would automaticly
open all three files, and put them in Linker, for you to  click  on  and
edit.  This  wouldnt  be hard to add to a new editor, it would be really
easy infact.

Well so why should we make a new editor, and re inwent the  wheel?  Well
the  new  editor  would be written so that it takes advantage of all the
new features in Phoenix. And other things that it should  support,  that
GoldED and other editors doen't support (except for SuperTED, but it's a
bit "buggy"). Is the Label window, where every label appears in, so  you
easely  can  jump to them, by clicking on the label you want to jump to,
in the Label Window. Now this could be a seperat  window  that  you  can
open if you want to.

Well I have many ideas and comments  to  why  a  new  editor  should  be
written  for  Phoenix  (mind  you  the new editor wont be releaeed until
Phoenix has reached phase6, or in other word, become a new language).

 Kindest Regards,

Andreas H=E5kansson, Phoenix project Super Visor.





























@ENDNODE
