@NODE "Mail.190" "Re[3]: BlitzPPC?"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Wed, 11 Mar 1998 18:26:10 +0100
Subject: Re[3]: BlitzPPC?


 Hi Paul,

Well what I wrote about in my last mail hadn't anything
to do with the  3rd  party libs (will talk  about  them
more further down in the mail), but  about  which would
be the best way for Red When Excited to  make  the  PPC
part of blitz. And I still  think  that  the  cpu  data
plugin method is the best  way  to do it, since it will
automaticlly make it much  easier  to  make  the  blitz
compiler generate code  for  anyother  cpu  types  that
might be put in the future  amiga  machines (would only
have a write a new cpu data plugin  for  that  cpu, and
and give out to the blitz community). And it would also
be a smart way of making it easyer to  make  bug  fixes
and updates to the compiler, since you would  only need
to  change  the  cpu  plugin  file (which  wont  be big
commpared to a full compiler). 

Ok  now  to  the  3rd party  libs. Lets split them into 
three  diffrent  types  of libs ok. The 68000 libs, the
optimised libs (for lets say the 020 cpu) and  the  ppc
libs. We can all agree that the current blitz  libs all
are  the first  type, which  arn't  optimised  for  any
special 68k cpu. These libs can still be  the  same  in
any version of blitz (68k or ppc), since  the  commands
in them, can be compiled for both cpus, just  like  any
C compiler with ppc support can handle the standard 68k
libraries found in  your  libs  drawer. Since  it  will
generate ppc code that will access the 68k  based libs.
This will mean that all the  library  accesses will  be
in the same speed as if they where  called  from a  68k
application.

Now if people started ot  make the  ppc libs for blitz,
then it  would  be something  completly  diffrent. Then
when a command from the ppc  libs is  called, with will
run on the ppc and not on the 68k. This means that  for
full  ppc  optimisation  you  will  have  to  have libs
written ppc native code. This  applies  for  with  C as
well as for any blitz  compiler that can  compiler  ppc
code. But hey this doesnt  mean t hat if  you  where to
write a program in blitz, only  using  68k  based libs,
and then generate ppc code, and run it  of a  ppc  cpu,
that it would run at the same speed as if you ran it of
a 68k cpu. It will be much  faster, much  much  faster,
since the ppc preforms  calculations  etc  much fatser,
and it can do more things in each cpu  cycle then a 68k
can, since  it  has a  reduced  instruction  set (hence
RICS). If there is a ppc  blitz  version, then  I would
very much like to have the graphics based libs (shapes,
bitmaps etc) reweitten in ppc native  code, since  this
would mean enourmous blitting speed, much  faster  then
on a 060. Even though the  todays  graphics libs  would
run much fatser in ppc native  compiled code, since  it
preforms things faster (like I said before).

And for optimised libs. There are  two methods of doing
this. Write new libs that uses 020  unique commands, to
speed them up (on a 020 or above). Or make a plugin for
the  compiler, which  generates  pure 020 code. Combind
both and you'll have even  faster code. Once  more  the
plugin system shows how usefull it would be, since  you
could  also  make 030, 040  and  060 plugins  for   the
compiler and support them as well.

 ByE!





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.191" "Re: Re[3]: BlitzPPC?"
	Mon, 16 Mar 1998 18:14:59 +0100 (MET)
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 18:14:58 +0100 (MET)
From: Claus Herrmann <cyclone@rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>
Subject: Re: Re[3]: BlitzPPC?

On Wed, 11 Mar 1998, Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= wrote:

> 
