@NODE "Mail.192" "Re: Re[3]: BlitzPPC?"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Sat, 14 Mar 1998 11:47:46 +0500
Subject: Re: Re[3]: BlitzPPC?

On 11-Mar-98, Andreas H=E5kansson flashed:

> Hi Paul,

>Well what I wrote about in my last mail hadn't ...

>Now if people started ot  make the  ppc libs for blitz,
>then it  would  be something  completly  diffrent. Then
>when a command from the ppc  libs is  called, with will
>run on the ppc and not on the 68k. This means that  for
>full  ppc  optimisation  you  will  have  to  have libs
>written ppc native code. This  applies  for  with  C as
>well as for any blitz  compiler that can  compiler  ppc
>code. But hey this doesnt  mean t hat if  you  where to
>write a program in blitz, only  using  68k  based libs,
>and then generate ppc code, and run it  of a  ppc  cpu,
>that it would run at the same speed as if you ran it of
>a 68k cpu. It will be much  faster, much  much  faster,
>since the ppc preforms  calculations  etc  much fatser,
>and it can do more things in each cpu  cycle then a 68k
>can, since  it  has a  reduced  instruction  set (hence
>RICS).

Pardon my interuption, but this is a common misconception
which murkys up the water considerably in peoples views
on processors.
  RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Chip [or CPU in some
circles]) processors tend to turn higher cycle speeds
due to not having as great an instruction list to go
through. This looks impressive in specs, and in fact
that propaganda value was one of the main reasons for
the 'Wintel' consortium to go to them in the first place,
because it looked good on advertising.  A RISC chip does
NOT however 'do more things' per cycle than a CISC chip.
Allthough there are many thing which will effect
performance, all other things being equal a CISC chip
actually averages more accomplished per cycle.  In other
words, if the speed, buffers, busses and some other
things are the same then a CISC chip will out-perform
a RISC chip, especially at certain types of tasks.
The RISC chip requires bulkier code because some of the
missing instructions require 'building up' from several
other available instructions when they are needed.
  So why is RISC the way to go now? Simply because it
has been developed more and taken to higher speeds.
  If the same energy, time and research had been
expended on CISC chips they would at this time be
superior to RISC chips.  Much debate is even now taking
place within the electronics research community about
this subject.  Many feel that even now RISC should be
abandoned and some are even pushing the idea (with
good reasoning to back it up) of processor chips with
a SuperSet of hard-wired instructions.
  As is the case of the Amiga, the best doesn't always
become the best selling.  Advertising and business
proceedures (sometimes basically dishonest) have more
to do with who and what wins than utility and quality,
unfortunatly.


>       If there is a ppc  blitz  version, then  I would
>very much like to have the graphics based libs (shapes,
>bitmaps etc) reweitten in ppc native  code, since  this
>would mean enourmous blitting speed, much  faster  then
>on a 060. Even though the  todays  graphics libs  would
>run much fatser in ppc native  compiled code, since  it
>preforms things faster (like I said before).


 True it will run faster, but only because of faster cycle
speeds.

  Sorry about getting so far off the beaten path, but we
all need to be aware of the way things really stand.


     Donovan Reeve  (bubby@inetnebr.com)







@ENDNODE
