> > is  causing alot of problems. Conflicting librarys numbers, lack
> > of free library numbers etc. Can this be solved in another way?

>   Certainly.  There is absolutly no need to use set numbers.
> That is cludgy just like line numbers were cludgy and should be
> done away with for the same reason.  Alph-numeric lib names are
> sufficient an flexible.

This has sparked an idea off. Why not allow the compiler to
create a number for us. The number could be created using
somthing like:

size of lib * number of functions * (sum of ascii val of lib name) 

Then simply subtract 65,000 from the answer until the result is
small enough for a WORD. Then we have a 65,000-1 chance
of any lib having the same lib number :)

But what is the point in these lib numbers anyway? If the source
code is not Tokenized then is it necessary to have such a number
system. Can't the compiler simply give each lib a number as they
are loaded in?


Cheers

