>  Yes, this would be a good way of doing things IMHO.

I agree - certainley the new language should allow the user of other editors.

But why throw away SuperTed?  It is not as if we need to make a new editor
from scratch.  Just enhance SuperTed to support the new compiler, and add as
many of the suggested features as can be easily done.

Then, if someone doesn't feel that it suits their needs, of course they may
use any other editor they wish!

But for marketing purposes, there must be some kind of editor included.  You
can't sell someone a programming language, then tell them they must buy a
separate editor just to make it work.  This would be like selling an auto
without wheels...





