  Your points are all good and valid as far as simply editing code goes.
But when I said extra, helpful features I meant help specific to the
language itself and tokenization aimed specifically at aiding programing
in that particular language.  The helps and tokenization in the fine
editors you mentioned are all aimed at text editing in general and would
offer no help with commands or procedures specific to Blitz/Pheonix.

  I guess I am thinking of the novice programers and lunkheads like me
who forget things a lot.  #;u)>
  Maybe what I am envisioning is to complex, I don't know.  It just seems
like having a lot of specific on-line help would help the creative juices
flow better and faster.  I personally hate to have to go searching,
searching for some syntax, command or method that I forgot when I'm
trying to juggle complex ideas and fresh inspirations in my head.
  Of course, everybody is different.  I just know that there seem to be
far more people struggling and getting hopelessly discouraged than
there are those who sail right through coding projects.

  I'm not trying to be a hardcase here, but to me it seems valuable to
have a dedicated editor.
  I do believe however that it should also be made as easy and pleasant
as possible on those who prefer to use the editor of their choice.
Definately the code should not be handled in such a way as to limit it
to only being uasble on the dedicated editor.

  I hope I am not making myself obnoxious here as I realise there are
definately several different preferances extant on this subject.


