@NODE "Mail.222" "Re[2]: Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Sun, 29 Mar 1998 03:45:22 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: Next Generation of Blitz

Hi,

> > I even sometimes use SuperTed on it's own as a text editor.
> 
> I use SuperTed almost exclusively.  I seldom use any other editors fo
> anything. In fact, it is the editor I use with YAM and I am using it
> right now to type this!
> 
> I believe we need a dedicated editor with the extra helpful features
> but it isfine to make it so people can write or modify Pheonix code
> in a normal editor if they want to.  They would just have to do without
> the extra helpful features.
> Allthough why anybody would want to do that I don't know.  #;u)>

Ted offers very little extras compared to a modern text editor. Something
like GoldEd offers Tokenizing, Procedure folding, Drag & Drop,
QuickReference/Online-Help, Indention of blocks, Formatting functions,
AutoBackup, Clipboard support, Parenthesis check (can be modified for
If..EndIf Repeat..Until checking), AutoCase, Wildcards, Insertion/remove
of columns, Proper Undo & redo, Automatic phrase completion, XPK support,
Built-in file search, Sequence/Macro recording, Very Configurable GUI,
Amazingly(sp?) Configurable Menus/Hotkeys/Macros etc..

okay so I went over the top listing stuff but you get the idea. It
does everything and a lot more compared to SuperTed. Wouldn't it be
a huge waste of time to try and re-invent the wheel when it comes to
source code editing?

GoldEd is just an example, we also have a CygnusEd which is now supported
once again. We have BED which looks like another good alternative.

What I'd like to see if a very open compiler system. Maybe a small
GUI that can sit on the screen of your favourite editor (SuperTed?)
an this can be used for compiling and compiler options. In addition
to this it could be controled from the editor with user defined
menus options via a Rex port.

So, I suggest that the new compiler is simply a GUI/Commodity that
can be controlled from a modified SuperTED and/or any other Editor.
I see no reason why SuperTED can't evolve to support this system
but the 3rd part Editors will always offer more Editing features. 

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

