>> pixels to a window.

>BitmapToWindow will be executed via some kind of planar to chunky
>system. It's possible that you could write an exceptionaly fast
>p2c function to replace BitmapToWindow but this would only benefit
>GFX ard users and for them you would be better to use chunky
>modes in the first place. So yeah, forget that :)

No, maybe I worded it wrong.  I was really looking for a way to put a fast ram
chunky directly into a standard (non-GFX card) window, without needing to
convert it to a standard (chip ram) bitmap.

So standard AGA systems, as well as GFX card systems, could easily use fast
ram chunky commands too. 


                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.225" "Re[2]: New ChunkyCPU Blit command planned"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 01 Apr 1998 03:11:39 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: New ChunkyCPU Blit command planned

Hi Curt,

> > You say we should replace BitmapToWindow, but I think
> > WritePixelArray8 would have the same effect, as it writes a chunky array of
> > pixels to a window. 

> Well, yes I know it would - if I could figure out how to use it - I get lost
> once it gets to the part with the quadruple parenthesis and the temporary
> rastport.

the rastport bit is simple. If it's window 1 then you just use RastPort(1)
Just think of RastPort() as a way of telling OS functions which window
you're talking about.

> And it shows the pointer to the chunky "array" as a byte - how can I do this?

it's the address of the first byte in the array. Array meaning a
2D bitmap created by a 2 dimentional array. Just supply the start
address of this array eg:

&chunkybuffer(0,0)

or the address of the memory bank or chunky buffer depending on
the method you're using.

> I was kind of hoping for a Blitz command version of this  :)

Somone could easily make one. You'd still have to supply the address
of your buffer and the probably the window you wanted to render it
to but a replacemenr function would be pointless considering how easy
the function is to use once you work it out :)

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

"I stayed up all night playing poker with tarot cards.
I got a full house, and four people died..."
-- Stephen Wright




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.226" "Re[2]: New ChunkyCPU Blit command planned"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 1998 14:29:05 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: New ChunkyCPU Blit command planned

Hi,

> You say we should replace BitmapToWindow, but I think
> WritePixelArray8 would have the same effect, as it writes a chunky array of
> pixels to a window.

BitmapToWindow will be executed via some kind of planar to chunky
system. It's possible that you could write an exceptionaly fast
p2c function to replace BitmapToWindow but this would only benefit
GFX ard users and for them you would be better to use chunky
modes in the first place. So yeah, forget that :)

> You can do all your graphics operations on the chunky bitmap
> with the proposed new library.

Yes, rendering direct to a fast mem chunky buffer is the fastest
way to render. Much faster than rendering direct to the gfx card.

You said you'd done some speed tests and they went well. You'll
probably find that speeds show fairly good results on 030 but
once you get into the 040/060 league you'll notice how fast
the chunky modes speed up.

> So anyone interested? I think we need someone with experience of creating
> libraries (Christos?), and people with some knowledge of ASM. We should also
> come up with a list of commands people would like. I can think of the
following
> that need chunky equivalents, off the top of my head:
> GetAShape

yeah, you coul do with deciding on a new object type. The chunky
shape object! probably quite easy to come up with. You only
need to support width, height, handles and possibly a depth flag
for the addition of 16 or 24bit support at a future date.

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

"The cow landed in a bone-heap."
-- Brass Eye




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.227" "Re[2]: Multitasking"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Sun, 29 Mar 1998 03:23:10 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: Multitasking

Hi Donovan,

> > routines I coded myself to replace the Blitter calls. Then you dump the
> > results of your byte buffer to the window using WritePixelArray8_().
> > This method was
> > suggested to me by Paul Burkey. It involves the most effort by far.

> If someone could give us a concise, fully detailed explaination of this
> I would like to include it in the new manual.

There isn't much to say about this method really. It's just a case of
creating a chunky buffer similar to this array:

Dim chunkybuf.b(320x256)   ; 320x256 chunky buffer

Then you render to it using whatever methods you like. The most simple
method is to render pixels like this:

chunkybuf(200,100)=5  ; similar to Plot 200,100,5

More complex methods would include the type of thing that was offered
in a recent mail. The Asm routines to blit chunky shapes to the
chunky buffer. Chunky commands like Cls, Box, Line etc.. are very
simple to create for chunky buffer. Just imagine that it's an
array of bytes because thats all a chunky buffer is.

Once the chunky buffer is ready to be displayed you can use a
chunky to planar system for the AGA version. A chunky to planar
command is available in the 'QuickLib.obj' available on Aminet.
For GFX card version you'd use something like WritePixelArray8_

for our 'Dim chunkybuf()' example it would look like this:

WritePixelArray8_ RastPort(win#),0,0,319,255,&chunkybuf(0,0),0

Which means:-

Dump chunky buffer to the RastPort of window win# starting at
coordinates 0,0 and ending at coordinates 319,255. The chunky
buffer starts in memory location &chunkybuf(0,0). The final
paramiter is 0. Read the docs on WPA8_ if you need more info
in this final paramiter of the command itself..

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

"I used to be an airline pilot, but I got fired cause I kept locking the keys
in the plane...  They caught me on an 80 foot stepladder with a coathanger..."
-- Stephen Wright




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.228" "Re: Re[2]: Make a much more powerfull Blitz 2"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 28 Mar 1998 06:14:18 -0600
Subject: Re: Re[2]: Make a much more powerfull Blitz 2

On 28-Mar-98, Fr=E9d=E9ric Laboureur wrote:

>    I think no, but we have a different point of view. Who will use all =
the
>String$ command in only one proggy ? Say me... Some a very specific. I t=
hink
>this is good to have all tyhe command separated with it's source code be=
cause
>we could easely change some CPU eating command in PPC obj, without any
problem
>(just use an different DefLibs). Agree ?

>> On the plus side I think it'll be a great idea to create
>> fixed versions of the buggy commands. If any of the commands
>> can be made faster then thats another big plus!

>    Yes, Right$, Left$, Mid$ command lacks of protection and crashe is y=
ou
>enter 0 or negative value to length. Easy to fix. For the speed, I'm
adressing
>to all this REAL Amiga ASM programmer ;-)

This sounds like a good idea to me.

But I do see one problem  (I may be wrong, I know little about ASM and le=
ss
about how the Blitz libraries are done)

Don't the commands in some libraries share some subroutines from the libr=
ary?

For example, "Left$", "Right$", "Mid$", all must determine the location o=
f the
given string in memory, get it's length (probably using the "Len" code?),=

allocate some memory for the new string, transfer the set number of chara=
cters
to the new string, and set the new string's pointer to point to this new
string.
I would think each of these steps would be a subroutine, and the commands=

themselves would simply tell the subroutines how many characters to get a=
nd
where to start.

So if you make each of these into it's own library, now each command has =
to
include all these routines.  If you use only one of them, your program wo=
uld
be shorter.  But if you used all three then the program size would be big=
ger
than with all of these in one library, because you have duplicated most o=
f it
3 times.

So I think this makes sense to do only with the libraries that do not sha=
re
much of the code among themselves.

Or if there is a way to separate the subroutines out too, and have Blitz
include
a copy of it if any command needs it,  but only include it once. =


-- =

                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
