>
>It should be a case of creting a huge 1 plane bitmap instead of
>creating the normal planar bitmap. Eg, a 320x200 8 plane bitmap
>would become a 320x1600 1 plane bitmap. If you want to get into
>shapes and other matters then things get harder to do but not
>impossible. I've not played with all this for a long while.


The problem with that method, is that the values in the bitmap structure =
will wrong.  With OS 3.x, you really need to use AllocBitmap() with =
#BMF_INTERLEAVED to create an interleaved bitmap (actually you should =
use AllocBitmap() for *any bitmap on OS 3+.)  It wouldn't take much to =
change the Blitz Bitmap library to use AllocBitmap() ...

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.232" "Re[2]: Interleaved bitmaps"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 19:42:21 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: Interleaved bitmaps

Hi Sami,

> code will continue execution immediately after the blitter is
> started. But if you have conventional bitmap the blitter first executes 7
> blittings and your prog have to wait until the 8 blitting is started, and
> after that it will continue.

Yes, thats a valid point. Interleaved bitmaps can give some good
speedups if you're lucky enough to be able to use them.

> I though have no idea how to alloc interleaved bitmap in the blitz,
> but by making it by yourself. :(

It should be a case of creting a huge 1 plane bitmap instead of
creating the normal planar bitmap. Eg, a 320x200 8 plane bitmap
would become a 320x1600 1 plane bitmap. If you want to get into
shapes and other matters then things get harder to do but not
impossible. I've not played with all this for a long while.

Cheers,

