@NODE "Mail.237" "Re[2]: Gfx cards (what else?)"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Mon, 30 Mar 1998 15:29:06 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: Gfx cards (what else?)

Hi James,

>   my questions/problem are getting more technical by the day... maybe someone
> could point me in the direction of a good technical reference for graphics
> card programming (preferably online)...

Why not start with the blits-os page. Learn a bit about using
the graphics.library and intuition.library and you're away! Apprt
from mastering AmigaOS functions theres very little to learn
about GFX card programming.

> doh! Yet another thing about gfx cards that I had no idea about. What are
> valid gfx card ModeIds? Is there somewhere I can find them?]

No. Every GFX card has its own set of ModeId's. What if you had a
PicassoIV and a CV64/3D in the same machine? You'd need to know
which one you wanted to use by using different ModeId's. Using
an ASL requestor is very easy but there are other more complicated
ways of getting the Id, for example using BestModeIDA_()

> And opening the screen without a gfx card ModeId?
> Will that open it using AGA unless he has a screen promotion
> entry to put it on his gfx card?

If you open a 640x256 screen with Blitz then *Blitz* will probably
default to an AGA mode. You're probably already using an AGA ModeId
with your open screen function. 

If he has screen mode promotion then it will promote to the GFX
card mode if he sets promotion up to do so. Supporting GFX cards
via the promotion method is regarded as a very "hacky" way to
support such screen modes. Using ASL mode requestor is easy to
do anyay.

>[Custom screen modes]

> OK, this can be done for CyberGfX, what about for Picasso? I'm in a quandry
> now, 320x240 is too small horizontally, and 640x400 too big vertically! If
the
> Screen Promotion commodity were used what size would it promote to? 600x400?

Well an important part of GFX card support is understanding that
screen aspect is almost always "square". None of this squashed
pixels stuff. Even though I managed to crete a 640x256 screen mode
on my CV64 it's still looks odd because the pixels on a GFX card
won't "squash" very much at all. It gives a Widescreen effect.

> > You are using an ASL Screen mode requestor to choose the ModeId?

> No... maybe this would be a good idea. But then I'm still missing my 640x256
> resolution. And if I promote to 640x400 my graphics will look all squashed
> and nasty.

Don't forget that the large size is actually 640x480 not 640x400. You
could get away with 640x400 but it would leave a space at the bottom.
Is there any way you can support variable sized displays? With my game
you can open any size screen and it will render more or less view area
depending on how much space there is. I must admit it's complicated to
add this at first but it works well.

I don't remember the exact details on your game but imagine a kind
of C&C game that displayed it's game in a grid of 15x12. With a
larger screen it could expand this to 15x20 IYSWIM. Building in this
type of thing is extra work but it looks amazing when pushed to the
limits eg, on a 1600x1200 screen mode :)

I do honestly think your 2:1 aspect is going to cause problems.
Would you consider going for hires or supporting hires and medium
resolution graphics?

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

