@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.246" "Re[2]: Chunky CPUBlit Benchmarks"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 01 Apr 1998 03:48:42 +0000
Subject: Re[2]: Chunky CPUBlit Benchmarks

Hi Anton,

> running at 50 frames a second? I don't have a fast processor or a
> graphics board, so I can't check it out :-/  With interleaved bitmaps in
> AGA, the blitting takes virtually no main loop time as it parallel
> processes.

Well no matter how you put it the blitter is slow and can't do
that much work in 50th of a second. a fast cpu can do a lot more
rendering compared to the blitter. On faster cpu's we're talking
about 4-5 times as much gfx work. So in theory you could do twice
as much rendering and twice as many cpu calculations as you would
with a slower machine with very little effort. If you stick with
using the blitter you're stuck with rendering at 14mhz no matter
what machine you're running on. I guess it boils down to the big
old problem on the Amiga... Use the custom chips and keep the users
with slow cpu's happy or use the cpu and make the high end users
happy. You can't easily have both and there are valid reasons
to support either of these two choices. If you choose to use the
Blitter then you'll find 040 and 060 users complaining that the
game could have had better effects, more objects, more details
and smoother gameplay if you din't limit renering to the speed
of the blitter. It really depends who your target user is and
whether you're happy limiting the complexity of the game to
work with slow machines.

> Is there anything similar to blitting functions on graphics boards,
> that would parallel process as well?

I'd say that graphics card blitter works in exactly the same way. If
the source data is in the graphics card memory then the card blitter
will render it quicker than you'd ever imagine! The problem is
when you want to do masked blitting (usually!?) it dosn't seem
possible to do it using on board data. As far as I know it's
only AmigaOS BitMaps and Screens that are stored in gfx card memory
so theres a problem trying to create a 1plane mask which is what all
the graphics.library masked blitting finctions need.

The most common rendering method for gfx cards is to render the
display in fast mem and then dump it to the gfx card. The actual
dumping proccess is fairly slow depending on what bus you're
using. I have a Zorro2 bus and it's slow. Zorro3 is more common
and much faster. The new PPC BVision cards will eliminate this
problem by bringing the GFX card and the cpu together. The whole
business of rendering in chunky fast mem means you'll see massive
speedups with faster cpu's. As time goes on it becomes more
important to go with this approach.

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

"Fifty pounds - a small price to pay for the gift
of a fully functioning body that works properly."
-- Brass Eye




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.247" "Re[2]: cgx double buffering (what is Viewtype?)"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 06 Mar 1998 02:33:54 +0100
Subject: Re[2]: cgx double buffering (what is Viewtype?)

Hi Steven,
 
> Some time ago, Paul Burkey explained his double buffering
> technique- I think there was pointer to some type 
> caled .Viewtype, could somebody please give the definition
> of this type.

The type is .ViewPort and it's defined in amigalibs.res
if you really need to know the structure then here it is:

NEWTYPE.ViewPort
  *_Next.ViewPort
  *ColorMap.ColorMap ; table of colors for this viewport
                     ; if this is nil, MakeVPort assumes default values
  *DspIns.CopList    ; user by MakeView()
  *SprIns.CopList    ; used by sprite stuff
  *ClrIns.CopList    ; used by sprite stuff
  *UCopIns.UCopList  ; User copper list
  DWidth.w
  DHeight.w
  DxOffset.w
  DyOffset.w
  Modes.w
  SpritePriorities.b ; used by makevp
  ExtendedModes.b
  *RasInfo.RasInfo
End NEWTYPE

Okay so obviously you'd need to know the structures:

.ColorMap
.CopList
.UCopList
.RasInfo

which in turn would require the structures:

.CopIns
.ViewPortExtra
.TagItem
.PaletteExtra

which would require more structures that would require more....
It makes you glad to have amigalibs.res ready made for you! :)

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

"The car's a bitch... you're the queen and i like it."
-- Brass Eye




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.248" "Re: Re[2]: C source convertor?"
