@NODE "Mail.251" "Re[2]: BlitzPPC?"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 10 Mar 1998 22:25:39 +0100
Subject: Re[2]: BlitzPPC?

Hi Andreas,

>  Well first I  would like to say that if this
> project is made into reality, then blitz will
> become a very popular  developer language for
> the ppc cards. The reason for this is that it
> will be the only basic language  that has ppc
> support (eat dust am*s...).

It would be funny if AMOS got PPC support first though ;)

> (3) Have a plugin based  compiler system. The
>     compiler would use  plugin  file for both
>     cpus. The  plugin  file  would  hold  all
>     the compiler DATA for  the diffrent cpus.
>     And the main compiler program  would  get
>     the DATA it  need from  the plugin  file.

Doesn't all this get a bit messy when you come to 3rd party libs.
What is an ideal way to allow 3rd party developers to supply
libraries with multiple cpu support. Don't forget the finer details
of Steven Dobbs' suggstion where not only would there be 68k
compile and PPC compile but also FPU, 000, 020 options etc.

Maybe an updated + backward compatable BlitzLib format would
be good where for example the RIGFXLib.obj could have 000, 020
and PPC versions of all functions. At the same time, the user
could also have a copy of ElmoreDosLib.obj that contained only
the standard 68000 code. New libs could arive with only PPC code
in them. Then all you have to do is update the compiler to deal
with the different target cpu's.

Of course an update of the compiler that stops it from including
the whole lib even if it only needs 1 command would be even more
important if the lib contains PPC and 020 code.

> I  know  for  a  fact  that that
> solution is only a  short term  solution. And
> with short term I mean for the next 2-3 years
> (could   be   abit  longer, depends  on  many
> diffrent factors).

The success of OS3.5 is one rather large factor, but I prefer not
to dwell on the complexities of the Amigas ambiguous future
which is why I unsubscribed from the ICOA mailing list. I prefer
to keep my blindfold on and fingers crossed :)

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

"Pick-me-up distilled from dead gymnasts."
-- On the Hour




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.252" "Re[2]: Blitz Committee"
From: Eoghann Irving <eoghann@thenet.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 02:40:47 +0100
Subject: Re[2]: Blitz Committee

Hi :)

On 18-Mar-98, Alexander Wingrove wrote:
> On 17-Mar-98, Andreas H=E5kansson wrote:
> <snip##>
>##> Yes we should start designing a webpage for this committee.  I  can
>##> do  the  html  code,  but  I think we should find a really good gfx
>##> artist that can design the gfx for the page, since we will  need  a
>##> professional looking site, if anyone is going to take us seriously.

> I would also be happy to offer my services for html writing and page
> design. You are right that we need a professional-looking site though t=
o
> show our commitment.

Might I suggest that the initial site could be on geocities (currently
giving 3MB I think).  If it proves a big success we can always look at th=
e
possibility of hosting elsewhere.

Features (amongst others):

1) A comprehensive link directory for Blitz pages
2) The Blitz FAQ (expanded)
3) Information on 3rd party libraries
4) Links to every peice of Blitz code on aminet.
5) The Blitz Manual (If you recall a number of us discussed this concept
   some time ago)
#
> It is important that the board members have the time and commitment to
> handle the task of being in charge.

Yes, but my feeling is that for the initial setup phase we shouldn't worr=
y
about the structure of the organisation.  Get the page up and some
resources on it. Then work out the structure of the Committee itself.

> Therefore, I think the best way of starting this off would be for those=

> who are able to do the job to submit an application for board membershi=
p.
> We then need to determine how many board members we want and see if we
> have a short-fall or not. Only if we have too many applicants will we
> need to vote.

This I think should come once we have an initial web site. Democracy is
good but slow.

> Another point would be a name for this commitee. Just "The Blitz
> Commitee" sounds a little bit naff. Something more like "The Advanced
> Blitz Organisation" would seem better. Does anyone else have some ideas=
?

CABB

Comitee for the Advancement of Blitz Basic. ;)

I would also like to tag another thing onto this while everyone is
enthusiastic.

I just wrote to Steve Matty about our ideas for talking to ACID and
Guildhall Leisure etc.

If he's interested (and he may not be).  I think that this is the site
which should host the petition etc.

-- =


Have fun,

Eoghann

