@NODE "Mail.264" "Re: remove!"
          Tue, 31 Mar 1998 09:23:35 -0600
From: "Donovan Reeve" <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 1998 10:21:26 +0500
Subject: Re: remove!

On 31-Mar-98, Berhan Karag=F6z flashed:
>Is there a way of checking what e-mails are there in the list so I can
>enter a CORRECT e-mail addy so to remove myself?

  I am sorry I don't know the answer to that question, but I DO know
what you are going to have to do if you find that out.  Read carefully.
(I have sympathised with your plight but didn't know what the problem
was untill it happened to me.)

  EVERYBODY PAY ATTENTION IF YOU DON'T WANT TO WIND UP SOMETIME WITH THE
SAME PROBLEM AS BERHAN HAS!!!


  I just changed ISP servers and wound up with the same trouble as Berhan=
=2E

  Here is the problem: If you change email addresses you MUST unsubscribe=

FROM YOUR OLD EMAIL ADDRESS and wait for the confirmation email from the
automatic list program to come TO YOUR OLD EMAIL ADDRESS (usually only
about 1 minuet after you send the unsubscribe email).  Then you must send=

an empty reply to the address on the confirmation email FROM YOUR OLD
EMAIL ADDRESS.  The auto-list program will then send another email TO
YOUR OLD EMAIL ADDRESS telling you that you have been removed from the
Blitz list.

  If you try to unsubscribe from any email address other than the one you=

are trying to unsubscribe IT WILL NOT WORK.  This is obviously to prevent=

people from unsubscribing sombody else which could be a real mess.

  I would guess that the same holds true for subscribing but I have not
tried it.
  I was fortunate in that when I tried to unsubscribe from my new email
address and it didn't work, I could still go back to my old address and
unsubscribe from there as I had not shut it down yet ( to avoid missing
any posts to this list).  That overlap saved me from winding up in the
same boat as Berhan.


   Berhan,
  If you find out what address is forwarding you the Blitz list, you will=

have to unsubscribe from there or fake it.

  There is a way to fool who or whatever is on the other end as to where
your message is coming from but I don't know how, I only know it is possi=
ble.
  If you can email from wherever you subscribed from OR fool the list-
maintainance program into thinking you did, then the confirmation message=

will be forwarded to you.  You can then reply to it either from the real
address or again fool it into thinking you have.  You should then recieve=

the message saying that you have been unsubscribed.

  Note:  If someone has hacked you into having Blitz list forwarded to yo=
u
(for a joke or to be mean?)  this will still work IF you can find out wha=
t
address the Blitz -list is sending to (which is forwarding it to you) and=

IF you can either physically go to that place and unsubscribe from there
or find out how to fool the Blitz-list maintainance program into thinking=

that you unsubscribed from there.

  (whew)

  I wish you success

     Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)









@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.265" "Re: remove!"
          Tue, 31 Mar 1998 09:48:28 -0600
From: "Donovan Reeve" <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 1998 10:46:19 +0500
Subject: Re: remove!

On 31-Mar-98, Berhan Karag=F6z flashed:
>Is there a way of checking what e-mails are there in the list so I can
>enter a CORRECT e-mail addy so to remove myself?

  Sorry for bugging you again, but I just wanted to be sure you
remembered when you unsubscribe from whatever address is forwarding
Blitz-list to you that you replace the @ in the email address with =3D
or it will say there is no such address.

  The address you are sending to must NOT be:

        blitz-list-unsubscribe-berhan@blaBla.com@netsoc.ucd.ie
   will NOT work.

  Instead it must be:

        blitz-list-unsubscribe-berhan=3Dblabla.com@netsoc.ucd.ie


    In other words:

          your email address   berhan@blabla.com

          change to            berhan=3Dblabla.com

     within the address you are emailing the to for unsubscribing.


   Good luck!

     Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.web)






@ENDNODE
