@NODE "Mail.285" "Re: Proper use of Put,Get,Fields"
From: Matt Daniels <mattd@underused.u-net.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 22:20:36 -0000
Subject: Re: Proper use of Put,Get,Fields

Hi Tommi, On 19-Mar-98 you wrote...

>Hi
>How does the Put,Get and Fields commands actually work.
>Im trying to save and load some newtypes like this

>for b=0 to 35
>   usepath Star(b).SSys
>   fields 0,\LocX,\LocY,\Name
>   Put 0,0
>   for B=0 to 9
>     usepath Star(b)\NavP[B]
>     fields 0,\NLocX,\NLocY,\NType
>     Put 0,0
>   next B
>next b

>It writes something to disk , but when i try to
>load them the same way (ofcourse using Get instead of Put),
>it loads something but all the values and everything is lost
>somewhere. So how does those commands work?

I don't know how to use these commands, but for writing
a sequence of newtypes this code works well for me.

--

#FILE = 0            
#RECLEN = 4 ; Size of our Newtype in bytes
            ; (eg our newtype contains x.b, y.b and z.w in that order)
file$ = "ourfile.bin"

;set up a variable eg "var" then save
If WriteFile(#FILE,file$) = True ; if we can open our file for writing
   WriteMem #FILE, &var\x, #RECLEN ; write a variable of our newtype
EndIF

CloseFile #FILE
;initialise a variable "varb" of the same type
If ReadFile(#FILE,file$) = True ; if we can open our file for reading
   ReadMem #FILE, &varb\x, #RECLEN ; read into a variable of our newtype
Endif
;"varb" will now be the same as "var"
CloseFile #FILE

--

You can always open your files with a hex editor to make sure that the
right data was written.

Thanks
-- 
Matt Daniels
mattd@underused.u-net.com



@ENDNODE
