@NODE "Mail.295" "Re: PPC Version of Blitzy"
Subject: Re: PPC Version of Blitzy
Date: Fri, 20 Mar 1998 10:41:09 +0000 (GMT)
From: "Adam Lounds" <adaml@tcp.net.uk>

> 
> On 19-Mar-98, Claus Herrmann wrote:
> 
> ASM thingy trashed
> 
> > as you see, a risc processor cant read or wirte directly to the RAM. it=
> > has to be done with the store unit of the processor.
> > also there is a limit of jumping to certain routines.. 64Kb can a jump =
> > only take. jumping from 0 to 1Mb has to be done through a special =
> > register. the jump register. and due to the fact, that you can only ent=
> er =
> > a value of maximum $5fff, you need about 4-6 commands for this purpose.=
> 
> > example: 68K code
> 
> > jsr$10000000
> 
> > ppc code:
> 
> > addis d0,0,$1000# load d0 with $1000
> > ori   d0,d0,$0000       # shift d0 and load $0000
> > mtspr d0,lr             # move to link register $1000 0000
> > bclr  0b10100,0         # jump to adress in link register !
> 
> Well here is the other story you have to make the RTS command by yourself=
> 
> too. So you first before jump you have to write the return address
> somewhere and then when the 68k is executing the RTS PPC have to do anoth=
> er
> jump to the given address...

Ok. So PPC is slow. Let's not bother. 

With 32 32bit registers, a lot of ram-writing won't be necessary.
Oh, and 32 64bit Floating point registers as well.

Oh, and according to the spec sheets, the 604e:
* Completes up to 4 instructions plus 1 store and 1 branch per cycle 
* Hardware controlled load-multiple and store-multiple registers and 
byte strings 

So jumps take a few instructions? So what! It's faster than a very
(very - ed) fast thing. No matter what processor we switched to, 
some degree of change would have to be made in the way we code. 

-- 
