@NODE "Mail.297" "PPC Version of Blitz"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 10:45:44 +0100
Subject: PPC Version of Blitz


>Hi guys. I am writing this new letter for  easier  responding  to
>the  matter  : PPC Version of Blitz. Many people here on the list
>are speaking of a PPCBlitz Version. Now  to  make  things  a  bit
>clear,  let  me  explain you how the blitz compiler does his job.
>First of all you  got  all  those  support  libraries  (acid.lib,
>RWElibs  and so on) all these libs are precompiled 68K code. when
>the compiler detects a command which is from one lib,  he  linkes
>the  whole  lib (with all the commands even you used only one) to
>you code.

Yep, pretty sure everyone knew this, if not then now they do :-)

>now to the problem. when we design a new  blitzppc  compiler  all
>those  libs  from  RWE and ACID have to be RECOMPILED to the PPC.
>this would be easy, if those libs were in c. but they are not :((
>most   of   the   libs   are   written  in  assembler...  in  68k
>assembler.....now you see the problem.. so if there will be  ever
>a  ppcblitz, it has to be done completly new, since the structure
>of the PPC is  also  completly  different.  thats  why  i  plead,
>writing a new language.

Well I'm pretty sure you've read that a "new  language"  is  being
planned,  since  90%  of  all the mail thats been sent to the list
these last few days has been about just that. The way is going  to
be done, is to write a replacment compiler, with new features that
the present compiler doesnt have, so that the current blitz  users
will  start  using  it. This compiler will be 100% campatible with
the current compiler, but  have  those  extra  features  that  the
presnt   compiler   doesnt.  Now  once  people  start  using  this
replacment compiler, we have taken the first, and  most  important
step  towards  the  new  language.  Now as the compiler enters new
phases (phase1 to phase6 is  planned,  but  not  what  each  phase
should  include, only that when phase6 is reached the new language
should be born), it will offer more and more features,  that  will
make  it  move further away from blitz (still being as easy to use
as blit, but offer much more power).

Now one of the new features  for  the  compiler,  which  could  be
implemented  in  lets say phase2 or 3, could be the possibility to
use 3rd party libs, thats been written in C.  Now  once  this  has
been  implemented,  the  new  language will have taken a huge step
towards the possibility to give it ppc support. Yes I know that to
start of with, there will be very few ppc libs for blitz, but once
there is a possibility to use ppc from blitz (or should I say  the
new  language,  in  one  of it's transformation statges), I'm sure
that there will start to appear ppc libs for it.

We could even setup a workgroup, that work with  making  ppc  libs
for   the  new  language,  but  this  wont  be  needed  until  the
possibility to use C compiled lib, with the new  compiler,  and  a
good  ppc support base has been implemented into the new compiler.
But once this has been done, such a workgroup could be formed.

You seem to know much about this, and if you also should happen to
program in Assembler, then I  would like for you to be on   the *New*
*Compiler* workgroup. Let me know if your intrested.

designing  the  language,  and  offering  the  old   blitzers   a
possibility  to  use  new  feature  and  commands  through a lib.
(restricted of course, due to the fact it is something  completly
different)

Look above.

>so we should get up some groups.

Look above

>and for the "new" language, i could also offer a mailing list.

This would be great. Any chance of offering more the  one  mailing
list further on? Since each workgroup could do with a mailing list
of thier own.

 ByE!













@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.298" "Re: PPC Version of Blitz"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 12:29:29 +0100
Subject: Re: PPC Version of Blitz


>but fact is, that you cant mix binary froms..you  cant  use  a  3rd
>party  ppc  lib  from  a  68K  side.  so  you cant mix up those two
>structures.. :( so we have here two different compilers .. one  for
>the  ppc  which  has to be rewritten and one for the 68k side. both
>being completly the same. so you need one workgroup who  designs  a
>completly new compiler for the ppc blitz which is compatible to the
>current one, and one team enhancing the current compiler..  i  dont
>think   this  is  a  good  solution.  iw  ould  say,  creating  two
>teams/groups.  one  group  enhancing  the  old  compiler  and   one
>team/group  designing  something  new for the ppc which has all the
>features of the blitz 68k compiler.

Your quite right that you cant mix binary forms, and that  you  cant
use a 3rd party ppc lib from the 68k side. The option of writing two
diffrent compilers has been disscused before. But  I  feel  that  we
should  try to solve this problem somehow, so that it has the option
of generating code for both cpu's, where you choose  which  cpu  you
want  to  generat the code from in the Compiler Options menu. Having
two teams would be very hard. I think we can find a good solution on
how to solve this. Steve Matty from Red When Excited might have some
ideas on this. The whole idea of  the  new  compiler  was  to  start
offering new features that the present complier doesn't support, and
the possibility to generate ppc native code would be the best  move,
to  make  people  start using, as would be to solve the problem that
blitz generates rather large exefiles (more about this later in  the
mail).  Remember that the compiler doesn't have to be a single file,
it could very well be written so that it can be adapted to new cpu's
very  easely, with the help of somekind of cpu data system, that the
compiler would interpet. So I think we  should  try  to  solve  this
problem,  and  tyr not to have to make a two compiler solution. Look
at AM*S it planning to get PPC support, and I dont think  they  will
make  two  versions  of  it  (a  68k version and a ppc version). The
beauty of having a compiler which can generat code for both cpus, is
that  people  can generate code for ppc's even though they dont have
one (I know this would require ppc version of the  3rd  party  libs,
but it can be done, the biggest problem is the compiler).

The problem with large exe files is also something that needs to  be
looked  into.  I  think  this could be solved by making the compiler
accept 3rd party libs thats been compiled in C (automaticly makes it
easyer  to  make the compiler make ppc code as well, and all new 3rd
party libs thats written in C, could easely be compiled as ppc  libs
as  well.).  Remember  that we will try to set somekind of standards
for the new language (and current blitz,  WITH  the  new  compiler).
This means that once the C library solution has been implemented, it
wont be hard to convince people to compile a ppc  version  of  thier
libs, even if they dont have any need for it them self.

>yeah, but stated above.. you cant mix 68k code with ppc code. so  a
>completely different compiler has to be written..

Look above.

>i am interested and i produce ppc asm code,  but  i  have  no  idea
>about  programming a compiler.. i can produce some sort of routines
>which are needed, but a whole compiler :)

Thats why Steve Matty's expertiase come  in  handy.  Since  RWE  has
updated  the  present  compiler,  he  should  have knowlage of how a
compiler should be structured.

>could be done ... will be no problem....

This is extremly good. Just look what we can acheiv when we  combind
our forces. Microsoft watch and learn.

 ByE!



