@NODE "Mail.299" "Re: PPC Version of Blitz"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 18:53:50 +0100
Subject: Re: PPC Version of Blitz


>ok.. doing one compiler would be possible, but what do you do when
>the  person  who wants to compile his programm and uses as example
>"screen", but the 3rd library only exist as a 68K routine.. should
>the  compiler  say:  ok guy.. you lost ?? i mean having one or two
>compiler is irrelevant. because  haveing  two  compilers  and  one
>interface will also look as one compiler to the user ? :))

Well it's not irrelevant at all, infact it plays a  very  important
role  in  what  we  are planning to do. As I've stated before, that
what we are trying to do, is slowly try to morph the current  blitz
into  the New Language (NL from here on). Now the way we want to do
this, is to in phase  introduce  new  features,  that  the  present
compiler  doesn't support, meaning that if people want to use them,
they will have to use the replacement  compiler.  The  second  they
install  the replacment compiler, and start to use it, then they've
actually moved from blitz to the  NL  (remember  that  we  are  not
updating  any  present blitz things, but making something completly
new. And ACID/GUILDHALL cant do shit about it, since it's  actually
a NL that just happens to support blitz as well, but it's important
to include new features, otherwise it wont be a NL).

Now lets say we make two diffrent compilers. This would  mean  that
the  68k  version,  would be in the morphing process, right. Now at
the same time we release the ppc version as well. This wont  be  in
the  morphing  phases, since it wont be compatible with the present
blitz at all. Now already we have made the NL, but  sofar  it  only
has ppc support, and no 68k support, and it wont have until the 68k
version catches up with the ppc  version  (remember  that  the  68k
version  would  have to go threw the six diffrent phases, before it
will have morphed into the NL,  but  the  ppc  version  would  jump
straight  to  phase6.  Not a very smart move. Thats why impementing
the ppc support into the replacement compiler, as well as  the  68k
side  of it, will make them move side by side. This is as I see it,
a must, and it will help get the users of present blitz start using
the replacement compiler.

As for the 3rd party libs. In your example you brought up,  that  a
user  wanted  to compile a ppc version of his program, but used the
screen command, that only existed as a 68k lib. This can be  solved
in  a  very easy way. Since we'r already talking about changing the
3rd party lib header, so that the compiler will know that  the  lib
is  a  "new  lib" (written for the replacement compiler, and at the
sametime for the NL), we could add a cpu  flag  in  the  header  as
well. All 68k libs could have the cpu flag set to 68000 and the ppc
libs could have it set to PPC (I know it explained in a  lame  way,
but  I  think you understand what I mean). And when you compile the
code, the compiler would scan threw the code, to check if any  libs
that  wont  work  with the choosen compiler mode (remeber you would
have to select what cpu you want to generate your code to,  in  the
compiler options). Eg, lets say you want to generate ppc code, then
a flag will be set (perhaps something like COMPILERMODE=3DPPC),  then
the  compiler  would  check  the  lib header for the libs that each
command comes from, and check if the lib header is the same as  the
COMPILERMODE  flag, if not, then return an error like "The *Screen*
command, is only avalible in 68k compiler mode). Same goes for  the
other way around.

Now perhaps this is not what you ment, maybe you  ment  that  there
was  no  ppc  lib  that  had  the  equivelant command to the screen
command, and therefor the user wont be able to make a ppc  program,
that  opens a screen. Well maybe we havn't said this in plain text,
but when the ppc support is introduced, we must of  course  already
have  standard  libs, into ppc libs (an ppc version of the acidlibs
etc, we cant convert all the 3rd party libs as well, since it would
be  a  to  big  job.  Perhaps  after  the  standard  libs  has been
converted, that workgroup, could continue to write new libs,  usinf
the  newlib structure, and make both 68k and ppc version). You have
to agree with me that this is how it must be, if we  want  to  make
this project work.

>have a look at SAS/C .. Steve Krueger also  uses  two  compilers..
>the original SC and the SCPPC :/

Yes, but remember that he already had a  language  to  make  a  ppc
compiler to, we dont until phase6 has been reached. If we had, then
we could to just like Steve Krueger, and make two compilers.

>we could change the header  of  the  3rd  libs.  if  the  compiler
>detects  the new header format, he knows, that this library is one
>of a newer kind, where he can take single  commands  from  without
>linking  the whole lib into. other thingy would be, if we create a
>language, with which you could create your own  3rd  libraries  to
>compile..  ??  then you dont need to compile your new library to c
>and then to NBlitz (NewBlitz). this would be very  interesting  to
>many  users/programmers. putting their code into a usefull library
>(other language do the same.. like c).

First we should add the possibility to write libs in  C,  and  make
teh  lib  format, so that the compiler only incuded the commands it
needed into the exe file, and not  the  whole  lib.  When  this  is
finsihed,  then  making  an  integrated lib maker, that chould make
libs of NL code.

just tell me the amount and the names of the mailinglists !

Well I guess we would need one for each workgroup,  at  the  moment
there  are  5.  And they should be called after the workgroup name.
But we shouldn't setup the workgroup ml's until everything has been
planned. But we could setup a mailing list for the project it self,
where we can dissucs the things we are talking about on this  list,
since  if  you do think about it, the blitz mailing list wasn't put
up to have these kind of disscussions on it, but it  was  setup  so
that  people  could get help with programing problems. So we should
move the new language disscussion on to a list of  it's  own.  Once
the  whole "Blitz Committee" (really need a name), has been formed,
then we should make that list INVITE only, since  we  are  actually
talking  about  a  secret project, and we dont want outsiders (like
the people that develops amos again), to join and  rip  ideas  etc.
And  on  the  workgroup  ml's  oly  people that is in the workgroup
should be allowed on (and the blitz committee board if they want).

Ohh yeah, to all of you thats on the list, remember that everything
we have talked about is SECRET, and shouldnt leave this list. Doing
this could mean that people leeach of the solution  we  find  (once
again that could be the people thats developing amos).

 ByE!




