@NODE "Mail.300" "Re: PPC Version of Blitz"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 23:33:36 +1200
Subject: Re: PPC Version of Blitz

On 19-Mar-98, Claus Herrmann wrote:
 
>so if there will be ever a ppcblitz, it has to be done completly new, 
>since the structure of the PPC is also completly different.
>thats why i plead, writing a new language.

  How easy is it to port 68k assembler to PPC assembler? It might make
things easier in the beginning, as there are a lot of libs to rewrite in
PPC- just an idea, I've no idea how practical it would be.   
 
-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.301" "PPC Version of Blitz"
	Thu, 19 Mar 1998 10:24:45 +0100 (MET)
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 10:24:45 +0100 (MET)
From: Claus Herrmann <cyclone@rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>
Subject: PPC Version of Blitz

Hi guys. I am writing this new letter for easier responding to the matter 
: PPC Version of Blitz.
Many people here on the list are speaking of a PPCBlitz Version.
Now to make things a bit clear, let me explain you how the blitz compiler 
does his job.
First of all you got all those support libraries (acid.lib, RWElibs and 
so on) all these libs are precompiled 68K code.
when the compiler detects a command which is from one lib, he linkes the 
whole lib (with all the commands even you used only one) to you code.

now to the problem. when we design a new blitzppc compiler all those libs 
from RWE and ACID have to be RECOMPILED to the PPC. this would be easy, 
if those libs were in c. but they are not :(( most of the libs are 
written in assembler... in 68k assembler.....now you see the problem..

so if there will be ever a ppcblitz, it has to be done completly new, 
since the structure of the PPC is also completly different.
thats why i plead, writing a new language.

designing the language, and offering the old blitzers a possibility to 
use new feature and commands through a lib. (restricted of course, due to 
the fact it is something completly different)

so we should get up some groups.

and for the "new" language, i could also offer a mailing list.

Cheerio Claus

.-------------------------------------------.
| A4000 - Cyberstom PPC 604e 200 / 68060-66 |
| - Only phase5 makes this possible -:)     |
`-------------------------------------------'


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.302" "Re: PPC Version of Blitz"
	Thu, 19 Mar 1998 15:35:58 +0100 (MET)
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 15:35:58 +0100 (MET)
From: Claus Herrmann <cyclone@rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>
Subject: Re: PPC Version of Blitz

On Thu, 19 Mar 1998, Anton Reinauer wrote:

> On 19-Mar-98, Claus Herrmann wrote:
>  
> >so if there will be ever a ppcblitz, it has to be done completly new, 
> >since the structure of the PPC is also completly different.
> >thats why i plead, writing a new language.
> 
>   How easy is it to port 68k assembler to PPC assembler? It might make
> things easier in the beginning, as there are a lot of libs to rewrite in
> PPC- just an idea, I've no idea how practical it would be.   

it is completly different. the 68k is a cisc processor and you can do 
things like:

move.l $700,d0    # copy the contents of adress $700 to the register d0
move.l d0,$700    # copy register to $700
move.l $700,$1400 # copy long from $700 to $1400

in ppc assembler things have to be done different.

lhw    d0,$700    # load the register
shw    d0,0($700) # store the register

and to achieve the same as in the third line in ppc asm you have to do this:)

lhw    d0,$700    # read data
sthw   d0,0($1400)# and copy it back !

as you see, a risc processor cant read or wirte directly to the RAM. it 
has to be done with the store unit of the processor.
also there is a limit of jumping to certain routines.. 64Kb can a jump 
only take. jumping from 0 to 1Mb has to be done through a special 
register. the jump register. and due to the fact, that you can only enter 
a value of maximum $5fff, you need about 4-6 commands for this purpose.

example: 68K code

jsr	$10000000

ppc code:

addis d0,0,$1000	# load d0 with $1000
ori   d0,d0,$0000       # shift d0 and load $0000
mtspr d0,lr             # move to link register $1000 0000
bclr  0b10100,0         # jump to adress in link register !

so you see it is not so easy converting 68k code into ppc code.

cheerio !



@ENDNODE
