@NODE "Mail.305" "Re: PPC Version of Blitz"
From: "Julian Kinraid" <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
Subject: Re: PPC Version of Blitz
Date: Sat, 21 Mar 1998 10:57:52 +1200
	charset="iso-8859-1"

Hi all,

>Well it's not irrelevant at all, infact it plays a  very  important
>role  in  what  we  are planning to do. As I've stated before, that
>what we are trying to do, is slowly try to morph the current  blitz
>into  the New Language (NL from here on). Now the way we want to do
>this, is to in phase  introduce  new  features,  that  the  present
>compiler  doesn't support, meaning that if people want to use them,
>they will have to use the replacement  compiler.  The  second  they
>install  the replacment compiler, and start to use it, then they've
>actually moved from blitz to the  NL  (remember  that  we  are  not
>updating  any  present blitz things, but making something completly
>new. And ACID/GUILDHALL cant do shit about it, since it's  actually
>a NL that just happens to support blitz as well, but it's important
>to include new features, otherwise it wont be a NL).

Wouldn't we have to start from scratch though?  We couldn't use any of =
the Blitz code that Guildhall own, otherwise we would probably be =
breaking a copyright law.  Starting from scratch does have plusses =
though.

We could design it from the ground up and write it in a high level =
language.  We wouldn't have to worry about modifying the existing =
assembly source code to support new features, and Guildhall wouldn't be =
a problem.

Of course, the downside ... We would have to right a compiler.

>Now perhaps this is not what you ment, maybe you  ment  that  there
>was  no  ppc  lib  that  had  the  equivelant command to the screen
>command, and therefor the user wont be able to make a ppc  program,
>that  opens a screen. Well maybe we havn't said this in plain text,
>but when the ppc support is introduced, we must of  course  already
>have  standard  libs, into ppc libs (an ppc version of the acidlibs
>etc, we cant convert all the 3rd party libs as well, since it would
>be  a  to  big  job.  Perhaps  after  the  standard  libs  has been
>converted, that workgroup, could continue to write new libs,  usinf
>the  newlib structure, and make both 68k and ppc version). You have
>to agree with me that this is how it must be, if we  want  to  make
>this project work.

The only problem with making the libraries is time.  They won't be that =
hard to make (he says confidently :), because as long as someone knows =
the OS well, they could write a Screen/Window/whatever lib easily =
enough.  If the 'NL' supported Amiga object files (ie. what a linker =
uses to create an executable), the libs could be written in C, which =
would speed things up even more.  That would even make PPC support =
almost trivial for some libs.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid






