@NODE "Mail.310" "Re: Poke/Peek"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 1998 19:38:31 -0600
Subject: Re: Poke/Peek

Hi,

On 03-Mar-98, C.J.R.Jarvis wrote:
>Hello, there
>I sent in a request a few days ago on help with Poke peek, and I
>realise that myquestion was badly worded. My problem is not the usage of
>the comaands, but more that I have absolutely no concept of how to use
>memory location. I do not know how to find anything in memory, I do not
>know what the values mean - I know NOTHING.
>Say for instance I had 5 bitmaps in memory. Would I know how to
>find them? NO.
>Therefore I would like a tutorial from somewhere, or even help
>from people on the list, about the usage of ROM/RAM locations.

First, to find the location of a bitmap (or any other Blitz Object),
use the Addr command:

a = Addr BitMap(0)

will give you the location of Bitmap 0.

And if you look in your Blitzlibs: , you can find a file "bb2objtypes.bb".  In
here you will find descriptions of all the Blitz Objects.  Here is the one for
BitMaps:


NEWTYPE.bitmap       ;size=64
  _ebwidth.w[0]      ;00: for compatability.
  _linemod.w         ;00: value to get from one scanline to next.
  _height.w          ;02: currently pixel height - but open to commodore      
    ;'enhancement'.
  _depth.w           ;04: number of bitplanes.
  _pad.b[2]          ;06: nothing.
  _data.l[8]         ;08: actual bitplane pointers.
  _pad2.b[12]        ;40: zilch.
  _flags.w           ;0=normal bitmap, <0=interleaved.
  _bitplanemod.w     ;value to get from one bitplane to next. MAY BE 0!
  _xclip.w           ;pixel width for render clipping
  _yclip.w           ;pixel height for render clipping
  _cclip.w           ;number of colours available on bitmap ( = 2^_depth)
  _isreal.w          ;0=no bitmap here, <0=blitz created bitmap, >0=borrowed
End NEWTYPE

So, to determine the depth of BitMap 0:

dpth = Peek.w (Addr BitMap(0)+4)

I hope this helps a little...


                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
