@NODE "Mail.314" "Re: PictureViewer"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 11 Mar 1998 21:11:53 -0600
Subject: Re: PictureViewer

Hi Manfred,

On 11-Mar-98, Manfred Fessler wrote:
>Hiho !

>The is the first posting of a youngster who started to code
>with BB2.

>I have a Problem:
>I want to do  a pictureviewer in a OS-friendly way, sdomething
>"doubble bufferd" where one picture is displayed while a other
>one is loaded.
>First problem when I LOADBITMAP and COPYBITMAP
>to a WINDOWSBITMAP, the COPYBITMAP-command is to slow
>in need a way where it can=B4t be seen how the Bitmap comes to
>the window. I need to use a HAM8-Mode so it=B4s realy slow...
>Second all the Pictures have different sices, and i want them all
>centerd on the screen. Maybe someone haves a hint for me
>how to get this in the most easyest way.


I am not sure if this first method will work, as I haven't tried putting =
a
bitmap in anything but the front window, but try this:

scrnwidth=3D640        ;set to width of your screen
scrnheight=3D400       ;set to height of your screen
window 0 (make it scrnwidth wide, scrnheight high, etc)
window 1 (the same as window 0)
frontwin=3D1           ;window currently in front
backwin=3D0            ;window in back

repeat

  WindowToFront_ (frontwin)       ;puts picture in front =


  picname$=3D(whatever you do to determine the next picture to show)

  ILBMinfo picname$               ;gets size of picturre

  picwidth=3DILBMwidth

  picheight=3DILBMheight

  Free Bitmap 0                   ;get rid of old picture
 =

  Bitmap 0, (the size & depth of the picture)
  =

  windx=3Dscrnwidth/2-picwidth/2    ;centers picture horizontally
  =

  windy=3Dscrnheight/2-picheight/2  ;centers pic vertically
  =

  BitmapToWindow 0,backwin,0,0,windx,windy,picwidth,picheight
  =

  exchange frontwin,backwin

until (whatever you do to exit program)

This will always load the picture to the window that is in back, then pop=
 the
window to the front of the other one.  But as I said, I have never tried =
this,
so it may not be any faster, or might not work correctly at all.  I know =
the
next method does work.

I have done a similar code (which was used to show a title picture while =
the
program was loading) that makes a screen in the back of the display (so y=
ou
don't see it), loads a picture to the screen's bitmap, then pops this scr=
een
to the front.  You could do this using 2 screens rather than 2 windows, f=
or
double buffering.  This would also let you load pictures of different dep=
ths &
resolutions.

I don't know if either method works with a GFX card - maybe one of the GF=
X
card owners can help here.

                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.315" "Re: PictureViewer"
From: "Julian Kinraid" <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
Subject: Re: PictureViewer
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 21:35:09 +1200
	charset="iso-8859-1"

Hi Manfred,

>I have a Problem:
>I want to do  a pictureviewer in a OS-friendly way, sdomething
>"doubble bufferd" where one picture is displayed while a other
>one is loaded.
>First problem when I LOADBITMAP and COPYBITMAP
>to a WINDOWSBITMAP, the COPYBITMAP-command is to slow
>in need a way where it can=B4t be seen how the Bitmap comes to
>the window. I need to use a HAM8-Mode so it=B4s realy slow...
>Second all the Pictures have different sices, and i want them all
>centerd on the screen. Maybe someone haves a hint for me
>how to get this in the most easyest way.


If you use the ScreenTags and WindowTags commands, adding these tags can =
help with a picture viewer -

*bitmap_pointer.l =3D addr bitmap(0) ; or whatever bitmap you want to =
show

; Add these tags to the Screentags command

#SA_BitMap, *bitmap_pointer
#SA_BackFill, 1

; Windowtags
#WA_BackFill, 1

The #SA_BitMap tag will tell the OS that you want to open a screen that =
will show your bitmap.

When you open/close a window on a HAM8 screen, the window will probably =
take a while to draw itself.  It needs to do this when you will have =
more than one window open (eg. the workbench.)  With a picture viewer, =
your only going to open one window, so you can the OS that it doesn't =
need to redraw the window when you open/close it.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid



@ENDNODE
