@NODE "Mail.335" "Re: OS-friendly Graphics Rendering"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 1998 15:00:56 +0100
Subject: Re: OS-friendly Graphics Rendering

Hi James,

> The method I`m using is to render all my graphics to a bitmap, then use
> BitmapToWindow to display the results on my screen, using a borderless
> full-screen window. I think that this is a bit slow though?

Yes, it's very slow. It's actually the same method that I used
in the code I sent to the list yesterday.

> Can anyone suggest a better way of
> doing this? I can`t see how WBlitting straight to the window would work
> as I think this would look even worse as you see the screen redraw? Is
> there a way to do OS-friendly double buffering?

The code I sent to the list yesterday used double buffering. When
I started coding CyberGraphX stuff I discovered that CGFX din't
support OS double buffering so he only way to do it was to open
a screen that was twice as tall as the display. Then you render
to the hidden part and thn scroll th screen into view. That's
what my RTGHack code did. 

> As I understand it ScreensBitmap is a no-no if you want to run
> on graphics-cards?

oh yes, that a very big no-no. Another imposibile method is to
use ShowBitmap. So basicly there are two ways you can support
gfx cards with good results.

The First method is to render the display in a chunky buffer
which can be a simple 'Dim chunkybuffer.b(320,256)' where the
array contains all the pixels on the display. Then use whatever
code you need to render into it using pokes or whatever. Then
at the end of the rendering you simply call WritePixelArray8()
function which will dump the array onto the screen. This isn't
as hard as it sounds and with a collection of good functions
you can write any type of game with this, not only Doom clones. 
This method is many times faster than the render to bitmap
mthod you've played with becaue a> the chunky buffer can be in
fast ram an b> you're dealing in chunky modes so theres no
nasty planar2chunky conversion each frame.

Second method is slower but possibly easier to impliment. Basicly
you render direct to the screen (hidden part of the screen) using
a mixture of OS commands like BltBitmapRastPort() aka WBlit, 
WritePixel() aka WPlot or any method you can find to render
your shapes to the Screen/Window RastPort.

Both of the amove methods wouls take a LOT of extra work and
I wouldn't recomend it to anyone who doesn't have a GFX card.
Foundation would have been released last october if it wasn't
for me deciding to support GFX cards.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

