@NODE "Mail.337" "Re: OS game"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 19:09:28 -0600
Subject: Re: OS game

Hi Dave,

On 13-Mar-98, Dave wrote:
>Hi all

>  I have been trying to write a little game in OS mode but
>  I am disappointed with the speed. I am only bblitting 8
>  small (about 15*15) objects to screen and moving them around
>  also only 16 colour at the moment, I was going to increase
>  this to at least 64 but now I`m not sure.
>  I have tried using queues instead of buffers but it didn`t
>  really help.
>   Has anyone done interleaved bitmaps in OS ? I know the OS
>   will set them up but will I need to use different blitting
>   commands.
>   Anyone got any other advice for fast OS gfx? as it says in
>   devCD 60fps NTSC animation is possible.

>Thanks for any comments

>Dave

I think the slowdown is coming more from the calculations you are doing each
loop, rather than the actual BBlitting.  I wrote a card game in Amiga mode,
which uses 24*32* 3 bitplane card shapes.  These are much larger (2304 bytes)
than the 15*15 * 4 shapes you have (900 bytes), but even on a standard 68000 I
could move up to 16 cards at full speed in NTSC mode.

Here are a few ways to speed up calculations:

Use Words and Bytes rather than Quicks whenever possible.

Avoid multiply's and divide's if at all possible.  They are slow!

Use GoSubs instead of Functions for more speed.  In fact, for best speed try
to keep your main loop all in-line when possible.

Update your scores, etc. only when something changes - not each loop.

Try updating your shapes direction calculations in groups:
One frame, update the first 4, next frame the other 4, etc. On the frame they
are not being updated, just move them in the old direction, speed, etc.

I hope this helps a bit...  


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.338" "OS game"
          (Post.Office MTA v3.1.2 release (PO203-101c)
          for <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Fri, 13 Mar 1998 17:40:18 +0000
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 17:37:57 +0000
From: Dave <d.boaz@virgin.net>
Subject: OS game

Hi all

  I have been trying to write a little game in OS mode but
  I am disappointed with the speed. I am only bblitting 8
  small (about 15*15) objects to screen and moving them around
  also only 16 colour at the moment, I was going to increase
  this to at least 64 but now I`m not sure.
  I have tried using queues instead of buffers but it didn`t
  really help.
   Has anyone done interleaved bitmaps in OS ? I know the OS
   will set them up but will I need to use different blitting
   commands.
   Anyone got any other advice for fast OS gfx? as it says in
   devCD 60fps NTSC animation is possible.

Thanks for any comments

Dave


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.339" "Re: OS game"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 22:16:51 +0100
Subject: Re: OS game

Hi Dave,

>  Has anyone done interleaved bitmaps in OS ? I know the OS
>  will set them up but will I need to use different blitting
>  commands.
>  Anyone got any other advice for fast OS gfx? as it says in
>  devCD 60fps NTSC animation is possible.

When I started programming Foundation I used BLITZ mode but
then I tried the early versions out on an Amiga screen. When
I made some speed tests I couldn't for the life of me notice
any significant speed difference. In both cases you're only
blitting shapes to bitmaps using the exact same functions
so there's hardly any reason for a big difference in speed.

Do you have any comparison test between Amiga and Blitz
mode with the code you're running? What about screen mode?
It is just a regular mode or are you using a cpu hogging
DblNTSC or similar? What about Commodities or fast ram. If
you're running a *lot* of tasks or if you're using something
like Executive then you may see a change in speed. If you're
running short of fast ram then you're program may be forced
to execute in chip which is very slow. Sometimes a program
can be pushed into chip mem anyway.

So, I'd recomend you compile two versions of your test
program, one using blitz mode and the other using a
regular PAL or NTSC screen. Run them both and let us know
what sort of speed differences you're getting. I must say
I'm not very experienced at that type of comparison. I've
not touched Blitz mode for years.

Cheers,

Paul

