Total Connectivity Providers    | WWW: http://www.tcp.co.uk/


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.355" "Re: Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Alex Wingrove <awingrove@thenet.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 23:27:05 -0000
Subject: Re: Next Generation of Blitz

Hi all,

On 18-Mar-98, Andreas H=E5kansson wrote:
AH>*Phase1*
AH>In this phase a replacment to the current compiler should  be
AH>written.  New  features  should  be  implemented  as well, to
AH>attract the current blitz users to use it instead of the real
AH>blitz compiler. This complier should be written in such a way
AH>that it will be easy to develop it much  further.  Ones  this
AH>phase  is  finished,  then we will have take the biggest step
AH>towards making a "new" language. This complier shouldn't have
AH>to  a  ton  of  new features, only a few good ones, that will
AH>attract people to use it. One of these features could be  CLI
AH>Compiling, but it should also offer something new in codeing,
AH>so that if people use it, they will be able to  use  the  new
AH>things,  that the old blitz compiler doesnt support. I'm sure
AH>you guys out there have a few ideas to what  this  could  be,
AH>and  I'm  sure  Steve  has few things he would like to see as
AH>well (perhaps ppc compiling, since this  would  attract  many
AH>people to use the new compiler).

Some small but important ideas for the replacement compiler:

Ditch the tokenised source code. There is no reason why the source code
shouldn't be in standard ascii and this would make use of external
editors possible.

As suggested by Steve, include the ability to force predefinition of
variables. Keeping track of a large number of variables is a hassle,
especially when you go and make a spelling mistake in one. However, you
should be able to define these variables anywhere, as in C++.

Forward definition of Functions and Statements as well.

Unsigned variables!

Strings and Floats as constants would be nice.

AH>And like I said,  once  phase6  has  been  reached,  we  have
AH>succesfully morphed blitz into a new and powerfull language.

And by the time we got near to this stage, the state of the OS and other
standards will be much clearer and hopefully easier to implement.

AH>Now I also have  a  few  suggestions  to  how  to  keep  this
AH>organised, and very efficitan. The Blizt Committe (more about
AH>the name further down the mail), will be setup with a  board,
AH>and  workgroup,  that deal with diffrent things that needs to
AH>be done to reach phase6.

AH>Today I can think of 4 four workgroups, that sould  be  setup
AH>right from the start.

I can think of another workgroup. *Web* *Site*. Keeping this up to date
with developments, links and code would be a task in itself.

AH>*New* *Complier* *workgroup*

How many experienced Asm programmers do we have in the list to work in
this group?

AH>*OS* *Programming*

The new Blitz should be able to work directly with libraries and .fd
files to cut out the need to convert and assign library numbers. This
will open up many OS libraries to Blitz programmers and therefore good
documentation on using the OS will be essential.

AH>*New* *Editor*

Perhaps Editor should extend to a full Intergrated Devlopment Environment=

such as the StormC one ( or many of the Windows languages ).

AH>*New* *Manual*

Plenty of examples would be necessary for this and would be a good place
for lots of people to get involved even if they don't have the expertise
or time to join another workgroup.

AH>Now to something completly diffrent from workgroup. We need a
AH>few things to be decided. A name for the committee (since The
AH>Blitz Committee found lame), and we also need a good name for
AH>the  "new  language".

When Lava was going through it's name change to REBOL, I thought that
Magma would be quite a good name ( unless it is a rude word in another
language :). BTQ, please don't let us end up with a name like REBOL. It's=

has to be quite the blandest ( and unimaginitive ) name for a language
I've ever heard.

AH>I  think  people  should send in thier
AH>suggestions,  and  after  a  sertain  date,  we   close   the
AH>submission  of  entries, and vote which ones we sould use for
AH>the group and  language. We  also  need  people  to  submitt
AH>suggestions of people to be on the board, and in the diffrent
AH>workgroup, and just like with the group  and  language  name,
AH>will  will vote on the candidates. I think that people should
AH>write a short text on why the thinks the people  he  submitts
AH>as possible candidates is sutible for the task.

I would have thought it would be better to work the other way round.
Those people who feel they can join a work group put themselves forward
and are then either accepted or turned down. I for one do not know the
capabilities of many of the people on the list so am not in a position to=

nominate them.

AH>I  think  we  need  a spokes man (that can talk to the press,
AH>when it gets around to that), a workgroup super  visor  (That
AH>talks  to  the  Workgroup  leaders,  to  check  how things is
AH>comming along). Of course there  will  be  a  need  for  more
AH>position then this..Please make your suggestions.

Perhaps the whole PR bit could be part of the Web Site workgroup. This
way all info is going out of a central location/group.


Would an IRC discussion be a useful tool to get things going quickly? We
already have the #blitz channel on Dalnet, but choosing a time will be
the hardset part. How about 6pm-ish (GMT) on a Saturday or Sunday?

Bye,
Alex

