@NODE "Mail.356" "Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 20:40:26 +0100
Subject: Next Generation of Blitz


    Hiya Blitzers,

First I would like to say  that  the  kind  of  respons  I've
recieved  on  my  suggestions,  is  amazing.  The blitz basic
programers is a  small  family,  where  eberyone  cares  what
happen  to  eachother.  I've  never  seen a disscusion on the
list, where as many people has take part of, like this one.

Well I can impossible answer to every mail thats  been  about
the  Blitz  Committee.  So  far  I've recieved about 25 mails
today conserning the Blitz Committee. So what I decided to do
was to write this mail, which is the conclusions I have drawn
from those mails.

Many people the told me that they think that it would be best
not  to  try  to  get somekind of license to the blitz source
code, but to write a new language from scratch.  I  agree  to
this, but with a few remarks. I think we should leave the old
blitz source behind, and start on something new. it would  be
very  stupid  to  start from scratch though, since blitz is a
good starting base to start from. So what does it come  right
down  to,  regardless  of what language we are talking about?
The compiler thats what. The compiler is the language.

So my suggestion would be to develop the compiler  more,  and
include  new  features  to  it.  This  will be the first step
towards the "new language". I see this project as having many
phases.

*Phase1*
In this phase a replacment to the current compiler should  be
written.  New  features  should  be  implemented  as well, to
attract the current blitz users to use it instead of the real
blitz compiler. This complier should be written in such a way
that it will be easy to develop it much  further.  Ones  this
phase  is  finished,  then we will have take the biggest step
towards making a "new" language. This complier shouldn't have
to  a  ton  of  new features, only a few good ones, that will
attract people to use it. One of these features could be  CLI
Compiling, but it should also offer something new in codeing,
so that if people use it, they will be able to  use  the  new
things,  that the old blitz compiler doesnt support. I'm sure
you guys out there have a few ideas to what  this  could  be,
and  I'm  sure  Steve  has few things he would like to see as
well (perhaps ppc compiling, since this  would  attract  many
people to use the new compiler).

*Phase2* - *Phase5*
Keep adding new support to things that the old blitz compiler
doesnt support (and never will, since who will update it?).

*Phase6*
By now, we should have moved away from the old blitz  system,
quite  alot  (and  most likely have gotten a VERY big part of
the blitz coders along with us), and are ready for  the  main
phase,  where  the  announcement  of  the "new language" will
happen. In this phase, the more improved  compiler,  will  be
released  in  a  package  with  a  new  editor,  and many new
libraries, and what  ever  we  decide  to  add  to  the  "new
languge".  By  now,  the library system has evolved in such a
way, that the new libs wont work with "old blitz",  since  it
will use a old and out of date library system.

And like I said,  once  phase6  has  been  reached,  we  have
succesfully morphed blitz into a new and powerfull language.

Now I also have  a  few  suggestions  to  how  to  keep  this
organised, and very efficitan. The Blizt Committe (more about
the name further down the mail), will be setup with a  board,
and  workgroup,  that deal with diffrent things that needs to
be done to reach phase6.

Today I can think of 4 four workgroups, that sould  be  setup
right from the start.

*New* *Complier* *workgroup*
This workgroup would be the ones that developed the the first
version of the "new compiler", that I talked about in phase1.
They will also be in charge of setting up the  new  standards
that  the  "new language" should have, and write the compiler
in such a way, that they will be easy  to  add,  as  we  more
further  away from "old blitz". I suggest that Steve Matty is
choosen as Workgroup Leader  in  this  workgroup,  since  hes
already  help write patches etc for the present compiler, and
should have much  knowlage  about this. This  workgroup  will
need people with good ASM skills, and good knowlage about the
amiga system.

*OS* *Programming*
This workgroup would work with the suggestion Paul Burkey has
about  writing  blitz adapted "autodocs" for the OS libs etc.
This will be usefull for both the "old blitz" and "new blitz"
(or  perhaps  "new  blitz"  will support the OS libs, by this
workgroup will still be usefull to help attract new users etc
to  the  current  state  of blitz basic). I suggest that Paul
Burkey is choosen as  Workgroup  Leader  in  this  workgroup,
since he has extended knowlage of using OS calls from blitz.

*New* *Editor*
This workgroup would work with writing a new (and actually  a
good)  editor  that will support the "old blitz", but also be
written in such a way, so that it can easely  be  adapted  to
support the new features etc, that the compiler will support,
as it moves toward phase6.

*New* *Manual*
This workgroup would be in charge of making a new manual  for
the  current  version  of  blitz  basic.  They would also add
everynew  function  thats  added   to   the   compiler,   and
documentation  for  every new lib that gets created threw the
"Blitz Committee", to that manual. It  sould  be  written  in
such a way, that you can print it out on paper, and volia you
have a new manual. The old design of  the  manual  is  pretty
good,  but the contents is crapp. I know someone on this list
already has converted  the  current  manual  into  PostScript
format,  which  is  a  big  step  for this workgroup. If that
person wants to share his work with  the  "Blitz  Committee",
then  I  suggest  we  give him the Workgroup Leader ststus of
this workgroup.

Now to something completly diffrent from workgroup. We need a
few things to be decided. A name for the committee (since The
Blitz Committee found lame), and we also need a good name for
the  "new  language".  I  think  people  should send in thier
suggestions,  and  after  a  sertain  date,  we   close   the
submission  of  entries, and vote which ones we sould use for
the group and  language.  We  also  need  people  to  submitt
suggestions of people to be on the board, and in the diffrent
workgroup, and just like with the group  and  language  name,
will  will vote on the candidates. I think that people should
write a short text on why the thinks the people  he  submitts
as possible candidates is sutible for the task.

Well this is only my thought about whats been suggested. This
doesnt mean it will be like this, but it's a damn good start.
We also need to decide what positions the group should  have.
I  think  we  need  a spokes man (that can talk to the press,
when it gets around to that), a workgroup super  visor  (That
