  The point here really, is that we're assuming that the Amiga will take
off again- then it would be worth putting the effort in- a calculated
risk I know, but one worth taking. 
  I have to agree with Dave, just purely from a practical basis, having
some monetary reward coming in, will keep the language alive, as it
keeps the incentive to upgrade the language on a long-term basis. Also
if the language gets ported to PC/Mac (rewriting the language from
scratch in say C, would make this much easier), substantial money could
be made in the future. Without that financial incentive, a PC or Mac
version is much less likely to be made! 

  But I like your other suggestions :-)

 Oh, and please, please if we make a new language can we have the
default variable type .w not .q :-)
 
