@NODE "Mail.365" "Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 20 Mar 1998 16:53:40 -0600
Subject: Next Generation of Blitz 

Hi Everybody,

Ok, from the past weeks postings I see the following points have been
discussed - please correct me if I am wrong on any of these:

* PPC support requires a different compiler than 68000 code.

* Guildhall owns the rights to Blitz, which at the present time they are
unwilling to give up.

- But what is it they own?

* RWE owns the rights to SuperTed.
* RWE owns the right to BSS (I think - or does Guildhall own this too?)
* most (all?) of the 3rd party libs are freely distributable (check dev/basic)
* NO ONE owns the rights to a PPC BLITZ compiler, as it doesn't yet exist

So, it looks to me like they own:

* the Blitz 68000 compiler
* the name Blitz Basic
* the original Ted editor
* the copyright to the existing manual

In other words, they really only own Blitz circa version 1.6 or so...

So, I would suggest:

* For now, forget about the 68000 compiler re-write.  Instead, those of you
who are capable of this type of programming should put your efforts towards
the PPC compiler.

* Create a new version of SuperTed which can link with both the 68000 compiler
as it does now, and also the new PPC compiler.  And also incorporate many of
the suggested improvements that don't depend on alterations to the compiler
itself.

* Work on the new manual (keep in mind that we CAN NOT duplicate parts of the
existing manual, this must be all re-written.)

* Also Paul's "Blitz-Autodocs" is a much needed improvement.

Once this is all accomplished, WE would own most of the "Blitz" system - at
this point, we are in a much better bargaining position with Guildhall - what
they own is now (from a commercial standpoint) worthless and obsolete without
our parts.
And we have proven that we are capable of doing the rest, so they may be much
more willing to give us the rights to the compiler.  If not, this is the time
to consider doing our own 68000 compiler from scratch.



                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
