@NODE "Mail.370" "Re: Next Generation of Blitz"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 13:06:41 +0500
Subject: Re: Next Generation of Blitz

On 19-Mar-98, Alex Wingrove flashed:
>Some small but important ideas for the replacement compiler:

>Ditch the tokenised source code. There is no reason why the source code
>shouldn't be in standard ascii and this would make use of external
>editors possible.

  Yes!

>As suggested by Steve, include the ability to force predefinition of
>variables. Keeping track of a large number of variables is a hassle,
>especially when you go and make a spelling mistake in one. However, you
>should be able to define these variables anywhere, as in C++.

  If a special editor was designed it could have some special features
to facilitate the work of programers both experianced and new.  This
wouldn't preclude the use of other editors, they just wouldn't have the
special help features available.
  One thing came to mind as a result of the above comments.  Why not
have hotkeys to aid the user.
  Say the editor was set up so you could have several options for how
to deal with variables.  For those who like help in avoiding errors an
option could be turned on which would cause the editor to check each line
for text which was not a command, statement, perameter or comment each
time a line was exited by moving the curser or hitting return.  This text
would be then checked against the list of declared variables.  If it was
not a declared variable a requester would come up giving the user several
options.  The user could choose to have it declaired as a variable if
that was the intent.  The user could choose to correct the line if the
text was in error.  The user could kick in his screen and stomp on his
keyboard. #;^)>

  This is just one small idea of the type of online help I would like to
see incorporated in any upgrade or new language.  Care would have to be
taken however that online help be controllable by the user and not trap,
confuse or irritate the user.  We don't want any help like the Mac error
routines! "An error has occured in the process 'unidentified' because an
error has occured"  #%^6>


     later,
              Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)





@ENDNODE
