>editor, but personally I LIKE SuperTed.  I for one would not want to be
>without it - the hilighting of commands, the direct compiling and de-bugger
>control, the list on the side of selected points in the code.

  Me too.  I like the extra helps a lot.

                                                                I would like
to
>see this list be in a separate window that could open, close and scroll...

  Yes! So it would be handy, but not in the way.  And scrolling would solve
the
only problem I have with the marker list: not long enough.  #;u)>


>I even sometimes use SuperTed on it's own as a text editor.

  I use SuperTed almost exclusively.  I seldom use any other editors fo
anything.
In fact, it is the editor I use with YAM and I am using it right now to type
this!

  I believe we need a dedicated editor with the extra helpful features but it
is
fine to make it so people can write or modify Pheonix code in a normal editor
if
they want to.  They would just have to do without the extra helpful features.
Allthough why anybody would want to do that I don't know.  #;u)>

  Seriously, we just need to make the new editor so good that everyone finds
it
the best editor to use for Pheonix programming. (and maybe everything else
too)

  I can see it now...  Amiga owners who have absolutely no interest in
programing
buying Pheonix just to have the editor!   #;u)>


    Have a good one,

     Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com) for now (may change soon)





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.373" "Re: Next Generation of Blitz"
	Fri, 20 Mar 1998 09:55:43 -0600 (CST)
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Fri, 20 Mar 1998 10:53:34 +0500
Subject: Re: Next Generation of Blitz

On 20-Mar-98, Adam Lounds flashed:

>Why not do a colour based thing - where Blitz currently uses a colour
>to identify valid commands, it could colour valid variables in another

  Yes, that would be a good option and easy to do.  It would aid in
reading the code and quickly finding what happens where.

>colour. It could append .s/.b/.w/.l to vars automatically if applicable
>(ie there is not count.b and count.w, which are treated as separate vars).

  Yes, so long as the user had the option of choosing the types.

>Or even use different colours for different types. Configuability
>is the key word here..

  Definately, configurability.

>Variable completion like KingCon/bash with the tab key would also be cool.

  As an option.

>You could even write it so that if you _do_ create a new variable in the
>middle of your code, it would add it to a list of predefinitions
>at the top of the code. That way you get the best of both worlds.

  Yes, that is one of the things I had in mind, but it probably should be
a choosable option.

>A configurable window, sort of like the TED shortcut list on the right, but
>with a list of vars (with optional (? maybe not..:)) descriptive notes)

  Speaking of the TED heading list, it the limit on it always bugged me.
Mayby we could find a way to ease that situation and also to make it
moveable.  I personally wwould much prefer a popup window.

>would be cool. All of this would effectively be part of TED, so no changes
>to the compiler per se would be necessary. 

  Exactly.

>I know there's a lot of disagreement over keeping TED/ having a standalone
>cli compiler, but an integrated compiler/editor with text import
>is one way around this. 

  My proposal is to have a dedicated editor with lots of cool features and
helps, but to still have it possible to do coding on a regular editor.
  This would be very easy to do by simply using asci and having any
imbeded tokanization on seperate lines and limited to editor options.
Any time the source was loaded into the dedicated editor the tokens
would be updated, but they would have nothing to do with the actual
code to be compiled so the compiler would not need them and would in fact
totally ignore them.  That way, source written on any asci editor would
compile just fine, only that the special helps for the programer
wouldn't be available when the source was being worked on.
  Compiler options could either be a data line at the end of the
program which would be directly editable on an asci editor, or their
could be a compiler option command with perameters to put in the
program.  This command could in fact be used more than once within the
program thus allowing certain compiler options to be changed in the
middle of compilation.  I can think of several good uses for that.


>Mind you, I'm still sceptical over this whole thing. A fully PPC 
>compatible compiler will take more than a few people doing it in their
>spare time. And you really aren't going to make any money out of it.
>RWE say 500 copies of Ultimate Blitz have been sold. Even at 20UKP royalty 
>per sale, a new compiler will only make 10 grand. Hardly a wage for 
>a full time group of coders.

  I myself have questions as to whether we will really pull it off,
its a huge job.  Will enough people stick to it?  Will we be able to
give it enough time?

  One thing is for sure though, we won't accomplish anything if we
don't try.  #;^)>

  I'm willing to give it a go.  I have no doubt about the ability of the
group here to do the job.  We certainly have the collective expertise,
it's just a matter of commitment.

  As for the money matter,  we'll cross that bridge when and if we
come to it.  I believe that the main reason there is so much enthusiasm
for the idea is that we all want the finished product so we can USE it
to make money with. (and/or for fun!)  Money is after all just a means
to an end, and if we can reach that end without going through the
'you pay me, then I pay you, meanwhile the government takes a huge cut'
phase so much the better.  If the Amiga market grows (which I believe
it will) and we find ourselves with a good market for it I think we
can figure out what to do.  #;^)>


>On another note, I don't know how libraries work, but I thought that 
>you have a list of routines at offsets into the code. I assume that 
>these offsets are defined in the autodocs or whatever they're called.
>Would it be possible to split the library into function chunks,
>run through a "convert to PPC code" routine, then build a new library
>with a new set of offsets? That way it would be possible to 
>use libs on the PPC side without having to rewrite them. 

>I accept that the converting to ppc code wouldn't be very optimised, but
>would it really matter? Optimising could be done at a later date when 
>spare time is available.

>I know it sounds too simple, but where does the problem arise?


  These last three points there are others here much more qualified to
speak to.  I'me just the manual guy.  #;^)>

  PS - In case anyone has wondered why my smiley faces always end with a >,
thats supposed to be my beard.  #;u)>


     Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)




@ENDNODE
