>fine to make it so people can write or modify Pheonix code in a normal =
editor
>if
>they want to.  They would just have to do without the extra helpful =
features.
>Allthough why anybody would want to do that I don't know.  #;u)>


Wouldn't it be a bit hard writing an editor for Pheonix when we have no =
idea how Pheonix will work?  At the moment, Blitz JSR's directly into =
Teds code, and there are much better ways of communicating with Ted.  I =
think that there should be a Pheonix shared library or message port, so =
Ted (or any editor) can easily get Pheonix to tokenise the source code, =
compile, stuff like that.  So I think we should wait till we have sorted =
out how Pheonix will work before jumping in to write an integrated =
editor.

>  Seriously, we just need to make the new editor so good that everyone =
finds
>it
>the best editor to use for Pheonix programming. (and maybe everything =
else
>too)


That would be quite difficult.  Have you tried GoldED?  Ted isn't even =
on the same planet when compared to GoldED.  I use it for C programming, =
and it can highlight brackets, comments, C commands, practically =
anything.  It really is head and shoulders above Ted.  You can even set =
breakpoints for a debugger in the same window.  It supports lots of =
different types of plugins, so you would have to be a wizard to beat =
GoldED!  In fact, I could write a plugin that tokenises Blitz =
commands...

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid




