@NODE "Mail.376" "Re: Next Generation of Blitz"
	(envelope-from tucks@pavilion.co.uk)
Date: Sat, 21 Mar 1998 08:08:50 +0000
From: Liz Tucker <tucks@pavilion.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Next Generation of Blitz

Anton Reinauer wrote:
> 
> On 19-Mar-98, Steven Wojciechowski wrote:
> 
> >How about creating a language which uses the structures of C but just
> >represents them differently.  Infact, just a rework of C this would
> >make importing and exporting of C easy.
> 
>    It's not a bad idea, especially when you remember that Blitz has a
> lot of C structures already, and a new version will most likely have
> more. The thing I hate about C is the aweful notation- it's hard to read
> and a nightmare to debug! If we had C features with the Basic notation,
> that was easy for beginners to learn (3rd party libs etc), then I think
> we'd be onto a winner!
>   Another thing to think about would be C++, or Java features, like
> inheritance etc. Maybe you could have a compiler option which allowed
> you to work fully object orientated- some ideas anyway.

What you are describing here seems to be very similar to AmigaE.

That is very C like but with easier to read notation and has OOP support
built it from the start.

If a new lauguage is to be created then we have to ensure we are
creating
something new and different that people will enjoy using, rather than
spemding the next couple of years re-creating something which has
already
been done.

Also portability between platforms is something to be considered as this
is where C comes into its own. Then you will have an easy to use,
powerful,
fast language which would allow easy porting between platforms. Now that
is
something new and exciting.
 
See you,

Liz.   

