@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.412" "Re: more OS-gfx questions"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 1998 15:13:11 +0100
Subject: Re: more OS-gfx questions

Hi James,

> I see now looking back through my mail archives that ShowBitmap is the
> command you can`t use... so is ScreensBitmap OK? Also is ShowPalette
> OS-friendly?

The problem with ShowBitmap and ScreensBitmap is they are
both dealing with planar/chipmem bitmaps. This means it's
totaly impossible to combine them with GFX cards where the
display is situated in GFX card memory in chunky mode.

The key to help you when dealing with GFX cards is you
must ask yourself these questions:

does this command use direct blitter? eg, "Blit"
is my source data in chip mem? eg, Bitmaps, Shapes
is my source data in planar mode? eg, Bitmaps, Shapes

Direct blitter is a no-no and anything dealing with chip
is slow. Anythig moving from chunky<->planar will require
a conversion process. The nicest thing is this c2p, p2c
conversion is done for you by the OS and it's prety fast
but at the end of th day you're lossing the whole point
of using GFX cards in the first place.

ShowPalette works exactly the same on a GFX card. As do
all the Window based functions and mouse pointer funtions.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

"How much orange is in a dead body?"
-- Brass Eye




