> 
> It certainly needs optimizing. The original is more than 2 times
> as fast. Still, it's a good idea!
> 
> You would have to convert most of the string functions because if you
> only converted Right$(), Left$(), Mid$(), Str$(), Chr$() and you
> needed to use Instr, Replace$, UnLeft$, LCase$ etc.. it would be
> a waste of time. In h case of h string functions you've got over
> 30 commnds contained in a 3k lib. This makes it even more important
> to optimize the libs for size as well as speed.  
> 
> At the end of the day your only talking about a 3k lib. In fact
> almost all of the Acid libs are that small. The Acid lib that
> contains the Poke command is less than 0.5k. The Acid libs are
> split into more than 80 libs already. The average size of an
> Acid Libs is well under 3k. 
> 
> Well, the idea is great but I think the benefits will be very
> small. You may get a small speedup if the commands are highly
> optimized. You will save some size if you are using very few
> commands.
> 
> On the plus side I think it'll be a great idea to create
> fixed versions of the buggy commands. If any of the commands
> can be made faster then thats another big plus!

Yes, but if he can get his own versions of all these commands, it's a 
step on the way to a blitz-independant language.

Speaking of which, 

Does anybody else wonder why whenever anything new is planned
for the Amiga, everyone has a fixation with calling it Phoenix?

There's always discussions "Oh, what shall we call the new Amiga - 
A1400? A6000? A2001? I know - let's call it phoenix! Like a phoenix
rising from the ashes!"

I don't consider the blitz language (or the Amiga for that matter) to 
have to rise from any ashes. That would be akin to saying it's dead and
buried, and anything new has to be some sort of second coming.

Just my 2p
