-- The Day Today



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.446" "Re: Interleaved bitmaps"
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <samin@megabaud.fi>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 18:00:52 +0200
Subject: Re: Interleaved bitmaps

On 15-Mar-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
> Hi BootBlock,

> > Can someone tell me the difference between a normal bitmap/screen
> > and an interleaved bitmap/screen?

> An interleaved bitmap is where the planes are stored in memory
> in an interleaved way as apposed to a '1st plane, 2nd plane,
> 3rd plane' system. An interleaved bitmap will contain 1 line
> of plane 1, 1 line of plane 2, 1 line of plane 3 etc.. Then the
> 2nd line of plane 1, the 2nd line of plane 2 and so on...

> So an 8bit bitmap of size 320x400 will be stored as a 1bit
> 320x3200 bitmap. When displayed on an Interleaved screen it
> will look just like a normal bitmap.
>  =

> > As far as I know, it's stop flicking or something (not that
> > I've notice that happen).

> It stops a bit of flickering when you're blitting to it but
> it's not perfect. It can actually be a faster mode as long as
> your source image is interleaved too :)

And here an add on info! :) The interleaved bitmap makes it possible to
blit one shape with one blit instead of blitting the shape plane by plane=

so if you think that you have 8 bitplane bitmap and you use interleaved
bitmap your code will continue execution immediately after the blitter is=

started. But if you have conventional bitmap the blitter first executes 7=

blittings and your prog have to wait until the 8 blitting is started, and=

after that it will continue. So if you got many blits to take its better
use interleaved one and between blits do some calculations to the next
blitting or so.

I though have no idea how to alloc interleaved bitmap in the blitz,
but by making it by yourself. :(

