@NODE "Mail.449" "Important Threads"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 1998 15:03:54 +0500
Subject: Important Threads

To all,

  We have at the moment several important continuing threads of
discussion occuring on the Blitz list which overlap just enough
that some are being confused by the situation.
  
  Please allow me to clarify the situation and suggest a tactic to
prevent confusion without detracting from any of these important
subjects.

  There is a discussion of the possibility of having Blitz Basic
upgraded and including PowerPC support mostly occuring under the
subjects begining with BlitzPPC and RWE_and_Blitz.
  I propose that everyone wanting to address the subject of
upgradeing the existing Blitz Basic try to use BlitzPPC as the
first part of their subject.


  There is a discussion of the idea of making a replacement for
Blitz Basic under a different name and with all-new source code
which branched slowely off of the BlitzPPC subject through the
RWE and Blitz Committee subjects.  This discussion is solidifying
now under the subject begining Next_Generation started by
Andreas Hakansson and being piloted by him.
  I propose that everyone wanting to address the subject of
coming up with a whole completely new replacement for Blitz Basic
try to use NextGeneration as the first part of their subject.


  There is a discussion of prepareing a new and better manual for
the EXISTING Blitz Basic and all of the third party improvements
available for it which branched off of the Sorting_files subject
and which project I (Donovan Reeve) am piloting.  Please note
that this project has NOTHING to do with the NextGeneration 
project which will of course require an entirely different manual
of its own.  That project is in the future and its manual will
not be able to be started until the coding is well along which will
take a long time.  The present Blitz Basic still needs an updated
and upgraded manual for those who are using it and will use it.
  I have changed the subject name of this discussion to Blitz
Manual to make it clearer what is being discussed.
  I propose that all who wish to discuss the production of a new
manual for the existing Blitz Basic try to use BlitzManual as the
first part of their subject.



  These discussions are all important so it is essential that we
keep them seperate without confusion between them.


   Regards to you all,

         Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)
   
 



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.450" "Re: Icons"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 14 Mar 1998 08:50:12 -0600
Subject: Re: Icons

Hi,

On 14-Mar-98, Oliver Marks wrote:
>Hi,

>Does anyone know how to load icons into blitz and display them in a
>window as i am unable to find any commands in the blitz manual which
>tell you how to use icons.

There are some icon handling commands in your RIToolTypes doc.  If you have
not yet found them, there are several doc files in your libsdev.lha file that
comes with Blitz.  These explain many commands you won't find in the manual.

There is a command which will put the icon into a DiskObject structure.
Unfortunately, there is no command to display the icon's image directly from
Blitz, and I don't have any info on how the DiskObject is set up.

But the icon imagery must be contained in it, and it should be possible to
transfer this to a Blitz shape object so you can display it in your window.

Does anybody know about the DiskObject structure?


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.451" "Re: Icons"
From: "Julian Kinraid" <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
Subject: Re: Icons
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 21:43:57 +1200
	charset="iso-8859-1"

Hi,

>>Does anyone know how to load icons into blitz and display them in a
>>window as i am unable to find any commands in the blitz manual which
>>tell you how to use icons.

[snip]
>But the icon imagery must be contained in it, and it should be possible =
to
>transfer this to a Blitz shape object so you can display it in your =
window.
>
>Does anybody know about the DiskObject structure?


I wrote a small test program a while ago that loads an icon and draws =
the image onto a window.  IIRC, the DiskObject contains a gadget =
structure, which contains pointers to the icons image.  My program uses =
the OS command DrawImage() to draw the icon onto a window, but if you =
wanted to transfer the icon image into a shape, you would have to write =
a routine to do that yourself.

I'll dig it up and send it to whoever wanted it (Oliver Marks?)

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid



@ENDNODE
