@NODE "Mail.461" "Re: Here we go again...."
From: "Adrian O' Neill" <aon@geocities.com>
Subject: Re: Here we go again....
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 14:44:26 -0600
	charset="iso-8859-1"

Hia,
I don't know much about Delphi, but I can tell you about C++ and Java.

The theory behind Java is that you should be able to develop applications
that will run on any machine that can run the Java Virtual Machine
(Including, eventually, the Amiga), but in reality, if you want to develop
really powerfull apps for the PC in Java you will have to use Microsoft's
MFC and hooks to the MS Win32 API, thereby really developing for the PC
alone.  Because of this, there really isn't much between the languages on
the PC.  In terms of the languages themseleves Java is strongly object-based
and so favored by educational institutions, whereas C++ has a massive user
base so is favored by the software industry.

If you decide to take the Java path, start out with the Java Development
kit, free from Sun's web site - http://java.sun.com - then move up to
Microsoft Visual J++.  The C++ path is much more expensive - the industry
leader is deservedly Microsoft's Visual C++ compiler, but it comes with
quite a heafty price tag.  However if you are quick, MS are giving away NT4
Workstation free for a limited time with each purchase.  If you have the
finances, go for Microsoft Visual Studio, which has both tools (and a few
more, including Visual Basic), and also comes with NT4 free.

For more on OO stuff, inc. some Java/C++ comparisons, see my web site:

http://www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Way/2374/tutorials.html

Hope this helps,
Adrian
Who has been only coding in MS C++ for one week....


