@NODE "Mail.469" "Re: Help needed"
From: Luca Carminati <toffi@spm.it>
Date: Mon, 04 Sep 1995 12:38:47 -0500
Subject: Re: Help needed

On 22-Mar-98, BootBlock of Carnage wrote:

>On 22-Mar-98, Henry Sopko wibbled:
>>Hello everyone,

>>          I'm trying to make a small executable program that gets calle=
d
>>from a script file, and I need to know how to make the program send a
>>error # to the OS? I went through the whole Blitz manual to see if ther=
e
>>was a command to setup a error # return I could set, so my scipt file
>>would know what action to take. Any help (a small example would be nice=
)
>>would be greatly appreciated!

>Right..... hmmm.... this is just a kind of "educated" guess, but just be=
fore
>your program ends, put the error number into d0, like this:

>   ... your prog...

>   MOVE.l  #5,d0
>   End


>Change the five in #5 to whatever number you want returning.

>I'm not sure if this'll work (depends if the #End# command messes up d0 =
or
>not), but it's worth a try! :)

No, this doesn't work since then End command always put #0 in d0 when qui=
tting
the executable.

I also tried:

   MOVE.l  #5,d0
   RTS   ; instead of End

Sometimes it works with memory losing and sometimes it causes a system cr=
ash.

I know that when a CLI program quits, its return code is stored in the lo=
cale
variable RC.  So I tried the following too:

   Execute_ "Set RC 5",0,0

This should set the RC variable to 5 but it doesn't actually work.

I asked the blitz-list for the same problem a couple of months ago.  It s=
eems
there isn't any solution.  Well, almost...  You could use the same soluti=
on I
used.  Set a global variable instead.  That is:

-------------------- blitz code ----------------------

FileHandle.l=3DOpen_("ENV:MY_RC",#MODE_NEWFILE)   ; global variable MY_RC=

If FileHandle
  rc$=3D"5"                                       ; 5 =3D error
  Write_ FileHandle,&rc$,Len(rc$)
  Close_ FileHandle
EndIf

-------------------- end blitz code ----------------------

Then in the script:

-------------------- cli script ----------------------

(call your blitz executable)

IF $MY_RC EQ 5
  Echo "There was an error"
ELSE
  Echo "All right"
ENDIF

-------------------- end cli script ----------------------

If this is not clear enough, please tell me.


-- =

Best regards,

Luca.

