@NODE "Mail.484" "Re: Graphics cards and Vertical Blanks"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 27 Mar 1998 06:21:24 -0600
Subject: Re: Graphics cards and Vertical Blanks

Hi James,

On 27-Mar-98, James Marshall wrote:
>Hello all,
>  I've just been converting my game to run in NTSC mode, which also
>involved retiming my MED modules so they played at the right speed when
>syncing with the Vertical Blank. But then I had a though... do graphics
>cards work in the same way as the custom display hardware regarding
>Vertical Blanks? Can you use VWait and the Vertical Blank interrupt for
>a game that will run on graphics cards? How often do graphics cards
>generate Vertical Blanks? Does it vary between 50Hz and 60Hz, or is it
>exclusively one value? Does it depend on the monitor/screen mode they
>are using? Can someone please explain all this to me? I'm a little
>confused on this subject, and don't have access to a graphics card to
>test anything out.
>    James

I'm not sure about the Vblanks on GFX cards.

But a better solution might be to use EML.lib (in Aminet/dev/basic) which will
play tracker modules in CIA mode.  This will run at the same speed on NTSC or
PAL systems.  You would need to convert your mod from OctaMed to Tracker
format, but this is easily done in OctaMed.

Or there may be a similar library to run Meds in CIA mode.


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.485" "Re: Graphics cards and Vertical Blanks"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Sat, 28 Mar 1998 11:59:56 +0500
Subject: Re: Graphics cards and Vertical Blanks

On 27-Mar-98, James Marshall flashed:
>Hello all,
>  I've just been converting my game to run in NTSC mode, which also
>involved retiming my MED modules so they played at the right speed when
>syncing with the Vertical Blank. But then I had a though... do graphics
>cards work in the same way as the custom display hardware regarding
>Vertical Blanks? Can you use VWait and the Vertical Blank interrupt for
>a game that will run on graphics cards? How often do graphics cards
>generate Vertical Blanks? Does it vary between 50Hz and 60Hz,

  Yes.  The hardware syncs the display speed acording to whether NTSC
or PAL mode is chosen.  This happens whether the Amiga or a graphics
card is creating the display.  Here in the U.S.A. we often have problems
with programs written to require PAL mode running to fast.  I imagine
that folks elsewhere have problems with our badly written programs
running to slow.  If the MEDs are synced to the display you may have
that problem but the solution is not to sync them to the display.
  Hopefully someone else can tell you what the best way to do that is
as I havn't worked with music in Blitz much.

                                                               or is it
>exclusively one value? Does it depend on the monitor/screen mode they
>are using? Can someone please explain all this to me? I'm a little
>confused on this subject, and don't have access to a graphics card to
>test anything out.
>    James


  Have a good one,

     Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com) for now (may change soon)





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.486" "Graphics cards and Vertical Blanks"
Date: Fri, 27 Mar 1998 10:02:53 +0000
From: James Marshall <homegrown@eclipse.co.uk>
Subject: Graphics cards and Vertical Blanks

Hello all,
  I've just been converting my game to run in NTSC mode, which also
involved retiming my MED modules so they played at the right speed when
syncing with the Vertical Blank. But then I had a though... do graphics
cards work in the same way as the custom display hardware regarding
Vertical Blanks? Can you use VWait and the Vertical Blank interrupt for
a game that will run on graphics cards? How often do graphics cards
generate Vertical Blanks? Does it vary between 50Hz and 60Hz, or is it
exclusively one value? Does it depend on the monitor/screen mode they
are using? Can someone please explain all this to me? I'm a little
confused on this subject, and don't have access to a graphics card to
test anything out.
    James

