@NODE "Mail.492" "Re: Gfx cards (what else?)"
Date: Mon, 30 Mar 1998 13:57:40 +0100
From: James Marshall <homegrown@eclipse.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Gfx cards (what else?)

Paul to the rescue again!
  my questions/problem are getting more technical by the day... maybe someone
could point me in the direction of a good technical reference for graphics
card programming (preferably online)...

Paul Burkey wrote:

> If you're opening the screen with a GFX card ModeId then it will
> open on the GFX card unless he's promoting it to AGA with a specific
> entry in his Screen promotion commodity.
>

doh! Yet another thing about gfx cards that I had no idea about. What are
valid gfx card ModeIds? Is there somewhere I can find them? In the developer
docs for the various graphics cards I suppose?And opening the screen without a
gfx card ModeId? Will that open it using AGA unless he has a screen promotion
entry to put it on his gfx card?

> That should be okay but it depends how fast the rendering is. Have
> you done any timing to check for the speed of he system *without*
> the WritePixelArray8 call? What I mean is a main loop like this:-
>
> Repeat
>   Render display to buffer. ;<- Maybe this is Damn slow?
>   Copy it to Screen.        ;<- Maybe this is super fast!
> Until GameOver
>

Yes, no figures but an indicator of how often the screen is updated (I left
out the WritePixelArray8 call but left in the WLine commands that draw
bounding selection boxes on the screen), so I got a rough idea. On my
030@50Mhz it seemed roughly as fast as the AGA version, but it was doing more
work (the RTG version redraws the entire screen every frame because I haven't
implemented chunky CPU bblit/unbuffer routines).

> Now, 640x256 is a very odd size for GFX cards. GFX ards usually have
> standard SVGA size screens like 640x480 or 320x240. If you ARE opening
> a 640x256 screen and it opens okay then I'm wondering if it really is
> an AGA screen. I have created my own 640x256 screen mode for my CV64/3D
> but it's not common for them to be one available.
>

OK, this can be done for CyberGfX, what about for Picasso? I'm in a quandry
now, 320x240 is too small horizontally, and 640x400 too big vertically! If the
Screen Promotion commodity were used what size would it promote to? 600x400?

> You are using an ASL Screen mode requestor to choose the ModeId?
>

No... maybe this would be a good idea. But then I'm still missing my 640x256
resolution.
And if I promote to 640x400 my graphics will look all squashed and nasty.

More problems.... I think I'm going to cry,
    James

