	charset="iso-8859-1"

Hi,

>one of my graphics card beta testers says my game runs unplayably
>slowly, and from what they say I think the game's screens may not be
>intercepted and displayed by the graphics card (which would explain the
>slowness). Is it possible that the graphics card may not intercept my OS
>graphics calls? My beta-tester has a CyberVision 64/3D. I'm opening my
>screen (640x256 256 cols) using the Screen command, rendering to a
>chunky bitmap using the ASM routines I just posted, and displaying the
>results using WritePixelArray8_(). Am I missing something out?


The 'Screen' command will always use a PAL/NTSC screen.  You need to use the
'Screentags' command, along with a screen modeid for a gfx card screen.  An
ASL Screen requester could be used to get the modeid.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.495" "Re: Gfx cards (what else?)"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Mon, 30 Mar 1998 11:32:38 +0000
Subject: Re: Gfx cards (what else?)

Hi James,

> one of my graphics card beta testers says my game runs unplayably
> slowly, and from what they say I think the game's screens may not be
> intercepted and displayed by the graphics card (which would explain the
> slowness). Is it possible that the graphics card may not intercept my OS
> graphics calls?

If you're opening the screen with a GFX card ModeId then it will
open on the GFX card unless he's promoting it to AGA with a specific
entry in his Screen promotion commodity.

> My beta-tester has a CyberVision 64/3D. I'm opening my
> screen (640x256 256 cols) using the Screen command, rendering to a
> chunky bitmap using the ASM routines I just posted, and displaying the
> results using WritePixelArray8_(). Am I missing something out?

That should be okay but it depends how fast the rendering is. Have
you done any timing to check for the speed of he system *without*
the WritePixelArray8 call? What I mean is a main loop like this:-

Repeat
  Render display to buffer. ;<- Maybe this is Damn slow?
  Copy it to Screen.        ;<- Maybe this is super fast!
Until GameOver

Now, 640x256 is a very odd size for GFX cards. GFX ards usually have
standard SVGA size screens like 640x480 or 320x240. If you ARE opening
a 640x256 screen and it opens okay then I'm wondering if it really is
an AGA screen. I have created my own 640x256 screen mode for my CV64/3D
but it's not common for them to be one available.

You are using an ASL Screen mode requestor to choose the ModeId?

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://burkey.home.ml.org

"Is God confused like his prating truth-pimps...or is he dead?"
-- The Day Today




@ENDNODE
