From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 27 Mar 1998 16:32:12 -0600
Subject: GFX card/fast ram

Hi all,

OK, I understand that if my program uses normal window drawing commands, it
will work with a GFX card.

So if I open a ScreenMode requester, I am guessing that a selection (or
selections) for the GFX card will appear with the rest of the modes?

If the user then selects a GFX card mode, and I open my screen in this mode,
will the program then be able to run on a GFX card?  Ie, will my screen and
windows display correctly?  And will they be sent to fast ram by intuition? 

It couldn't be that simple, I'm sure  ;)

I don't have A GFX card to try this on, and I know better than to try to
program for a piece of hardware I can't test it on (I have enough problems
with the hardware I CAN test it on, thank you) - 

But I do want to use a screen-mode requester.

And I would like the program to at least be able to be used on a GFX-card
system.
Oh, this is an application, not a game - no double buffering, etc. 

Any suggestions?
-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.497" "Re: GFX card/fast ram"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Fri, 27 Mar 1998 23:17:05 +0000
Subject: Re: GFX card/fast ram

Hi Curt,

> So if I open a ScreenMode requester, I am guessing that a selection (or
> selections) for the GFX card will appear with the rest of the modes?

Yes,

CV64/3D: 8Bit 320 x 240
CV64/3D: 8Bit 640 x 480
CV64/3D: 8Bit 1600 x 1200
CV64/3D: 16Bit 320 x 240
CV64/3D: 16Bit 640 x 480
etc...
 
> If the user then selects a GFX card mode, and I open my screen in this mode,
> will the program then be able to run on a GFX card?  Ie, will my screen and
> windows display correctly?  And will they be sent to fast ram by intuition? 

Windows and Screens open up using intuition.library so they are
automaticaly dealt with by CyberGraphX or Picasso96. They will all
exist on in GFX card memory.

> It couldn't be that simple, I'm sure  ;)

I'm sure :)
 
> Oh, this is an application, not a game - no double buffering, etc. 

I can see very few problems. It is very likely that you could
create a huge Application using system friendly methods like
Windows, WBlit, Gadgets etc.. and it'll work 100% on CyberGFX
and P96 with no special testing.

Your free to send me test projects if you want anything testing.

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://paulburkey.home.ml.org

