@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.507" "General about RISC/CISC"
    16 Mar 98 12:06:37 0
From: "David Mcminn" <MD.BE4.Student.eee.rgu.ac.uk@eee-student.eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 12:06:22 GMT0BST
Subject: General about RISC/CISC

 RISC chips have less instructions and so can be made from less 
silicon. However, more advanced features can be implemented on these 
processors as there is always the capability to use more silicon. 
 CISC chips do not normally have enough silicon to implement these 
features, although the Pentium range do use some of these advanced 
features.

 Also because the RISC chips can be made from less material, more 
expensive (but faster) materials, such as Gallium Arsenide, can be 
used for the same development costs as a v.fast CISC.

 However, the main basis of a RISC chip is that it can execute one 
instruction per cycle, and all instructions are capable of being 
executed this fast.

Farewell, for now,

.oO David McMinn Oo.
-=-=-=-=-==-=-=-=-=-
*A1200T 1.3Gb 16xCD*
-=-=-=-=-==-=-=-=-=-


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.508" "Re: General about RISC/CISC"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 10:33:23 +0500
Subject: Re: General about RISC/CISC

On 16-Mar-98, David Mcminn flashed:
> RISC chips have less instructions and so can be made from less 
>silicon. However, more advanced features can be implemented on these 
>processors as there is always the capability to use more silicon. 
> CISC chips do not normally have enough silicon to implement these 
>features, although the Pentium range do use some of these advanced 
>features.

> Also because the RISC chips can be made from less material, more 
>expensive (but faster) materials, such as Gallium Arsenide, can be 
>used for the same development costs as a v.fast CISC.

> However, the main basis of a RISC chip is that it can execute one 
>instruction per cycle, and all instructions are capable of being 
>executed this fast.


  The amount of silicone used in a chip is almost irrelivant.  A chip
can theoretically be made as large as the designer wishes as long as
the electrical requirements and other resulting potential problems are
taken into consideration.  Silicone and other semi-conductor materials
are relatively cheap when you consider the small amount used and
constitute only a very small part of the cost of a chip.  This is why
a 68000 for instance now costs almost nothing even though it still
contains the same amount of silicone.  The developement costs are the
major costs for production of any chip, and when they have been defrayed
the price of the chip is mainly determined by production volume and
what the market will bear.  How many features a chip includes is also
mainly determined by developement costs verses potential gain.

  I am goin to drop this branch of the subject now, realizing that I
am guilty of getting to far off subject and opening a can of worms.
  For that I appologize to you all.

  As for the origional subject of encouraging support in Blitz for
PPC and perhaps even other processors, YES let's do everything we can
to support that effort!


       Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)
 



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.509" "Re: General about RISC/CISC"
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <samin@megabaud.fi>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 20:48:23 +0200
Subject: Re: General about RISC/CISC

On 16-Mar-98, David Mcminn wrote:
>  RISC chips have less instructions and so can be made from less =

> silicon. However, more advanced features can be implemented on these =

> processors as there is always the capability to use more silicon. =

>  CISC chips do not normally have enough silicon to implement these =

> features, although the Pentium range do use some of these advanced =

> features.

>  Also because the RISC chips can be made from less material, more =

> expensive (but faster) materials, such as Gallium Arsenide, can be =

> used for the same development costs as a v.fast CISC.

>  However, the main basis of a RISC chip is that it can execute one =

> instruction per cycle, and all instructions are capable of being =

> executed this fast.

In fact not all only the Singlepass Integer Instructions such as add sub
and not ... but mul and div take more clock cycles to execute same thing
for the FPU instructions too. So the processor is build in such a way tha=
t
it have 2 - 4 Singlepass Integer Units and 1 Multipass Integer Unit and o=
ne
FloatingPoint Unit. So the processor can still execute those logical
commands even if it have to multiply at the same time.
Because this structure you really should try to do multiple things at the=

same time so if you multiply two registers you shouldn't use this result =
in
the next instruction because the CPU have to wait until the result is
coming from the MIU. So here is an example:


start:mullir0,r1,#1000multiply reg1 by 1000 and result in reg0
addir2,r2,100add 100 to reg2
lwzur3,4(r2)load word (32bit) from address reg2+4 to reg3
and store reg2+4 to reg2
addr0,r0,r3add reg3 to reg0
stwr0,0(r2)store reg0 to address pointed by reg2


start:addir2,r2,100add 100 to reg2
lwzur3,4(r2)load word (32bit) from address reg2+4
and store reg2+4 to reg2
mullir0,r1,#1000multiply reg1 by 1000 and result in reg0

here the CPU have to wait because it have nothing to do

addr0,r0,r3add reg3 to reg0
stwr0,0(r2)store reg0 to address pointed by reg2


This example do not work in any way, and do nothing sensible.
It is only made to illustrate the meaning of different "inner"
units in the RISC type CPU to the codes effectiveness!

PS. If you wonder where I get the info try ordering your own MPC604e
UserManual and look for your self. You can also order the data manual
(Programming guide) if you want to start coding PPC assembler. :)

