@NODE "Mail.520" "Re: ForcePal"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 24 Mar 1998 20:31:34 -0600
Subject: Re: ForcePal

Hi Matt,

On 24-Mar-98, Matt Daniels wrote:
>Hi,

>My game (/game/actio/ccalpha.lha) only works for NTSC users
>if they reboot in pal mode, and have a Pal compatable display.

>ForcePal will allow my Blitz mode game to run from an
>NSTC Amiga? How can I test this on my PAL machine.

I don't think it is possible to test it on your PAL system, since you know
already that it can display PAL screens.  The only reliable way is to have
someone with a real NTSC system try it for you.

Force PAL will do the same as booting the machine into PAL - if the machine
can handle it.  Any ECS or AGA NTSC Amiga can be switched into PAL mode (this
means anything that has at least 1M chip ram) but I don't know if this will
work if they have a TV instead of a real monitor.  With a monitor, it is no
problem to run a NTSC system in PAL mode.  However, the display is a little
better in NTSC mode  (in PAL it gets a little fuzzy for me - not bad, but
noticable)

>Also. 
>If they cannot display PAL will I have to recode my display
>and timing routines. And again, how can I test this.

If I run a program meant for PAL in NTSC mode, some of the bottom lines of the
screen can't be seen.  How many are lost depends on the overscan setting. 
Depending on what is at the bottom of the screen, this can make the game
unplayable.

Also, everything goes a bit faster - if the code can keep up to 60 fps instead
of 50.  If not, the game will slow down badly.

And some PAL programs will simply lock up if I try to run them in NTSC mode.

To test NTSC on your system, just boot into NTSC or use FORCE NTSC.  The
screen probably won't look quite right, but you can see if the timing is OK.



>Thanks.
>-- 
>Matt Daniels
>mattd@underused.u-net.com


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
