@NODE "Mail.532" "Re: Fast Ram bitmaps"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 17:44:00 +0100
Subject: Re: Fast Ram bitmaps



 Hiya!

>It's not just a case of displaying the  bitmap.  It  also  depends  on
>which  commands  you're  using  to read/write to the bitmaps. Commands
>like Plot and Point will probably be using the  blitter  so  fast  ram
>would cause problems there.
>It's quite a complicated thing you're trying to do  so  I'm  not  sure
>where  to  start  when  trying  to  give  you the best advice. I don't
>suppose it's too hard to write the iff file yourself, I'm sure someone
>has  ilbm writing source. Another thing to decide is, are you going to
>stick with planar or convert the data  to  chunky.  A  chunky  version
>would  allow  very  fast  scaling  but  you'll have to convert back to
>planar when writing the file. If you keep the data in planar form then
>it'll be much harder and slower to emulate the Point/Plot commands.
>The second idea is easier to impliment but will give you  the  slowest
>results.  The  chunky  idea  would be more work but would provide much
>faster results.
 
Well writing two small functions in asm, that would be like Point/Plot,
but  for  FastRam  shouldn't be that hard. You just need to know how to
write the data, so it's written like an IFF/ILBM  file,  otherwize  you
wouldn't be able to load it into anyother progs.

We at Vivid Imagination has written some custom routines, which enables
you  to load unlimited numbers of shapes into blitz (memory restricting
the numbers of shapes you can load), since blitz  only  lets  you  load
1024  shapes before it crashes. When we made these routines, we added a
MemType flag, that chooses  into  what  memory  the  shapes  should  be
loaded.  We can load the shapes into chip or into fastmem, and then use
them as normal blitz shapes without any problems. When storing them  in
Fast  Ram,  the code gets a bit slower (since it need to copy the shape
you want to blit, back into chip before blitting it, and erase it again
after  it's  been use), but this is not much at all, it accepteble. The
way we have made them, we can use the standard blit  command  in  blitz
(like Blit, BBlit, QBlit etc).

So I dont think writting some FastPoint{} and FastPlot  commands  would
be that hard to make.

 ByE!







@ENDNODE
