@NODE "Mail.536" "Re: Fast Ram bitmaps"
From: NUEL Xavier <xn.baddolls@a2points.com>
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 14:49:08 -0000
Subject: Re: Fast Ram bitmaps
X-Info: A2POINTS -> La poste de demain...

Le 17-Mars-98, Curt Esser a =E9crit:

Hi Curt,

>>   Hey !  I've made the command SaveILBM which will help you to write t=
he
iff
>>file ;-) This new command is in my litle library :  BDGfxLib .  I think=
 it's
>>easy to use, but if you need more help, ask me....

>Yes, I have just gotton the newest version of your nice library.
>I do have a couple of questions:


>        ------------------------------------------------------

>        CGrey.w =3D ColorGrey(Pal#,Color#)
>                    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
>        This command will return the Grey value
>        of the colour Color# in the palette Pal#

>I am thinking this would be, for example if I get return value of 15 thi=
s
>would be the same as setting my palette to Red=3D15, Green=3D15, Blue =3D=
15?  Or is
>this incorrect? =


   It just return the Grey value, but it doesn't change the Red, Green an=
d
Blue of your colour.
   Perhaps I would make this command to change the component of the speci=
fied
colour...

>        ------------------------------------------------------


>          NEWTYPE.BitMapHeader
>           bmh_Width.w       ; BitMap Width
>           bmh_Height.w      ; BitMap Height
>           bmh_Left.w        ; MUST BE 0 !!!
>           bmh_Top.w         ; MUST BE 0 !!!
>           bmh_Depth.b       ; BitMap Depth
>           bmh_Masking.b     ; 0=3DNo Mask    OR   2=3DWe got a ColorMas=
k

>What is this ColorMask?  I am not sure what I put here.  Does this make =
it
>save as a "Shape" instead of a "Bitmap"?

   Hummm... If you set the ColorMask to 0, then, if you load this picture=
 as a
Brush in PPaint, you got a 'solid' brush. But if you set it to 2, then yo=
u got
a brush with a transparent colour. I don't really know how is handle a sh=
ape,
but , with ColorMask set to 2, the IFF file will be save as a 'Brush'. I
suppose it's the same. =


>           bmh_Compression.b ; 0=3DNot Compressed  1=3DCompressed
>           bmh_Pad.b         ; MUST BE 0 !!!
>           bmh_Transparent.w ; Used if bmh_Masking=3D2

>And is this the transparent colour for the "Shape" saving?

Yes !!!

>           bmh_XAspect.b     ; Aspect in Width
>           bmh_YAspect.b     ; Aspect in Height

>And the Aspects? For example if my picture is 640 * 400, do I use 64 and=
 40?
>Or how do I use these?

   I don't really know who to calculate these values, but I think these v=
alues
depend on the ViewMode of the picture.

   I have found this :

      Width : 320         =3D XAspect=3D $2C =3D 44
      Width : 640         =3D XAspect=3D $16 =3D 22
      Width : 1280        =3D XAspect=3D $0B =3D 11

      Height : 200         =3D YAspect=3D $34 =3D 52
      Height : 256         =3D YAspect=3D $2C =3D 44
      Height : 400         =3D YAspect=3D $1A =3D 26
      Height : 512         =3D YAspect=3D $16 =3D 22

   If someone can find a relation between all these numbers, tell it to m=
e ;-)

>           bmh_PageWidth.w   ; Screen Width  ( Can be same as BitMap )
>           bmh_PageHeight.w  ; Screen Height ( Can be same as BitMap )
>          End NEWTYPE


>Also, my other question is if your library's commands will work on an EC=
S
>system, or only for AGA?

I don't know :-( , but I think it will only work on AGA... If someone can=
 try
my lib on an ECS system, tell me if it work.

>Thanks for your help.

>And thanks for making your good library even better!

:-)

Ciao & A+
