@NODE "Mail.537" "Re: Fast Ram bitmaps"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Sun, 15 Mar 1998 20:02:58 +0100
Subject: Re: Fast Ram bitmaps

Hi Curt,

> Is there a way to move both bitmaps into fast ram, or at least the source
> bitmap?

Blitz is prety much limited to chip ram bitmaps for almost all commands
so it's not easy to simply create a bitmap in fast ram. You won't
be able to examine or render anything to fast ram bitmaps and I'm
sure you'll even have trouble loading and saving too unless you
write your own iff load/save routines.

It's very easy to make fast ram bitmaps. You just allocate enough
fast memory using AllocMem() and then you cludge your new bitmap
to it using CludgeBitmap.

> I am using no other bitmap commands besides the "Point" and "Plot",
> and neither bitmap is ever seen.  But of course the output bitmap
> must be able to be saved as a standard iff picture.

It's not just a case of displaying the bitmap. It also depends on
which commands you're using to read/write to the bitmaps. Commands
like Plot and Point will probably be using the blitter so fast ram
would cause problems there.

It's quite a complicated thing you're trying to do so I'm not
sure where to start when trying to give you the best advice. I
don't suppose it's too hard to write the iff file yourself, I'm
sure someone has ilbm writing source. Another thing to decide is,
are you going to stick with planar or convert the data to chunky.
A chunky version would allow very fast scaling but you'll have to
convert back to planar when writing the file. If you keep the data
in planar form then it'll be much harder and slower to emulate
the Point/Plot commands.

The second idea is easier to impliment but will give you the
slowest results. The chunky idea would be more work but would
provide much faster results.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

"Let's have a look at the Japanese finance arse..."
-- The Day Today




@ENDNODE
