@NODE "Mail.557" "Re: Close all Windows"
From: C Dimitrakakis <cdimita@essex.ac.uk>
Subject: Re: Close all Windows
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 15:23:00 +0000 (GMT)
X-Authentication: IMSP


On Thu, 26 Mar 1998 13:10:42 +0000 Paul Burkey 
<paul%sneech.demon.co.uk@uk.ac.essex.mailhost> wrote:

> Hi,
> 
> I'm writing a statement that will check for open windows
> and close them for me. Basicly a CloseAllWindows{} command.
> 
..

> So my question is, Is there a way to detect Object Maximums
> durring runtime?
> 
I suggest that you replace all object creating calls with statement 
calls.. ie:

NEWTYPE .cust_window
  id.w
  x:y:w:h
........
END NEWTYPE

Dim List window_list.w(#MAX_WINDOWS)

Statement MyOpenWindow{winstruct.l}
  SHARED window_list()
  DEFTYPE .cust_window *mywindow
  *mywindow=winstruct
  USEPATH *mywindow
  Window \id,\x,\y..
  if AddItem(window_list()) then window_list()=\id
End Statement

...
MyOpenWindow{&winstruct}


CloseAllWindows:
  ResetList window_list()
  While NextItem(window_list())
    CloseWindow window_list()
  Wend
  ClearList window_list
  Return

..
This approach also makes it easier for you to use alternative calls for 
creating objects - what it basically does, is that it adds another 
level of object management into your proggy. Hm. Try it.



Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex
http://esewww.essex.ac.uk/~cdimita



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.558" "Re: Close all Windows"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 16:49:23 -0600
Subject: Re: Close all Windows

Hi,

On 26-Mar-98, Garfield Benjamin wrote:
>> I'm writing a statement that will check for open windows
>> and close them for me. Basicly a CloseAllWindows{} command.
>> Statement CloseAllWindows{}
>>   For w=0 to 9
>>     If Peek.l(Addr Window(w))
>>       CloseWindow w
>>     Endif
>>   Next w
>> End Statement
>> This is fine! What I'd now like to do is add this statement to
>> a collection of statements that can be included in any other
>> programs I write.
>> So my question is, Is there a way to detect Object Maximums
>> durring runtime?

>   Sure, the keyword is Maximum.

>   In the above example, you would replace the For w=0 to 9
>   with: For w=0 To (Maximum Window)-1

Yes, and to keep things simple, really the if/then loop is not necessary
either.
Blitz checks to see if the window exists before closing it, so
there is no harm in closing (or Free' ing) a window that is not open.
Same goes for bitmaps, shapes, and all other Blitz Objects.

-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.559" "Re: Close all Windows"
 Thu, 26 Mar 1998 14:01:50 -0500
From: "Garfield Benjamin" <gbenjam@sosbbs.com>
Subject: Re: Close all Windows
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 14:18:31 -0500

> I'm writing a statement that will check for open windows
> and close them for me. Basicly a CloseAllWindows{} command.
> Statement CloseAllWindows{}
>   For w=0 to 9
>     If Peek.l(Addr Window(w))
>       CloseWindow w
>     Endif
>   Next w
> End Statement
> This is fine! What I'd now like to do is add this statement to
> a collection of statements that can be included in any other
> programs I write.
> So my question is, Is there a way to detect Object Maximums
> durring runtime?

   Sure, the keyword is Maximum.

   In the above example, you would replace the For w=0 to 9
   with: For w=0 To (Maximum Window)-1


                Garfield Benjamin    e-mail:gbenjam@sosbbs.com
        Website( http://www.sosbbs.com/~gbenjam ): 50% Complete


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.560" "Close all Windows"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 13:10:42 +0000
Subject: Close all Windows

Hi,

I'm writing a statement that will check for open windows
and close them for me. Basicly a CloseAllWindows{} command.

The statement may look like this:

Statement CloseAllWindows{}
  For w=0 to 9
    If Peek.l(Addr Window(w))
      CloseWindow w
    Endif
  Next w
End Statement

I think this should work fine. It will check the first entry
in the .Window structure which will be NULL if the window is
already closed.

This is fine! What I'd now like to do is add this statement to
a collection of statements that can be included in any other
programs I write. The big problem is the For..Next is hardcoded
to support 0..9 which would give random results if the Object
Maximum was more than or less than 10.

So my question is, Is there a way to detect Object Maximums
durring runtime?

Cheers

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://paulburkey.home.ml.org

