@NODE "Mail.568" "Re: Chunky CPUBlit Benchmarks"
From: C Dimitrakakis <cdimita@essex.ac.uk>
Subject: Re: Chunky CPUBlit Benchmarks
Date: Tue, 31 Mar 1998 15:14:01 +0100 (British Summer Time)
X-Authentication: IMSP


On Tue, 31 Mar 1998 10:28:05 +0100 James Marshall 
<homegrown%eclipse.co.uk@uk.ac.essex.mailhost> wrote:

> 
> Blit: 1000 shapes in 149 ticks=6.7 shapes per tick
> cpu_blit: 1000 shapes in 93 ticks=10.8 shapes per tick
> 
> ClipBlit: 1000 shapes in 152 ticks=6.6 shapes per tick
> cpu_clipblit: 1000 shapes in 91 ticks=10.9 shapes per tick
> The results showing cpu_clipblit 
> to be slightly faster than cpu_blit were surprising considering the
> extra computation required, but I confirmed the results with an
> additional run of 10000 blits.
>     James
> 
It is problably the fact that your code is not pipelined properly in 
the first case..

Problems:
In your CPUBLOCK code:
You can replace your shape-size code with
the following, which does not have a jump 
Jumps are slow

GetReg d6,width
..
do check that d6 is a multiple of min_size (ie 32)
..
SUBQ.b #1,d6    ;now d6=width-1, so that AND will do proper wrapping :)
inner_loop:

...... this code wraps around the shape coordinates....
MOVE.b d0,d2
MOVE.b d1,d3
ASL.w #8,d3
EXT.w d2
ADD.w d3,d2
MOVE.b (a0,d2.w),(a1,d2.w)	;not sure if valid addressing mode in 
				;blitz assember
ADDQ.b #1,d0	;using ADDQ makes things faster
AND.b d6,d0	;(d6=width, d0=x)
SNE d2		;d2 is used a scratch register here
		;if d0 is wrapped around
ADDQ.b #1,d2
ADD.b d2,d1	
SUB.b d2,d7	;(d7=height)
BEQ inner_loop


This code was made on the fly, so I cannot be sure that it will work
Anyways, I hope it gives you some ideas.. try and avoid jumps...
use ADDQ/SUBQ (or ADDI/SUBI) where possible, make use of the Logical 
operators, try and use the Scc operation.. write pipelined code:

Example of optimizing code:

Beofe :)
------------
plot_done2:
ADD.l #1,a0
ADD.l #1,a1
ADD.b #1,d0
CMP d2,d0
BLT xline3
ADD.l d4,d0
ADD.l d5,d0
ADD.l #640,a1
ADD.l d0,a1
SUB.l d2,a1
ADD.b #1,d1
CMP d3,d1
BLT xline3

After :)
---------
plot_done2:
ADDI.l #1,a0	;(dont think ADDQ is valid for ax registers, however)
ADDQ.b #1,d0	;move this here for pipelining
ADDI.l #1,a1	;(in any case, it is better to use postincrement)
CMP.l d2,d0	;(specify size)
BLT xline3

ADD.l d4,d0		;just some pipelining here
ADDI.l #640,a1
ADD.l d5,d0
ADD.l d0,a1
ADDQ.b #1,d1
SUB.l d2,a1
CMP d3,d1
BLT xline3


Hope this helps




Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex
http://esewww.essex.ac.uk/~cdimita



