@NODE "Mail.598" "Re: BlitzPPC?(other cpus~way off topic)"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Mon, 16 Mar 1998 10:25:53 +0500
Subject: Re: BlitzPPC?(other cpus~way off topic)

On 15-Mar-98, Matt Daniels flashed:
>Hi Donovan, On 14-Mar-98 you wrote...

>[deletia]
>>  RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Chip [or CPU in some
>>circles]) processors tend to turn higher cycle speeds
>>due to not having as great an instruction list to go
>>through. This looks impressive in specs, and in fact
>>that propaganda value was one of the main reasons for
>>the 'Wintel' consortium to go to them in the first place,
>>because it looked good on advertising.
>[deletia]

>Intel`s Pentium chips may be more geared towards clock
>speed than than the equivalent AMD chips but they are
>not RISC. ASFAIK intel plan to miss RISC out completely
>and have a completely different sort of chip planned for
>the future. (the all important acronym escapes me;)

  You are of course entirely correct.  In my zeal to get
in a well deserved poke at Intel and Microsoft I lumped
them right in there, didn't I. &;^)>
  I have a tendancy to do that due to the simularities in
requirements for larger code.
  This is a subject which has electronics engineers going
all the time and I didn't really intend to make a big deal
of it here.
  Please forgive me my transgressions! #;^)>


>A lot of money is spent on developing the Pentium line,
>but i`m sure a 1GHz Alpha workstation  can outpace any 
>existing single processor pentium system. Both of them 
>running 32 bit Pentium  code under Windows NT.
>(see www.digital.com)

  Yup.

>Sorry if I missed your point but you either seemed to 
>be assuming that the pentium was RISC or your e-mail
>was not clear enough for me.

  Well, my origional point was that RISC processors do
not necessarily accomplish more per clock cycle
allthough there are many factors which enter into that.
  My main goal is to indicate that even though PPC
wouldn't have been my first choice of the way for the
Amiga to go,  it is now here and definatly should be
supported.
  As has been voiced by many others, I add my vote to
the idea of trying to get Blitz support for the PPC and
also maybe in the future other processors.

  And now, recognizing that I am a bit off base with this
discussion I humbly ask forgiveness and will mention that
branch of the subject no more.


     Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)





@ENDNODE
