@NODE "Mail.600" "Re: BlitzPPC?"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Tue, 10 Mar 1998 19:01:45 +0100
Subject: Re: BlitzPPC?


 Well first I  would like to say that if this
project is made into reality, then blitz will
become a very popular  developer language for
the ppc cards. The reason for this is that it
will be the only basic language  that has ppc
support (eat dust am*s...). I  dont mean that
it will be the language that will  be used to
develope all ppc software, since C++ and  Asm
is still  the leading languages. But  it will
mean that a lot more software will bw written
for the ppc card, since all basic programmers
will be able to make ppc software as well.

Just  like  Steven  Dobbs said in his mail, I
would  also  like  that  it  will  be able to
generate code for both  the 68k cpus  and the
PPC cpus. This will mean that it will be very
easy to  both  make a  68k  version and a PPC
version  of   your   programs  (although  you
proberbly  will have to change the code abit,
since  there  will  most  likely be ppc based
commands  as  well, to  get full advantage of
the ppc's). As  I  see it,  there  are  three
diffrent ways that RWE can accomplish this.

(1) Have   two  diffrent  compilers, one  68k
    compiler, and ppc code compiler. And then
    you could  choose what compiler to use in
    the   Compiler   Options. This  has   the
    advantage  that when one of the compilers
    gets  updated, you  only  had to download
    a smaller file, and if you dont need  the
    68k code  compiler  you simply  delete it
    from your HD, and saves space.

(2) Have  a  compiler  that   is  written  to
    generate both 68k code  and ppc code. And
    You  would  have to choose  which in  the
    Compiler Options. I  think  this  is what
    Steven Dobbs was talking about.

(3) Have a plugin based  compiler system. The
    compiler would use  plugin  file for both
    cpus. The  plugin  file  would  hold  all
    the compiler DATA for  the diffrent cpus.
    And the main compiler program  would  get
    the DATA it  need from  the plugin  file.

This is  the method I  would  like for RWE to
use, since it has the  most advantages of the
three  mentioned. A  few  of  them being that
each  plugin  file would be much smaller then
the file in method (1), since  it  only holds
cpu  unique data, and n o compiler  engine it
self, like method (1) would have to do.

But  the  biggest advantage of all is that it
will  make  it  very  easy (or  atleast  much
easyer) to  make  blitz  support  any  future
cpu's  that  will  be introduced to the amiga
community. Now  many  of  you  think that I'm
talking about a big  load of  rubbish, when I
say that ther will be  more cpu types used in
the diffrent amigas in the future, since it's
just been decided for the 68k + PPC solution.
But I'm not. I  know  for  a  fact  that that
solution is only a  short term  solution. And
with short term I mean for the next 2-3 years
(could   be   abit  longer, depends  on  many
diffrent factors). I know  for  a  fact  that
the long term goal for the  amiga  is to make
it a cpu independant system. This  would mean
that  there  will  be  amigas that uses cpu's
like PPC, MIPS, ALPHA etc.

Now  you  say  that this is  impossible since
the software wouldn't be  able  to run on all
the diffrent cpu  types. But  it's  not. This
will be solved  with either a  system  called
ADE or a system  called ANDE. It's  currently
being  disscused  which  system  would be the
best, or if they sould use both, and let each
user the option to choose which  method  they
want  to  use. Both  systems  is  a  kind  of
insallation  tool, but with the exeption that
it's  actually a  compiler  as well. The  SDE
system means that  code will  be compiled  on
installation, and  the ANDE system means that
the program  will be compiled  in  real  time
when  it's executed (now many of you say that
this will be  very  slow, but it wont. I cant
go  into  depth  why  not, atleast not at the
moment, but  keep  in  mind  that  this  wont
happen on a 68k cpu, but  on  a  MUCH  faster
cpu).

The  first  thing I tought of when I was told
about both methods  was  that this would mean
that  the  source  code  would  be  delivered
uncompiled when you  buy a peice of software,
since it hasnt been compiled yet. But it wont
since the code will  be  precompiled  into  a
slime   binary   form, which   the   SDE/ANDE
installer would use. So the  source  WONT  be
left for  hackers to change and  spread 10000
diffrent  version   of   your  software, with
thier own changes in it. Well I cant  go into
more details, both because the mail  would be
VERY  long, and  since  some  of the info  is
still a secret (as we  all  know it's Gateway
2000 policy not to reveil anything until it's
decided on). The  SDE/ANDE  systems  isn't  a
secret though and  it's  something  completly
new, and  has  been  around for a while (does
linux sound formilieur?).

How do I know all this then? Well  I'm on the
ICOA (Industry  Council OPEN Amiga) developer
mailing  list (please dont  ask how  you  can
join, since  the  list  is  invite only). And
thats   where  all  of  this  has/are   being
disscused. All  of  you  that  dont know what
ICOA does, I can tell  you  that  they decide
upon the  next  generation  amiga  standards,
that all  companies  that  will  make  amigas
under  licence  from  Amiga Inc, will have to
follow, to be  aloud to  put  the "Powered By
Amiga" logo in it. If you hadn't  heard about
ICOA before, then  check  out  thier homepage
(http://www.netreach.net/~fleecy/icoa/).  You
can also read more about the SDE/ANDE project
and much more at:

http://www.ug.ecs.soton.ac.uk/~sps196/archives/ICOA/index.html

It's  a  ICOA  malinglist archive and summary
page. There   are  a  TON  of  important  and
intressting   information, that   will   have
you reading for  a  few  hours  (if  you read
everything).

I'm sorry that this mail became abit long and
abit  of  topic, but  It   was  neccecary  to 
explain about the SDE/ANDE  projects for  you
to understand how method (3) would work.

As more proof I can  ask you this. Why do you
think I took the "risc" of  buying a ppc card
long  before  the  next  generation of  cpu's
where  decided. This  could have ment that it
could have become useless  right? Well I knew
about  the  SDE/ANDE  projects, so  I  wasn't
worried (and  it's kewl  to  have  one of the
first 100 card that was made..I have #92 :-))

Please  send  any  questrion  threw the list,
since the might be more people on  the  list,
that want to  know  the answer. Try  to  keep
them short, since  this  is  actually abit of
topic, and some on the  list might  not  like
us talking about this on the list.

  ByE!






@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.601" "Re: BlitzPPC?"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 14 Mar 1998 07:40:30 -0600
Subject: Re: BlitzPPC?

Hi all,

On 12-Mar-98, Eoghann Irving wrote:
>Hi :)


>Well I was in favour of this idea when it originally surface and I
>basically stil am.  I do have a few comments to make though.

>>#> What ever happend to tha suggestion that we should write
>>#> a well phrased and informed  email  to acid (or who ever
>>#> owns it), and explaine to them that  they  have  to hand
>>#> over the rights to the source code to RWE, if they  want
>>#> blitz to survive, and make any  money of it??? Was  that
>>#> idea killed? I think  we should  send  such  e-mails  to
>>#> them frequently (not regulary, since  that  woul d be to
>>#> obbvious). I'm  prepared  to write the  e-mail (I  would
>>#> first send it to the list to get your  oppinion about it
>>#> of course) and send it to them. If we decide to do this,
>>#> then I think everyone should  list what  they  think  we
>>#> should have in the email and we can vote  about it. This
>>#> way everyone gets a  say what we  should write. What  do
>>#> you guys think of this?

>The phrasing has to be very very careful.  We want to suggest something
>that can make them money rather than telling them they're being a bit
>stupid. ;)

>If we're going to nominate RWE then we have to know that RWE want to do it.

>So before we talk to Acid we talk to RWE.

>We have to define what we mean by "turn over the rights".  My first thought
>its that RWE should be given full control of the source (thats different
>from
>owning it) for upgrades and in return get a % of sales only on their
>upgraded
>Blitz.

>This strikes me as fair to all parties although exact percentages might
>take some negotiation.

>Now, assuming that we have RWE on side the next people to approach are
>Guildhall leisure since they are the distributors (well they are in the UK,
>whats the situation in other countries?).  Our argument with them
>is that new Blitz updates=new products to sell=money.

>If we have two sides of the triangle in place it should be easier to
>persuade Acid that this is worth doing.  I would leave it to Guildhall and
>RWE to approach Acid directly, but I would use this list (and magazines and
>any other method) to try and get a list of names of people who would be
>interested in buying an upgraded Blitz.  This would be good ammunition in
>persuading Acid.

Quite right on all your points.  How about one of the guys who has a web page
setting up something where people could "sign" the petition directly on the
site - like those surveys?  This could show a counter, too, letting everybody
know how many people have signed.  Then the rest of us could help out by
posting the site address and information to Aminet, bulletin boards,
