@NODE "Mail.602" "Re: BlitzPPC?"
From: "Julian Kinraid" <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
Subject: Re: BlitzPPC?
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 11:00:12 +1300
	charset="iso-8859-1"

Hi Andreas,

[snip]

>(1) Have   two  diffrent  compilers, one  68k
>    compiler, and ppc code compiler. And then
>    you could  choose what compiler to use in
>    the   Compiler   Options. This  has   the
>    advantage  that when one of the compilers
>    gets  updated, you  only  had to download
>    a smaller file, and if you dont need  the
>    68k code  compiler  you simply  delete it
>    from your HD, and saves space.


This would pose certain difficulties, because a PPC program will still =
need 68k code.  So in the end both compilers would have to talk to each =
other, and then you end up with a solution like (2) or (3)

[option (2) snipped]

>(3) Have a plugin based  compiler system. The
>    compiler would use  plugin  file for both
>    cpus. The  plugin  file  would  hold  all
>    the compiler DATA for  the diffrent cpus.
>    And the main compiler program  would  get
>    the DATA it  need from  the plugin  file.

>This is  the method I  would  like for RWE to
>use, since it has the  most advantages of the
>three  mentioned. A  few  of  them being that
>each  plugin  file would be much smaller then
>the file in method (1), since  it  only holds
>cpu  unique data, and n o compiler  engine it
>self, like method (1) would have to do.


IMHO, to be a good optimising compiler, each plugin would have to be =
sent a pointer to some information which it scans through and returns a =
result to the main program.  I don't see how the main program could just =
use data from a plugin to create decent code.  It sounds messy to =
implement, and I think it would be better to have the plugins do the =
compiling.  This might make the total size bigger, but does that =
*really* matter?  It might make it harder for someone with a A500 and no =
harddrive, but we can't live in the past.  Anyway, you could combine the =
020,030,etc. plugins into just the one 680x0 plugin.

You could (for example) have a 3 pass compiler.  Pass 1 would scan =
through the program and create a convenient representation for Pass 2.  =
Pass 2 would check that the code is correctly written, and create some =
intermediate code.  Pass 3 reads the intermediate code, passes it to the =
plugin/s, and outputs an executable file (or into a slim binary.)

The most important thing though (IMO), is to try and re-write Blitz in a =
high-level language.  Because trying to add all these cool things into =
the Blitz2.s asm code will be a bit of nightmare.  Even adding the =
ability to have three versions of a blitz library (68000, 020+ and PPC) =
will probably require a big change to the code.  A Bachelors degree in =
'Understanding Assembly Written by Mark Sibly would come in handy :)  It =
might be better to write Blitz 3 from scratch.

[snip]

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid




@ENDNODE
