@NODE "Mail.607" "Re: BlitzPPC and more"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 20:10:37 +0100
Subject: Re: BlitzPPC and more

Hi Andreas,

> The "rebirth" that AMOS is about to start, is  also  a  very  important
> thing  to  tell  them  about.  If AMOS gets this face lift before blitz
> basic does, then they wont make  any  money  of  blitz  anymore,  since
> people would swap to amos.

I don't think anyone will be swapping to amos unless it does
become a wonderful updated language with nice clean AmigaOS
and PPC support etc. The C language is becoming easier to
work with as packages are developed. If anyone has seen HiSoftC++
then you'll know how nice the Intergrated Developer Interface is
and how tempting it is to play with it. Yes, C/C++ is the big
temptation for many Blitz experts and the more you understand
Blitz the easier the move is. As the C languages get better
PPC support and the development environments improove, thats
where you'll see Blitz die off unless something serious happens.

> I know that there are much more to bring up, like AHI, RTG etc,

AHI and RTG isn't important. What is important is good open
support for external libraries and devices of today and tomorow.
Theres no point in making AHI part of Blitz if development
of AHI ends and a new sound system takes over. Blitz development
should be limited to the language itself, the syntax, the internal
workings, the compiler code, the Editor (or no editor) and above
all make it as open and as future proof as possible.

I think a blitz committee is a good idea even if it's created
to gather up information and to create some standards. I think
a Web page is a good start. A page that contains all the latest
libs and documentation. Links and example source for every
major shared library/device including mui, cybergraphx, AHI
etc. An official version of the acidlibs file with bugfixes
amended to it! :) Maybe an official amigalibs.res file that
includes not only a fixed/updated version of amigalibs.res
but also the definitions for ahi, mui, cybergfx etc. Maybe the
official BlitzLib numbers could be dealt with here. Bug reports
could be gathered and some fixes could be made available. These
are just a few ideas for he role of a blitz committee.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

