@NODE "Mail.613" "BLITZ PPC"
From: Roger Beausoleil <vision_fx@citenet.net>
Date: Mon, 23 Mar 1998 07:23:28 +0500
Subject: BLITZ PPC

Hi all...

Here's my opinion about the project of a new compiler, Ted editor, and a new
BLITZ PPC version:

a) You're right when you say that we won't be able to use the source of
Blitz... it's copyrighted! And, it's not sure that the owner will put this
source in public domain.

b) Please remenber this... If people code sharewares, freewares and giftwares
to generate GUI source code or any other programs to make BLITZ more easy to
use without to pay royalty... a new compiler should be the same!  This new
compiler will become only a new program to make BLITZ more flexible and useful
for all users. The compiler have only to get an other name like some of you
already make suggestions.  And Phoenix sound good for me!

c) Nobody can stop someone who wants to create something like that if when you
create it, you do not use sources... C is a language, Basic is a language...
Acid did not pay something to use C in its new language called BLITZ... This
should be same for who wants to create a new language with a base of C, or
Basic, or any kind of language...

I wrote all those lines only to say to all of you who are working in this
marvellous project... GO FULL AHEAD! And still remember that... if PixelPro3D
can load and transfert 3D objects in a lot of format, or PPaint and
DeluxePaint can use IFF...  without paying a royalty! You can create a
compiler to make BLITZ like you want it to be!

Roger Beausoleil 



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.614" "Re: Blitz Manual"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 21:12:10 +0500
Subject: Re: Blitz Manual

On 19-Mar-98, Eoghann Irving flashed:
>Hi :)

>>  Sounds like a project that some of us could get rolling.

>Whoa there.  Slow down a little.  Writing a good manual takes some time and
>pre-planning.

  Oh yes, I realize that.  I have written manuals before which is why I
propose to do the actual formatting and assymbly myself.  I have actually
allready done a considerable amount of planning for such a project but
I want input from others who have tried to use the original manuals about
the things they feel would be helpful.

>The problems with the Blitz manuals are precisely because the manual was
>written by an expert in the language.

  No problem there as I am only a mediocre expert in Blitz 2. #B^)>

>                                       A good manual has to do two things,
>serve as a general function reference for the programmer and introduce
>people to the language (and possibly to the theories of programming).

  Very true, and the old one failed on both accounts.  The layout and the
referance system were both clumsy and lacking in lucid and complete examples.
They also were error-ridden and some info was just plain missing.  As far
as introducing neophytes to the language and programing the net result was
to totally confuse people although a few points were fairly well done.


>I agree a new manual is needed.  I also agree that its something that Blitz
>users can help with.  But it has to be approached in an organised fashion.

  Yup, just what I propose to do.

>I'd be a little cautious about doing this by committe though.  Have you
>ever read anything where the wording was chosen by committe?  Its not
>pretty.

  Committees can be very useful if the final disposition is delegated to
one or two competant people. In this case I believe we need collective
expert input from many people, especially as I would like to include
info on third-party additions and utilities as well as the origional
Acid product.  I also wish to use discussion to be sure no useful
information is left out and no miss-information is included.

>Better get an expert explain it in full technical glory then have someone
>with good communication skills translate that into a plain english (or
>whatever language;) explanation. 

  That is precisely where you need someone with enough understanding of
language, human nature and the technical aspects to put it all together
without losing the accuracy of the information.  Manuals written by
language experts tend to be full of miss-interpretations and errors.
  The last Blitz manual actually appeared to have been dictated or
scribbled out by the coders and written and edited by people who knew
nothing about the subject with a missing link in between.  The coders
didn't know enough about language to realise that the final result
wasn't getting the information accross and the editor didn't know enough
about programming to realise that either.

>As Paul Burkey mentioned you then need example code.  The more the better. 
>Its the best way to learn programming.  Even for people like me who really
>aren't too hot at it despite two years at University studying it.

  Well chosen and written example code is doubtless very important.
One other major thing missing from the old manual was simply a clear
explaination of the purpose of each command and its limitations.


  Paul Berkey has kindly offered the e-text of an earlier Blitz manual
to help a starting point.  This will be especially helpful in avoiding
having to re-type certain of the technical info and referances.

>-- 

>Have fun,

  I will. @8^)>

  I do believe this will be enjoyable and useful.


  I hope you don't mind that I decided to post this to the Blitz List
even though you sent me your comments privately.  Your observations
were well thought out and pertainant and I believe many will have
similar questions and benifit from seeing this discussion.


        Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.615" "Blitz Manual"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Wed, 18 Mar 1998 10:39:22 +0500
Subject: Blitz Manual

On 18-Mar-98, Curt Esser flashed:

>Aha, another change they didn't bother to put in the manual!  In fact,
>comparing my old Blitz 1.7 manual to the 2.1 manual, I see they are exactly
>the same!  Except the 1.7 manual had more examples and such...

>Yes, the sad truth for those who complain about the Blitz manual  (that's ALL
>of us, isn't it?) is that the manual was actually better before they
"updated"
>it for 2.1.

>In fact, I think a better manual should go at the top of the list of
requested
>improvements for Blitz.


  Sounds like a project that some of us could get rolling.
I propose that we collectively write a new Blitz manual from the
storehouse of knowledge here in us.  I would be happy to actually do
the writing and formatting.  We could discuss each of the commands and
reach a concensus on what each one does and when and how it works and
should be used.  We could also come up with clear and complete
examples for the useage of each command.
  I further propose that we begin with a core of the most used and
needed commands so that the 'manual' could begin to be used by
neophytes in the Blitz realm right away.  I remember how hard it was
for me just to figure out how to get a picture on the screen in some
of the modes when I first started Blitz 2.
  We could release the text as a free E-book on Aminet and continue
to improve it over time.  We could also offer it to whoever makes the
next upgrade of Blitz Basic as a starting place for their new manual
and/or we could offer to continue developement of it for them either
to help the project or for a share of the profits.
  I have thought for a long time that a better manual was needed and
even for those of us more well versed in B.B. it could be very helpful
to have all of our knowledge pooled in one easily understood and
organised document.

  As I said, I would be happy to make the actual document if those of
you here would be willing to give it a go.  If I get a positive
responce I will begin right away.


     Regards,
               Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)

  P.S.  Sorry for sending this again but I thought after I had
       sent it that I should put it under a different subject so it
       would be noticed more.







@ENDNODE
