@NODE "Mail.618" "Blitz Committee"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 23:05:36 +0100
Subject: Blitz Committee


>AHI and RTG isn't  important.  What  is  important  is  good  open
>support  for  external libraries and devices of today and tomorow.
>Theres no point in making AHI part of Blitz if development of  AHI
>ends and a new sound system takes over.

This is true in more then one way, now that I think about  it,  but
your still both right and wrong. Let me try to explain abit better,
without making it to long. I know for are fact that AHI and RTG  is
very  likely  to be included in the future amigas, since I'm on the
ICOA mailing list, and workgroups has been setup for this (and much
more  is  going  on  behind the scens that cant be disscused at the
moment). The amiga needs to have these kind of  standards,  inorder
to  have  a  real plug and plau system, where all extra hardware is
automaticlly supported, if it's been written using the standard.

What we are talking about here is  three  things.  RTA  (Retargeble
Audio),  RTG  (Retargeble  Graphics)  and HAL (A kind of Retargeble
Hardware system). Once these three systems  has  been  implemented,
there  will  be  no need for special support in any language, since
they will be a new standard. So yes, I think this should be skipped
,  since  the  coding  time  can  be  used  for  much more relevant
problems.

>Blitz development should be limited to the  language  itself,  the
>syntax,  the  internal workings, the compiler code, the Editor (or
>no editor) and above all make it as open and as  future  proof  as
>possible.

Yes, an Open Programming System.

>I think a blitz committee is a good idea even if it's  created  to
>gather  up information and to create some standards. I think a Web
>page is a good start. A page that contains all the latest libs and
>documentation.  Links  and  example  source for every major shared
>library/device including mui, cybergraphx, AHI  etc.  An  official
>version of the acidlibs file with bugfixes amended to it! :) Maybe
>an  official  amigalibs.res  file  that  includes   not   only   a
>fixed/updated  version  of  amigalibs.res but also the definitions
>for ahi, mui, cybergfx etc. Maybe the  official  BlitzLib  numbers
>could  be  dealt with here. Bug reports could be gathered and some
>fixes could be made available. These are just a few ideas  for  he
>role of a blitz committee.

Yes we should start designing a webpage for this committee.  I  can
do  the  html  code,  but  I think we should find a really good gfx
artist that can design the gfx for the page, since we will  need  a
professional looking site, if anyone is going to take us seriously.

I think everyone should write down all the blitz related sites they
know  of,  and/or can find on the net (please try out all the links
before you send them to me). I would like for the person  that  has
the library page on his homepage, to contact me, so we can disscuss
the option of using his material on the committee page, since there
is  no use inventing the wheel twice. Same goes for the rest of you
out there, that has something to offer (you DONT have to  drop  you
own  page  since  that  would  be  stupid,  just share your already
gatherd meterial). Please write down  anything  blitz  related  you
have  or  can  find,  that  you  think  could  be  used on the page
(examples, docs, faq files - Is the author of the Blitz FAQ's still
on the list? if you are, then please contact me, since we could put
up a FAQ section on the site). Well I think you get the idea what I
want  you  to do. Please dont send me any files yet, only send me a
list of the stuff you have, and want to share.

Now to more important things. Who will  be  on  the  board  of  the
committee?  Some  people  must  be  in "charge". Then if some other
blitz user  wants  to  join  the  "team",  they  can  apply  for  a
membership  (Free  of  course,  but  this is a smart way of keeping
track on all the blitz users). Note how ever that when  you  applye
for a "membership" you dont get a place on the board.

Once we have made this work, and have established good  conections,
we  could  send  out  news, and info to the members, when it's been
sent to us. I'm quite sure that RWE would be  intressted  in  this,
and  would gladly work with us, since both part will benifit of it,
since we might be able to convince acid to share  the  source  code
with a group of coders etc.

 ByE!







@ENDNODE
