From: Daniel Allsopp <dallsopp@enterprise.net>
        Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Fri, 06 Mar 1998 17:13:17 +0000
Subject: BitplanesBitmap....this is getting on my tits!!!

Hi,

First off, thanks Paul Burkey for explaining the command as best you could,
I'm probably just thick and can't get it to work.

Paul will know what system I'm using here, 2 bitmaps for double buffering and
2 bitmap windows for the display, and a fifth bitmap for the background (i
think).

    Bitmap 0,320,256,8 : BitmapWindow 0,3,0,0,244,244
    Bitmap 1,320,256,8 : BitmapWindow 1,4,0,0,244,244
    Bitmap 2,320,256,8

This was the system I use, now I'm trying to implement BitplanesBitmap so I
can use shadows etc. SO I put in the bitmap command : 

    Bitmap 5,320,256,1 <--- One plane??

Now I don't know what to use for my BitplanesBitmap command, is it : 

    BitPlanesBitmap db,5,%10000000 <---- in my main loop after displaying my
other bitmaps

or

    BitPlanesBitmap 2,5,%10000000 <---- in my main loop after displaying my
other bitmaps

When I blit my 2 colour shape, should I blit it to bitmap 5 or db??

-- 
Cheers,
 Daniel



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.627" "Re: BitplanesBitmap....this is getting on my tits!!!"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 06 Mar 1998 18:53:41 +0100
Subject: Re: BitplanesBitmap....this is getting on my tits!!!

Hi,
 
> This was the system I use, now I'm trying to implement BitplanesBitmap so I
> can use shadows etc. SO I put in the bitmap command : 
> 
> Bitmap 5,320,256,1 <--- One plane??

NO! don't go making any 1 plane bitmaps. Thats what BitPlanesBitmap
is for.

> Now I don't know what to use for my BitplanesBitmap command, is it : 
> 
> BitPlanesBitmap db,5,%10000000 <---- in my main loop after displaying my
> other bitmaps

No!, BitPlanesBitmap is used at the start of your code only. It
will create a 1 plane bitmap for you to use for the rest of your
game.

As you may know, each bitmap you create uses an internal .bitmap
structure. In the bitmap structure it will have plane pointers.
An 8 plane bitmap will have 8 planes so it'll have 8 pointers to
8 chunks of memory where the actual planes are. When you display
this bitmap on a screen the Copper will merge these bitplanes
together to create what we see as 256 colour display even though
the bitmap is really 8 single 1bit "sheets" we call planes.

Now this bit of background info may help when I get to the next
bit. When you use BitPlanesBitmap 1,5,%10000000 it will create
a new bitmap (bitmap 5) and it will be created as a 1 plane
bitmap so it'll only need 1 chunk of memory for it's plane. Now
comes the important bit. Instead of reserving an area of memory
to hold this plane it actually re-uses the memory that is already
used by Bitmap 1. So any rendering you do to bitmap 5 will really
be rendering to the selected planes of bitmap 1. 

So you must first create your main bitmaps.
Then create a bitplanebitmap for each of these.
Now render your normal graphics to the 8 plane bitmap.
Now render to your bitplanesbitmap and the results will be instant. 

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
