@NODE "Mail.632" "Bitmap Positioning"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby@inetnebr.com>
Date: Mon, 09 Mar 1998 11:10:31 +0500
Subject: Bitmap Positioning

  I want to create a full overscan screen so there are no
visible borders, making the moniter appear like a window
with its own physical frame as the borders.  I need to do
this in low-res, hi-res and hi-res laced.  I am especially
interested in how to have the screen extend clear to the
left side of the moniter picture tube, displaying graphics
all the way there as I have been unable to achieve that.

  I also need to know how to show a bitmap with part of it
extending off the left side of the screen (in other words
in a negative direction).

  Both of these things I had no problem with doing in
Blitz 1 (the original Blitz Basic) but I cannot find any
way to accomplish them in Blitz 2.  Can anyone help me?

                Thanks,

                 Donovan Reeve (bubby@inetnebr.com)

         



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.633" "Re: Binaries"
Date: Wed, 25 Mar 1998 18:01:27 +0000
From: Adam Lounds <adaml@tcp.net.uk>
Subject: Re: Binaries

On Wed, Mar 25, 1998 at 12:43:37PM +0500, Donovan Reeve said:
> On 22-Mar-98, BootBlock of Carnage flashed:
> 
> >>>some people like me don't mind getting the occassional binary file 
> >>>especially when it's relevent to the list subject in this case blitz
> 
> >>I really don't mind getting binaries in my emailbox.  I have a 28.8k modem,
> >>getting 15k from a POP server does not take up too much of my time.
> 
> >Nope, I don't mind either. The whole point is to help each other out and
> share
> >code, so anyone feel free to email me those binaries with that luverly Blitz
> >type code in `em!
> 
>   I not only don't mind, I appreciate it!  It's great to have helpful stuff
> show up in my e-mail.  It sure beats all the junk mail and gripes.
>   Several programs which have showed up as an answer to somebody else have
> given me new ideas and/or solved problems for me.

Yes, but ASCII code would be better where appropriate. Not only
would it enable us to read/help/reply quicker, but it would
also help those people who download the monthly "digests" of the
list from Aminet. Or sites where someone pulls out the useful source
from the list and posts it on the web for future reference.

Libraries etc - Aminet. OK, it's down, but for normal use it's the best 
place to put stuff.

