@NODE "Mail.640" "Re: Basic Cross Compilers"
	Sun, 22 Mar 1998 19:17:16 +0100 (MET)
Date: Sun, 22 Mar 1998 19:15:57 +0100 (MET)
From: Claus Herrmann <cyclone@rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>
Subject: Re: Basic Cross Compilers 
ReSent-Date: Sun, 22 Mar 1998 19:17:10 +0100 (MET)
ReSent-From: Claus Herrmann <cyclone@rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>
ReSent-To: blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
ReSent-Message-ID: <Pine.SOL.3.91.980322191710.9658B@ultra10.rbg.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de>

On 22 Mar 1998, Evan Tuer wrote:

> Hi there, I am thinking of writing a simple Basic compiler (based on the
> Blitz command set, and written in Blitz) for a couple of Motorola chips
> that I have to do an /awful/ lot of assembler programing for.
>   What I want to know is, how difficult is it likely to be - I have no idea
> how compilers work, are there any conventions or examples I should know
> about?
> 
> Given the recent upheaveals, is there any chance that the blitz source
> itself  might become available, so I could get CLUEZ from it?
> 
> 
> Anyway. an example:
> 
> PORTA=$1000
> 
> if a<10
>  poke.b PORTA,$00
> else
>  poke.b PORTA,$01
> endif
> 
> would be translated to:
> 
> PORTA   equ $1000
> 
>         org     PROG
>         ldaa    a
>         cmpa    #10
>         bhi     else
>         clr     PORTA
> else    ldaa    #$01
>         staa    PORTA
> 
>         org     DATA
> a       rmb
> 
> 
> And then that could be assembled normally.
> 
> 
> But how do you handle different variable lengths and things like that?
> 
> I know that there are C compilers made for every processor under the sun,
> but I LIKE basic :)
> 
> 

there are two ways.. setting the string lenght to a maximum of 255 chars 
and if this exceeds then there is a new chuk with 255 chars.. and so on 
(in a sorrt fo list). or do it like C ask for a null terminated string 
("hello",0). the 0 gives the end of the string !

variables for digits you use standard forms as long, short, word and so 
on !





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.641" "Basic Cross Compilers"
Date: 22 Mar 98 17:18:37 +0500
From: "Evan Tuer" <et_@_enterprise_._net>
Subject: Basic Cross Compilers 

Hi there, I am thinking of writing a simple Basic compiler (based on the
Blitz command set, and written in Blitz) for a couple of Motorola chips
that I have to do an /awful/ lot of assembler programing for.
  What I want to know is, how difficult is it likely to be - I have no idea
how compilers work, are there any conventions or examples I should know
about?

Given the recent upheaveals, is there any chance that the blitz source
itself  might become available, so I could get CLUEZ from it?


Anyway. an example:

PORTA=$1000

if a<10
 poke.b PORTA,$00
else
 poke.b PORTA,$01
endif

would be translated to:

PORTA   equ $1000

        org     PROG
        ldaa    a
        cmpa    #10
        bhi     else
        clr     PORTA
else    ldaa    #$01
        staa    PORTA

        org     DATA
a       rmb


And then that could be assembled normally.


But how do you handle different variable lengths and things like that?

I know that there are C compilers made for every processor under the sun,
but I LIKE basic :)



@ENDNODE
