@NODE "Mail.662" "Am*s news"
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 13:48:28 +0100
From: Bob Stifter <stifter@mira.cz>
Subject: Am*s news

I have read the news about AM*S and it seems the users
have gathered and they actively create an update for Am*s.

So Am*s is going to support AGA and graphics cards etc. I.e. Amo*s is going
to bee like Blitz if not superior to Blitz. They also want PPC support etc.
Now they can use the .FD files like Blitz users FD Convert.

Seems like an update to Blitz is due. Any comment?
-------------------------------------

StB

http://www.amiga.org/news/1998/0223-mushroompd.html
http://www.amiga.org/news/1998/0305-amospro.html

--- cut ---

The source for AMOS + AMOSPro (including the compiler) have now been
released to a small team of
     developers, who wish to put this once ever-popular language back on
top of them all, by giving it a major
     overhaul.

     The major changes which will be added, will be AGA and graphics card
support for all AMOS modes,
     including its editor, yet still be able to provide the programmer with
complete control over its graphics
     system.

     Over the past couple of months, I have had a developers form on my
webpages
     (http://www.mushy-pd.demon.co.uk) asking existing users/old users what
they would like to see in a new
     version, and how they compared AMOS to other languages and why. Some
of the responses have been
     very interesting, and have been placed on the list to be included in
the near future.

     Some of the other features placed on the list include full AHI
soundcard support, GIF, JPG, PNG and
     other datatype access/creating, structured variables, multiple-code
platform (will allow to compile for a
     specific machine format, including PPC), PPC support, the list is
endless.

--- cut ---



Bob Stifter --===***===-- TEAM AMIGA *
tel.0327/515129 daily -=- A1200T 030 *
http://www.mira.cz/~stifter/HemP.htm *


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.663" "Re: Am*s news"
Date: 17 Mar 98 15:24:41 +0100
From: "Jonas Thorell" <jonasth@bahnhof.se>
Subject: Re: Am*s news
X-System: Amiga 1200/030@50 Mhz, 34 Meg, 1.5 Gig HD, 28k8
X-Software: Aweb, Miami, Thor
X-Misc-info: Who's reading this??

Bob Stifter (stifter@mira.cz) wrote:

>I have read the news about AM*S and it seems the users
>have gathered and they actively create an update for Am*s.

>So Am*s is going to support AGA and graphics cards etc. I.e. Amo*s is going
>to bee like Blitz if not superior to Blitz. They also want PPC support etc.
>Now they can use the .FD files like Blitz users FD Convert.

>Seems like an update to Blitz is due. Any comment?

Well, this is from one that actually uses both AMOS and Blitz for different purposes.
They're different, but still have some features and drawbacks in common. The main
difference is that Blitz have some stuff AMOS does not, like built-in support
for intuition and AGA. For AMOS you need an extension to do that (an extension is much
like the .obj files in Blitz). 

An ECS game written in BlitzMode isn't that much different from a game in AMOS
if the coders knew what they were doing. Both is incompatible to graphiccards
for example. The speed isn't necessarily the difference either (though it is
easier to get speed out of Blitz). Add some of the extensions that's available
to AMOS and it's easy to get really good results out of it. I have a demo here
that's written with some help of those extensions and it's playing fasttracker
modules, synced with the display and scrolling text and what have you. It
doesn't come close to what assembler-demomakers can accomplish but it's solid
work anyway.

AMOS great benefit over Blitz is that it's far easier to come to grips with. But
that update to AMOS is far off. They are just getting started but they do have
the original source which is likely to make things easier (depending on how
the code looks like...). I believe that if those coders can pull this through
(and considering what one of them has accomplished before, I have little
doubt they will) and nothing happens on the Blitzfront, AMOS is going to be
the better one. 

I don't know what will happen with Blitz but something needs to be done if it
isn't going to be superceeded by AMOS Pro V3 when that gets released.

---
Look at the shoes you're filling, look at the blood we're spilling
Look at the world we're killing, the way we've always done before
Look at the doubt we've wallowed, look at the leaders we've followed
Look at the lies we've swallowed and I don't wanna hear no more
---
Acting on a good idea is better than just having a good idea.



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.664" "Re: Am*s news"
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 15:15:59 +0100
Subject: Re: Am*s news

Hi Bob,

> I have read the news about AM*S and it seems the users
> have gathered and they actively create an update for Am*s.
> So Am*s is going to support AGA and graphics cards etc. I.e. Amo*s is going
> to bee like Blitz if not superior to Blitz. They also want PPC support etc.
> Now they can use the .FD files like Blitz users FD Convert.
> Seems like an update to Blitz is due. Any comment?

Yes, this is old news. They got the source code for amos a couple
of months ago. Apparently it's very messy (no shock there) and it
contains very little documentation (in french!).

The .fd lib system was added a while ago and they've had limited
AGA and fairly good CyberGraphX support for ages now. I was going
to create a CyberGraphX version of one of my amos games 'Sneech'
a while ago but the amos Editor is still stuck in 'hardware bashing'
mode so I can't run the editor on my system any more. The changes
they've made to the language already are good and the guys working
on the updates are very dedicated and fast workers. It would be nice
if Blitz could be in a similar situation where the users get full
control over what is done to bring it uptodate.

I think amos and blitz are in a very different situation. amos is
extremely outdated and needs a lot of work. Blitz is just a bit
outdated and needs some regular maintainance.

Things will change but who knows which way things will go? I hope
development will go well for both languages.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk

