@NODE "Mail.678" "Re: AGARGB"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 17:09:56 -0600
Subject: Re: AGARGB

On 26-Mar-98, Frank Otto wrote:
>Hi,

>I want to change some colours of an AGA-picture (>5 bitplanes).
>Therefor I use "AGARGB" but the compiler says that the colours must
>be under 32. It's the same when using "RGB".

>Is this another error in Blitz? AGARGB and RGB seem to be the same
>commands (excepting that AGARGB can change the palette from 0-255).

>How can I change AGA colours?

I am working on a program with 255 colour screen.  I just tried the AGARGB 
command to set register #200, and it worked fine.  There may be an error in
your screen opening, as this command alters the current screen's palette, so
it is limited to the number of colours on your screen.  So check to see if
your screen is greater than 32 colours depth.

If you are trying to alter colours in a palette object, use the AGAPalRGB
commands instead.



>Regards,
>--
>Frank



-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.679" "AGARGB"
X-Gateway: ZCONNECT UE dame.dame.de [PolyNet zTOr V4.93 (11.3.1996) Serie: "spy"]
X-ZC-VIA: 19980326000000W+1@dame.de
Subject: AGARGB
Date: Wed, 26 Mar 98 12:29:46 GMT
From: Robocop@dame.de (Frank Otto)
Bcc:

Hi,

I want to change some colours of an AGA-picture (>5 bitplanes).
Therefor I use "AGARGB" but the compiler says that the colours must
be under 32. It's the same when using "RGB".

Is this another error in Blitz? AGARGB and RGB seem to be the same
commands (excepting that AGARGB can change the palette from 0-255).

How can I change AGA colours?



Regards,
--
Frank




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.680" "Re: AGARGB"
From: Paul Burkey <paul@sneech.demon.co.uk>
Date: Fri, 27 Mar 1998 03:13:46 +0000
Subject: Re: AGARGB

Hi Frank,

> I want to change some colours of an AGA-picture (>5 bitplanes).
> Therefor I use "AGARGB" but the compiler says that the colours must
> be under 32. It's the same when using "RGB".

AGARGB seems to work fine with 256 colours. How many colours
does your palette/screen have?

