@NODE "Mail.700" "Re:  Keyboard input"
From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
Date: Sat, 14 Mar 1998 15:41:52 +0100
Subject: Re:  Keyboard input


 Hello,

We at Vivid Imagination has the solution to all your
keyboard  input problems. I  have   ripped   out   a 
interrrupt based mouse  and key press  trapper  from
one of our programs. Just put it  somewhere  at  the
begining of your program, and it is ready to use.

To  check  if  a mouse  button has been pressed, you
simply check what value is stored in the variabel Mb
(1=Left, 2=Right, 3=Both).

To check  if  a  key has  been  pressed, you  simply
check what value is stored in the  variabel  Key. It
stores the hexadecimal value  of the  key  that  has
been press (eg ESC = $45).

Feel free to use it in your own programs. 

SetInt 3
   MOVEQ   #0,d0
   MOVE.b  $BFEC01,d0
   NOT.b   d0
   ROR.b   #1,d0
   PutReg  d0,Key.w
   MOVEQ   #0,d0
   BTST.b  #6,$BFE001
   BNE     l1
   MOVEQ   #1,d0
l1:BTST.b  #2,$DFF016
   BNE     l2
   BSET    #1,d0
l2:PutReg  d0,Mb.b
End SetInt

ByE!





 





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail.701" "Re:  Keyboard input"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 13 Mar 1998 17:30:00 -0600
Subject: Re:  Keyboard input

Hi,

On 12-Mar-98, Donovan Reeve wrote:


>  The problem with edit$ is that I am using the keyboard as a control
>consel in many of my games.  The player presses a key and gets the
>desired reaction from the program.  I don't want them to have to press
>return afterwards because that would take away much of the conveniance
>and fluidity as well as confusing the player and slowing down their
>reaction time.
>  I will try your invisible window idea however I am worried about the
>additional ram that will take and won't that only work in Amiga Mode?
>  I need speed and I need to conserve ram as all of my games press the
>Amiga to its limits.

Yes, you can only have a window in Amiga mode.

For Blitz mode, use:

"Blitzkeys On" to allow reading the keyboard.

Then you can use Inkey$ or RawStatus to check for key-presses.


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



